<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UNCTAD, Israel Sign MOU to Promote Enterprises </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, June 17 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations Conference on
Trade and Development (UNCTAD) and the Israeli government signed a
memorandum of understanding (MOU) here Tuesday to help developing
countries and economies-in-transition in their national and
regional development efforts.
</P>
<P>
Pledging to combine their professional and operational
resources, UNCTAD and the Center for International Cooperation
(MASHAV) of the Ministry of Foreign Affairs of Israel will
undertake joint research and training in the fields of investment,
science and technology, and enterprise development for the benefit
of developing countries.
</P>
<P>
At the signing ceremony, UNCTAD Secretary-General Rubens
Ricupero said that Israel had undertaken excellent work, not only
through official government policies, but also with local
communities, in active investment promotion and in support of the
development of small and medium-sized enterprises (SMEs).
</P>
<P>
Israel's experience in identifying new enterprises and in
targeting investment promotion would be extremely valuable,
Ricupero said.
</P>
<P>
MASHAV, created 40 years ago, has set up some 150 training
programs, for example, in crop diversification, irrigation
savings, combating desertification and entrepreneurship.
</P>
<P>
Last year, over 4,000 professionals attended MASHAV training
courses in Israel.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
