<DOCNO> XIE19980618.0002 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> France Views Milosevic's Commitment as Insufficient </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, June 17 (Xinhua) -- France on Wednesday said the
promises made by Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic to resolve
the Kosovo crisis were insufficient.
</P>
<P>
"The commitments made by President Milosevic in the wake of his
meeting with (Russian) President Yeltsin only answer in an
incomplete manner the requests formulated by the ministers of the
Contact Group (on former Yugoslavia)," said French Foreign
Ministry spokesman Yves Doutriaux.
</P>
<P>
He said that Milosevic's refusal to withdraw federal troops
from Kosovo, as requested by the United States, France, Britain,
Germany, Italy and Russia, showed that he failed to yield to a
principal demand by the Contact Group.
</P>
<P>
"His declarations on the army and the formulation of his
communique linking the withdrawal of security forces to the end of
terrorist actions (by the Albanians) show that on this central
aspect the progress made remains insufficient," he said.
</P>
<P>
If an atmosphere of confidence was not established between the
Serbs and the Albanians, it would be difficult for the two sides
to resume talks, he said.
</P>
<P>
"We will rapidly consult with our partners of the Contact Group
to evaluate the situation in Kosovo and the stand to be maintained
toward the Yugoslav authorities," he said.
</P>
<P>
He also said that French Prime Minister Lionel Jospin would
discuss with U.S. President Bill Clinton the situation in Kosovo
when they meet on Thursday in Washington. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980618.0003 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Singapore Banks Suggested to Increase Transparency </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, June 17 (Xinhua) -- Singapore's Committee on Banking
Disclosure released a report Wednesday recommending wide-ranging
changes for banks to increase their transparency.
</P>
<P>
The committee attached high importance in its report to
enhancing disclosure standards and reforming current practice,
saying that the "Asian crisis highlights the need for greater
transparency and information disclosure to maintain confidence in
the banking system."
</P>
<P>
The committee was set up by the Financial Sector Review Group
chaired by Deputy Prime Minister Lee Hsien Loong and was assigned
to review and evaluate disclosure standards and practice in
developed and other Asia-Pacific countries and then made
suggestions on changes.
</P>
<P>
The committee, chaired by Elizabeth Sam, Deputy President of
the Overseas-Chinese Banking Corp., recommended disclosures in
eight areas.
</P>
<P>
On top above all, the committee called for a stop in the
current practice of maintaining hidden reserves and recommended
that Singapore banks disclose the market value of investment.
</P>
<P>
On changes in profit and loss account, the committee said banks
should provide details of other principal sources of income like
profit from securities trading and gains on disposal of fixed
assets.
</P>
<P>
Banks should also disclose specific provisions for loan losses
and general provisions, it said.
</P>
<P>
The team proposed to the government encouraging the build-up of
bank reserves through tax incentives, like making loan loss
provisions fully tax deductible.
</P>
<P>
The committee also recommended changing the current practice of
provisioning on a line-by-line basis for dealing with securities
to provisioning on the basis of the entire portfolio.
</P>
<P>
But it would be status quo for the current practice of
valuation for dealing securities, it noted.
</P>
<P>
On off-balance sheet items, the team asked for a disclosure of
all contingent liabilities, commitments and financial derivatives.
</P>
<P>
But the committee viewed suggestions of quarterly results
announcement as inappropriate for Singapore banks and recommended
the continuation of the current practice of half-yearly
announcement.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
