<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Announces Actions to Bolster Yen </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 17 (Xinhua) -- The United States intervened in
currency markets on Wednesday, selling dollars in a bid to bolster
the falling Japanese yen which dropped to an eight-year low
against the greenback.
</P>
<P>
This is the first time that the Clinton administration has ever
sold dollars in an effort to back another currency.
</P>
<P>
The administration confirmed the dollar sales in a simple
statement. "The New York Federal Reserve Bank is operating in the
exchange markets on behalf of the U.S. monetary authorities," a
spokesman from the Treasury Department said.
</P>
<P>
In another statement Wednesday, Robert E. Rubin, U.S. treasury
secretary, expressed his welcome for the Japanese government's
plans to "restore the health of the Japanese financial system and
to strengthen domestic demand."
</P>
<P>
"Japan has the financial resources and the capacity to deal
with the challenges it faces. Asia and the international community
as a whole have a large stake in Japan's success," Rubin noted.
</P>
<P>
He added, "the U.S. monetary authorities operated in the
exchange market this morning in cooperation with the monetary
authorities of Japan. We are prepared to continue to cooperate in
the exchange markets, as appropriate." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
