<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Insulin Inhalers Treat Diabetics </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 17 (Xinhua) -- Scientists said diabetics may
soon be able to treat themselves through an inhaler rather than
through a needle.
</P>
<P>
Scientists from University of Miami presented their findings
Tuesday in Chicago at the American Diabetes Association's 58th
Annual Meeting.
</P>
<P>
They said it will be more simple and popular for the
diabetics. A national study of 121 diabetics showed it is at
least as effective as injected insulin in controlling the
symptoms of diabetes.
</P>
<P>
A final trial of the inhaled insulin is set for this fall,
and will go into commercial use after the approvement by the U.S.
Food and Drug Administration.
</P>
<P>
Insulin-dependent diabetics must get injections several times
daily and their medicine must be kept cold. Thirty-thousand
Americans are diagnosed each year with insulin-dependent diabetes.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
