<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe's Farmers Told to Grow Less Tobacco </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, June 17 (Xinhua) -- The Zimbabwe Tobacco Association
(ZTA) Wednesday advised local tobacco growers to reduce their
plantings by 10 to 15 percent this year to avoid unnecessary
expenditures.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the 38th ZTA annual congress, out-going President
Robert Webb said Simbabwe's tried and tested auction system was
under threat despite extensive consultations with manufacturers
and merchants both here and abroad, the Zimbabwe News Agency
reported.
</P>
<P>
''My plea is that you do not over extend yourself by growing
more tobacco than you can handle efficiently,'' he said, adding,
''consequently, we recommend that platings be reduced by 10 to 15
percent from last year which should result in a crop to satisfy
all stake-holders.''
</P>
<P>
He said Zimbabwe's tobacco industry has not done very well
lately due to a number of factors including high import duties,
surcharges, sales tax, the five percent levies and a slump in
prices this marketing season.
</P>
<P>
''United States litigation is adversely affecting us in
Zimbabwe, the buying pattern has changed, we are becoming
uncompetitive due to unnecessary taxes and levies and our
viability is perched on a knife edge,'' Webb said.
</P>
<P>
The tumble in the Southeast Asian economies, leading to delays
and cancellation of tobacco orders had also impacted badly on the
tobacco industry, the country's biggest foreign currency earner.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
