<DOCNO> XIE19980618.0012 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cohen Says U.S. Force to Remain Near Kosovo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 17 (Xinhua) -- The United States will keep
warships and jets near Kosovo in case the North Atlantic Treaty
Organization (NATO) decides additional military action is needed,
U.S. Defense Secretary William Cohen said on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
"I believe the forces will remain in the region and will be
prepared to follow through with any military action, should any
ever be called for and agreed to," Cohen was quoted as saying by
the Associated Press.
</P>
<P>
Cohen made the remarks at the end of a tour of Europe marked
throughout by the crisis over Yugoslav government attacks in the
restive Kosovo province.
</P>
<P>
Speaking with reporters on his aircraft returning to
Washington, Cohen said a NATO decision to consider the use of
force could come speedily.
</P>
<P>
While NATO members may be divided about the legal basis under
international law for taking military action, such a debate will
not go on indefinitely, Cohen warned.
</P>
<P>
"If there is a continuation of the killing, I think there will
be a very strong tendency to reach a consensus quickly, rather
than engaging in an endless debate," Cohen added.
</P>
<P>
The secretary said that there's the fear the conflict in Kosovo
would spread much faster and further than Bosnia and therefore
requires more immediate attention.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
