<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 1530 GMT, June 17 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO -- Japanese Prime Minister Ryutaro Hashimoto said
Wednesday he and U.S. President Bill Clinton had agreed to
cooperate in stabilizing foreign exchange rates.
</P>
<P>
The two leaders reached the agreement during telephone talks
after the dollar hit an eight-year high earlier this week against
the lackluster Japanese currency.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. dollar hit an eight-year high of the 146.75 yen, the
highest level since August 1990, earlier this week in Tokyo on the
weakness of the Japanese economy. (Japan-US-Yen)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
ISLAMABAD -- Pakistani Foreign Minister Gohar Ayub Khan said
here Wednesday that Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif and his Indian
counterpart will "hopefully" hold a formal meeting at the
forthcoming SAARC summit next month.
</P>
<P>
"We would have a formal meeting with the Indian prime minister
in Colombo next month and hopefully the two prime ministers will
meet there," Gohar said in an interview with Xinhua Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The 10th summit meeting of the seven-nation South Asian
Association for Regional Cooperation (SAARC) is to take place in
Colombo, capital of Sri Lanka. (Pakistan-India)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
MOSCOW -- Six Russian Kosmos satellites launched on Tuesday
reached the projected orbit and are functioning properly, the
Russian Strategic Rocket Force stated on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
But the Interfax news agency quoted another military source as
saying that the first and second stages of the Tsiklon-3 launcher
fired as required, but the booster's second pulse was mistimed.
</P>
<P>
Instead of a circular orbit at an altitude of 1,400 kilometers,
the satellites are flying in an elliptical one with an apogee of
1,900 kilometers and a perigee of 1,300 kilometers, the source
said. (Russia-Satellites)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- Amid reports that some progress has been made
over further Israeli pullback from the West Bank, Israeli inner
cabinet met Wednesday to discuss the issue, but no result was
yielded.
</P>
<P>
Israel Radio reported that the members of the inner cabinet,
namely, Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu, Defense Minister
Yitzhak Mordechai, National Infrastructure Minister Ariel Sharon
and Minister of Industry and Trade Natan Sharansky, will meet
again in the next few days.
</P>
<P>
The meeting was held after Netanyahu confirmed Tuesday night
that there has been progress in the Israeli-U.S. contacts over the
redeployment. Speaking on Israeli television, the prime minister
said a decision on the scope of the second pullback has not been
made, but he believes that an agreement could be reached soon.
(Israel-Redeployment)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
ISLAMABAD -- Pakistani Foreign Minister Gohar Ayub Khan said
here Wednesday that Pakistan has invited representatives from
Afghanistan's Taliban militia and their rival Northern Alliance
to work out formulas to press forward their deadlocked peace
talks.
</P>
<P>
"We have invited one representative from each side to meet here
 to decide on some sort of formula for their possible talks in the
 future," Gohar told Xinhua.
</P>
<P>
During his visit to Afghanistan early this month, Pakistani
State Minister for Foreign Affairs Siddique Khan Kanju conveyed
this proposal to the leadership of both the Taliban and the
Northern Alliance, Gohar said. (Pakistan-Afghanistan-Talks)
</P>
