<DOCNO> XIE19980618.0020 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-17 16:31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cyprus Welcomes EU Conclusion Relating to </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, June 17 (Xinhua) -- Cyprus Wednesday welcomed the fact
that the European Union (EU) did not attempt to block the island's
entry into the organization as threatened by France.
</P>
<P>
Commending on the just-concluded EU summit held in Cardiff,
Britain, Government spokesman Christos Stylianides said "the EU
conclusions relating to Cyprus are positive in that they reaffirm
once more that Cyprus' accession course will proceed unhindered
without any pre-conditions."
</P>
<P>
The EU summit stressed that "each of these candidates (for EU
membership) will be judged on the basis of the same criteria."
</P>
<P>
Last week, a French president spokeswoman noted that it would
be difficult for a divided Cyprus to join the EU, hinting that
France may ask for a suspension of accession negotiations with
Cyprus during the June 15-16 summit.
</P>
<P>
And French President Jacques Chirac also said at the summit
that Cyprus should be considered as a special case in the entry
talks.
</P>
<P>
Expressing surprise at the remarks, Stylianides said "Cyprus is
not a special case at all, it remains in the same group of
candidate countries and proceeds with its accession course without
any problem."
</P>
<P>
He said it was "wrong" for France to have adopted this approach.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus started accession talks with the EU in March.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has been divided into Turkish Cypriot-controlled north
and Greek Cypriot-dominated south since 1974 when Turkey landed
its troops and took over the northern third of the island in the
wake of a pro-Athens coup.
</P>
<P>
Turkish Cypriots unilaterally declared a "Turkish Republic of
Northern Cyprus" in 1983, which is recognized only by Turkey.
</P>
<P>
But Turkish Cypriots walked out of talks last summer to protest
against the EU's decision to begin accession talks with Cyprus --
not their strong supporter Turkey. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
