<BODY>
<HEADLINE> PNA Criticizes Israeli Call for Egyptian </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, June 17 (Xinhua) -- A senior Palestinian official has
refuted the Israeli call on Egypt to pressure the Palestinians to
make further compromise on Israeli troop redeployment in the West
Bank.
</P>
<P>
Mohamed Sobeih, permanent delegate of the Palestinian National
Authority (PNA) to the Arab League based in Cairo, told reporters
Wednesday that Egypt would not intervene in the decision-making
process of the PNA on such crucial matters.
</P>
<P>
"The Egyptian leadership is very keen that the Palestinian
leadership takes its own independent decisions and is keen to
realize a just, durable and overall peace in the region on the
basis of the resolutions of international legitimacy," Sobeih said.
</P>
<P>
Sobeih, also secretary general of the Palestinian National
Council, was commenting on a statement by Israeli Deputy Prime
Minister and Minister of Tourism Moshe Katsav, who said that
Israel has asked Cairo to persuade the PNA to accept a 10 percent
pullback in the next Israeli troop redeployment.
</P>
<P>
Israel has so far refused to endorse the U.S. proposal for a
13.1 percent Israeli withdrawal, although the PNA has
accepted. The PNA has ruled out any further compromise on the 13
percent pullback plan, saying it had already made a big concession
on its original demand for a 30 percent withdrawal.
</P>
<P>
"Egypt will never accept this," Sobeih said. "Egypt has not, at
any stage, exercised any pressure on the Palestinians to influence
their decisions."
</P>
<P>
"The entire world highly appreciates the Egyptian leadership's
wisdom, far-sightedness and its keenness to work according to
international law and Israel should be aware of this," he said.
</P>
<P>
Egypt, the first Arab country to make peace with Israel, is a
strong advocate of the Palestinian cause. PNA President Yasser
Arafat is a frequent visitor here to coordinate stances with
Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak on the PNA's dealing with the
Israeli government. 
</P>
</TEXT>
