<DOCNO> XIE19980618.0025 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cyprus Protests Turkish Warships' Visit to </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, June 17 (Xinhua) -- Cyprus Wednesday launched a strong
protest against the visit by five Turkish naval warships to
Turkish Cypriot-controlled northern part of the island, describing
it as an "illegal action."
</P>
<P>
Government spokesman Christos Stylianides told reporters that
the Cypriot government condemns the move and will make relevant
representations.
</P>
<P>
Two Turkish submarines, a destroyer and a frigate docked in the
Turkish-controlled eastern port of Famagusta early Wednesday and
another warship at the northern port of Kyrenia.
</P>
<P>
The warships, part of an announced Turkish naval exercise, came
a day after four Greek F-16 fighters and a C-130 military
transport plane landed at a newly-completed air base near the
western coastal town of Paphos in the Greek Cypriot-dominated
south.
</P>
<P>
Greek aircraft's arrival, the first since the base was
completed in January, has drawn strong protest from Turkey.
</P>
<P>
Turkish Defense Ministry said "the move by Greek warplanes to
begin to use the Paphos military air base is a very worrying and
provocative development, aimed at damaging peace and stability on
the island."
</P>
<P>
It warned that, as a guarantor power, it will take all
necessary measures to stop development.
</P>
<P>
Turkey, Greece and Britain were guarantors of Cyprus'
independence under the 1960 Treaty of establishment of the Cyprus
Republic.
</P>
<P>
However, Stylianides Wednesday refuted that "it is grotesque
that a guarantor country which violated the unity of the Cyprus
state has been an occupation force since 1974 to lecture Cyprus on
sovereign rights and defense agreements which are based on
international law."
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has remained divided since 1974 when Turkey landed its
troops and took over the northern third of the island in the wake
of a pro-Athens coup.
</P>
<P>
Turkey has kept 35,000-strong armed forces in northern Cyprus
with the claimed aim to protect Turkish Cypriots, who unilaterally
declared a "Turkish Republic of Northern Cyprus."
</P>
<P>
The breakaway republic is recognized only by Turkey.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus government and its strong supporter Greece signed a
joint defense pact in November 1993, under which Greece will
provide military assistance if Cyprus is attacked. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
