<HEADLINE> Netanyahu Condemns Killing of Palestinian Farmer </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, June 17 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin
Netanyahu Wednesday strongly condemned the killing of a
Palestinian farmer near the West Bank city of Hebron, calling it a
"hideous crime."
</P>
<P>
In an interview with Israel Radio, Netanyahu said that the
killing was not acceptable and he would take actions against such
violence. The perpetrators will be brought to court within the
full range of the law, he added.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinian farmer, Abdel Majid Turki, was beaten to death
on Tuesday when he was attacked by several Jewish settlers with a
wooden bat near the Jewish settlement of Beit Hagai, south of
Hebron.
</P>
<P>
Three Jewish settlers, two of them minors, have been arrested
suspected of being involved in the killing. One of the suspects
said that they beat Turki just for "playing a prank."
</P>
<P>
The police have not given a motive.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Ahmed Abdel Rahman, the cabinet secretary of the
Palestinian National Authority, said Wednesday in Gaza that the
killing was a crime against Palestinian people.
</P>
<P>
He noted that the murder proved that peace could not be
achieved with the existence of the Jewish settlements on the
occupied territories.
</P>
<P>
The attack happened in the sensitive Hebron area, where the
Jewish settlers have engaged in frequent clashes with Palestinian
residents in recent years. In the bloodiest case in 1994, a Jewish
settler shot and killed 29 Muslim worshippers in a Hebron mosque.
</P>
</TEXT>
