<HEADLINE> Iran Welcomes Diplomatic Efforts on Kosovo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, June 17 (Xinhua) -- Iran stated on Wednesday that it
welcomes the recent international diplomatic efforts to resolve
the Kosovo crisis, calling for a peaceful solution to it.
</P>
<P>
"Sensitivity of the world community and a general conviction
on part of the Balkan states to put an end to the crisis can pave
the way for return of calm to the region," the Foreign Ministry
spokesman Mahmoud Mohammadi was quoted by the official news
agency IRNA as saying.
</P>
<P>
Mohammadi made the remark after the Yugoslav President
Slobodan Milosevic agreed on Tuesday to accept the West's main
demands for a peaceful solution to the Kosovo conflict.
</P>
<P>
Following talks with Russian President Boris Yeltsin, Milosevic
promised to stop actions against civilians in Kosovo and resume
talks with Kosovo Albanians, who fought for autonomy.
</P>
<P>
However, Milosevic insisted that there is no reason for the
pullout from Kosovo of the Yugoslav federal army as demanded by a
number of countries.
</P>
<P>
The Iranian Foreign Ministry spokesman voiced Tehran's concern
over the Kosovo situation and the tide of refugees caused by the
crisis, saying that Iran is of the belief that any military move
by other countries will deepen the crisis in the sensitive Balkan
region.
</P>
<P>
He said that Iran, as the chairman of the Organization of the
Islamic Conference, once again calls for a peaceful solution to
the crisis and the refraining from repressive moves against the
people.
</P>
<P>
"Direct negotiations between Belgrade and the local Kosovo
leaders as well as the realization of commitments by the Yugoslav
government, will be a good beginning for putting an end to the
unrest," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
