<HEADLINE> Iran Protests France Over Anti-Iran Film </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, June 17 (Xinhua) -- Iran's Islamic Human Rights
Commission (IHRC) on Wednesday sent a note to the French Embassy
here, protesting the broadcast of an anti-Iran film on a French
private television.
</P>
<P>
The protest was directed at the French TV Channel 6 for its
Monday night's screening of the movie "Not Without My Daughter," a
1989 production by American Jews which painted a negative image of
Iran and its leadership.
</P>
<P>
Iran believed that the film insulted the sanctities of Muslims
and the Iranian nation's traditions by presenting a backward
picture of its capital city Tehran.
</P>
<P>
Noting that the movie was broadcast during the ongoing soccer's
World Cup in France in which an Iranian team is participating, the
IHRC called the move "a violation of Iranians' rights and also
detrimental to the morale of the Iranian football players in the
World Cup matches."
</P>
<P>
It said that France should put emphasis on sports as an
instrument to enhance understanding and compassion among peoples
in the world.
</P>
<P>
The commission demanded an official apology from France to the
Iranian nation as well as its athletes, adding that the parties
responsible should be punished.
</P>
<P>
Head of the Iranian Football Federation Mohsen Safaie Farahani
and members of the Iranian national football team had earlier
handed a protest note to the World Cup Organizing Committee and
the world soccer's governing body, the International Football
Federation (FIFA).
</P>
<P>
The angry Iranian team briefly considered pulling out from the
World Cup in protest, but finally decided to stay on. The team
will play against the U.S. and German teams as scheduled. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
