<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Angola's Peace Process Takes Turn for Better </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, June 17 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations Representative
to Angola, Blondin Beye, asserted Wednesday that the crisis in
Angola will be over as the peace process will soon take a turn
for the better.
</P>
<P>
Beye made the remarks after holding talks with Angolan
President Eduardo Dos Santos, the visiting Beninese Speaker of
Parliament Bruno Amossou and delegates from the United States,
Russia and Portugal.
</P>
<P>
In order to get the process out of the current stalemate, Beye
said he went to the central city of Andulo Tuesday to meet with
Jonas Savimbi, President of the National Union for the Total
Independence of Angola (UNITA) for talks.
</P>
<P>
During the meeting, Savimbi promised to turn UNITA
headquarters of Bailundo and Andulo as well as two other
"sensitive" areas, Mungo and Nharea, over to government control,
Beye disclosed.
</P>
<P>
The UNITA leader agreed to allow a working team to start work
Wednesday in these areas to make preparation for the
reestablishment of local administrations.
</P>
<P>
Beye said Savimbi is opposed to the June 12 U.N. Security
Council resolution on imposing sanctions on UNITA, considering
that "it's unfair and goes too far, so it is unable to play a
positive role in the peace process."
</P>
<P>
However, the U.N. representative pointed out that through the
efforts by all parties, the Angolan peace process is getting on
the right track again and the situation is turning better.
</P>
<P>
The Angolan peace process hit snags after UNITA refused to
turn the so-called sensitive areas over to the governance of the
government and allegedly continued to keep a large armed force.
</P>
<P>
In order to compel UNITA to comply with the peace accord
reached by the two warring sides, the U.N. Security Council
decided last Friday to impose the third sanctions on the
opposition UNITA movement, including freezing its deposits in
foreign banks and curbing its exports of diamonds. 
</P>
