selected to power two Airbus Industrie A330-200s for Corsair,
France's largest tour operator.
</P>
<P>
The total engine business including a spare engine is worth
around 60 million U.S. dollars to the company, according to an
announcement Wednesday by Rolls-Royce.
</P>
<P>
The A330-200s will be powered by Rolls-Royce Trent 772B
engines, rated at 72,000lb thrust, the company said.
</P>
<P>
Mike Terrett, Rolls-Royce project director for the Trent 700
said: "Corsair is the first airline customer in France to buy
Trent engines and we look forward to a long and mutually rewarding
relationship with this successful European airline.
</P>
<P>
The A330-200 is the first new aircraft purchased by Corsair and
it will supplement the airline's existing long-haul fleet.
</P>
<P>
The Trent 700 entered service in March 1995, and has
accumulated over 100,000 flights and 250,000 hours in service.
Corsair is the 12th operator to select Trent 700 engines for its
A330 fleet.  
</P>
