<HEADLINE> Iran Blasts U.S. Paper for Fabrication </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, June 17 (Xinhua) -- An Iranian Defense Ministry
official on Wednesday attacked the U.S. newspaper Washington Times
for publishing "fabricated reports" on Iran's cooperation with
other countries to develop its arms programs.
</P>
<P>
The officials news agency IRNA quoted the official, Keyvan
Khosravi, as accusing the daily of making "a desperate attempt to
create a hypothetical enemy."
</P>
<P>
"Printing fabricated reports by the press affiliated to the
international Zionism cannot divert the public opinion from the
Israeli nuclear arms stockpiling," said Khosravi.
</P>
<P>
He said that arms production in Iran is in line with the
requirement of its armed forces, and merely for defense purpose.
</P>
<P>
Frequently accusing Iran of seeking weapons of mass
destruction, the U.S. and Israel have been exerting tremendous
efforts to prevent Tehran from acquiring missile and nuclear
technologies. Israel regards Iran as its leading enemy in the
Middle East.
</P>
<P>
The Iranian official also blasted Israel for taking advantage
of the nuclear tests by India and Pakistan last month to launch
extensive efforts to stockpile nuclear arms. Israel is believed to
be the only country in the Middle East that has acquired the
nuclear capability.
</P>
<P>
Khosravi said that equipping modern submarines with nuclear
arms was Israel's new practice of developing non-conventional
weapons.
</P>
<P>
He believed that Israel's stockpiling of nuclear arms is
supported by certain segments of western mass media, which are
seeking to ease the pressure exerted on Israel by the world
community.
</P>
<P>
He also criticized the U.S. for continuing to bear Israel's
huge burden of military expenditure despite the world objection to
the Israeli nuclear program. 
</P>
</TEXT>
