<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Netanyahu Heading for Pullback Agreement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, June 17 (Xinhua) -- Both supporters and opponents
are now of the same view that Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin
Netanyahu is heading for a long-overdue agreement on Israeli
redeployment in the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu, however, remained tight-lipped on whether such a
deal was forthcoming. In an interview with Israel Radio Wednesday,
he only confirmed reports that some progress has been made in the
last few weeks to prepare the ground for an agreement.
</P>
<P>
Significant gaps remain between Israel and the Palestinians, he
insisted.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli leader promised that he would work "continuously
and tirelessly" in order to "achieve an agreed and negotiated
solution which will give Israel the security it deserves and will
give us the Palestinian compliance which they promised."
</P>
<P>
Asked if there will be an agreement by the end of the current
Knesset (Parliament) session on July 29, Netanyahu said it depends
on the Palestinian side. He urged Palestinians to adopt "a
realistic attitude, an attitude of keeping their commitments" in
order to accelerate the peace process.
</P>
<P>
But several Cabinet ministers, for or against a redeployment
agreement, said Wednesday they were certain that the prime
minister is definitely moving toward a deal with Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
Public Security Minister Avigdor Kahalani of the centrist party
The Third Way, which has been pressing for an agreement, said
Netanyahu's biggest problem now is how to persuade the far-right
National Religious Party (NRP) to accept the deal. The NRP has
threatened to quit the coalition if Netanyahu accepts a major
redeployment.
</P>
<P>
NRP's Minister of Transportation Shaul Yahalom said Netanyahu
has made up his mind on the issue and will not stop it. He
expressed hope that the settlers, traditional political supporters
of the current government, would prevent Netanyahu from carrying
out such pullback.
</P>
<P>
He was referring to a recent decision taken by the Council of
Jewish Settlers in the West Bank and Gaza Strip on launching an
all-out campaign against major pullback through mass street
protests.
</P>
<P>
It appeared that Netanyahu has accepted the U.S. proposal for a
13 percent second redeployment, but the sticking point now is the
scope of the third and last pullback as stipulated in the signed
agreement.
</P>
<P>
Israel Radio quoted a senior political source as saying that
Netanyahu is waiting for answers from the United States and the
Palestinians to his proposal on the third redeployment.
</P>
<P>
Under the proposal, about 4 percent of the Israel-controlled
territories in the West Bank, or Area C, will be designated as
Area C-, where Israel has security control but Palestinians will
exercise broader civil powers.
</P>
<P>
Earlier reports said that Netanyahu was trying to postpone a
decision on the second pullback till the end of the Knesset
session in an attempt to avoid being brought down by the Knesset.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu denied he is counting on the opposition Labor Party's
help to push through his redeployment agreement when it is brought
to the Knesset for vote. But he urged the Labor to support him,
saying "if they are for peace, they should vote for us."
</P>
<P>
The Labor Party is divided over whether it should provide a
"safety net" for the government during the Knesset vote on the
redeployment agreement.
</P>
<P>
Some Labor lawmakers insist that Labor should support Netanyahu
because the broad peace goal should come above the narrow party's
interests, while others argue that the Labor should topple the
incumbent hard-line government at any costs in order to take its
place.
</P>
<P>
Under the Israeli law, the government should step down to pave
the way for new elections if 61 members of the 120-member Knesset
vote against it. The Netanyahu-led coalition now holds a
blade-thin 61 majority in the Knesset. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
