<HEADLINE> Number of Abandoned Babies Rises Sharply in S. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, June 17 (Xinhua) -- South Africa is facing a
dramatic rise in the number of abandoned babies, and child
welfare agencies have appealed to the public for help in
providing homes for the foundlings.
</P>
<P>
The Department of Welfare does not keep records of the number
of babies abandoned, but officials estimate that between 3,000
and 4,000 babies were abandoned across the country last year,
South African Press Association reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
According to Lynette Schreuder from the National Council of
Child Welfare, the number of children abandoned between April
1997 and April 1998 doubled that of the previous year.
</P>
<P>
Schreuder said 931 abandoned babies were reported by the
council's 173 affiliates around the country last year. The figure
for 1996/97 was 452.
</P>
<P>
In Johannesburg alone, Johannesburg Child Welfare received 25
cases of abandonment in the first 10 days of June.
</P>
<P>
"The numbers are definitely increasing, each week we record
between 10 and 15 new abandoned babies on our register," said
Shereen Patel, social worker at the organization.
</P>
<P>
Patel said the situation had reached crisis levels.
</P>
<P>
"We are desperately seeking foster homes for these babies,"
she said. "We are facing a crisis situation. There is a
tremendous need for adoptive parents, as well as temporary foster
homes."
</P>
<P>
In 1997, the total number of babies abandoned to Johannesburg
Child Welfare was 197 and the agency has managed to find homes
for 52, Patel said.
</P>
<P>
This year the Johannesburg Child Welfare is receiving up to 50
cases a month and Patel estimates that one in three of the babies
are HIV-positive. 
</P>
</TEXT>
