<HEADLINE> Rwanda to Exempt Tax on Vehicles </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
NAIROBI, June 17 (Xinhua) -- The Government of Rwanda has
decided to exempt local trucks importers from
paying import duties for one year as a strategy of revitalizing
the war-torn transport sector.
</P>
<P>
According to a notice issued by the Commissioner of Customs
Murangira Appolinaire last Thursday, all customs collectors were
instructed that "all lorries and trailers, pick-ups, buses and
bulldozers were exempted with immediate effect from paying import
duty," the Rwanda News Agency reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
This is aimed at boosting transport sector as a primary
necessity as well as to promote inter-regional transportation in
the country for servicing production sector, the report said.
</P>
<P>
However, the said exemption does not include sales tax
commonly known as ICHA (imp sur le chiffre d'affaires).
</P>
<P>
In Rwanda, import duty for imported vehicles are calculated
at varied rates from 20 to 50 percent of the basic price plus the
transport cost, depending on the type and size of the car.
</P>
<P>
"Businessmen welcome the decision as most were being
discouraged by rate of taxing which was very high compared with
neighbouring countries," said the secretary of information in
Rwandan Chamber of Commerce.
</P>
<P>
Some local transporters are opting to import trucks and
register them in Tanzania where heavy and light trucks are
exempted from paying tax for seven years, he added.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
