<HEADLINE> Sexual Harassment Cases Reduce in Zanzibar </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, June 17 (Xinhua) -- Cases of sexual harassment
against women have drastically dropped in Zanzibar last year, a
senior Zanzibar official said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The Minister of State in the President's Office responsible
for Women and Children Affairs Asha Bakari told the House of
Representatives that only 10 cases of harassment had been
reported in the twin islands of Unguja and Pemba in Zanzibar
during the year 1997, compared to 31 cases in the previous year,
according to a report reaching here.
</P>
<P>
Four cases had been recorded in Pemba and six cases in Unguja
in 1997 against 13 cases booked in Pemba and 18 in Unguja in
1996, she said.
</P>
<P>
The minister of state attributed the slump of the sexual
harassment cases to the educational program launched by the
government and non-governmental organizations (NGOs) against
sexual harassment.
</P>
<P>
She proposes that the government should harshly punish the
culprits in a bid to fight the offence mostly committed by
adults.
</P>
<P>
She also said the courts have prohibited the mass media to
show the suspected offenders on television screen or announce
their names through radio or newspapers until they were proven
guilty.
</P>
<P>
Under the law, a person was innocent unless proved guilty by
the court, she stressed.  
</P>
</TEXT>
