<HEADLINE> Blair Warns Hooligans to be Sacked </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, June 17 (Xinhua) -- British Prime Minister Tony Blair
on Wednesday sent a tough warning to soccer thugs that they should
expect the sack if convicted of hooliganism in France.
</P>
<P>
Speaking in the parliament, he urged employers to take "strong
action" against the "mindless minority" involved in soccer
violence.
</P>
<P>
The government could not carry on the fight against the
hooliganism alone, he said. "We also...have to encourage employers
to take strong action against those people that are convicted of
football hooligan offenses abroad."
</P>
<P>
He said public service and the armed forces particularly should
target any of their employees involved in hooliganism.
</P>
<P>
"Certainly (in the case of) anybody who may be employed by the
public service or the armed forces who are convicted of football
hooliganism, I hope very strong action is taken indeed," he said.
</P>
<P>
Blair also admitted the British police database of known
hooligans had proved inadequate to deal with supporters who caused
havoc in the French city of Marseille, where England played on
Monday.
</P>
<P>
"The intelligence that we have about these football hooligans
isn't as great as we need it to be, though we have the most
extensive database on it anywhere in the world," he said.
</P>
<P>
Blair had already apologized for the drunken destructiveness of
English fans to French President Jacques Chirac when the two met
at the European Union summit in Cardiff, Wales.
</P>
<P>
More people had been placed under restriction orders to stop
them travelling to France, and cooperation between the two
countries' police forces had been closer than ever.  
</P>
</TEXT>
