<HEADLINE> Handheld Devices To Overtake PCs for Net Access, </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Los Angeles, June 17 (Xinhua) -- Cheap devices for mass-market
Internet access will supplant desktop computers within the next
six years, according to a U.S. information technology market
researcher.
</P>
<P>
In a report released Tuesday, International Data Corp. (IDC)
predicted demand for handheld devices will nearly triple in annual
volume from 1997 to 2002, and exceed PC unit sales by 2004 or
2005.
</P>
<P>
In a previous report, IDC said that 1998 should be a banner
growth year for the smart handheld device market as unit shipments
are expected to hit 8.2 million worldwide. The projected growth
represents a 61 percent increase over estimated 1997 unit
shipments of 5.1 million units.
</P>
<P>
Without hinting that the PC will fade away, the Tuesday report,
however, indicated that as prices of simple devices like handheld
units, Web-enabled phones or set-top boxes fall below 100 U.S.
dollars, they will become more popular than PCs.
</P>
<P>
Some industry watchers say that the low-cost Internet device
will replace the PC simply because PC these days provide more
computer power than most people need. But they predict that cheap
access devices will proliferate until people find more compelling
reasons to browse the Internet.
</P>
<P>
An IDC analyst said that even at a low price under 1,000
dollars, people won't have three, four or five PCs around their
houses. People want to go online without having to go to the PC
room -- they want to use it wherever they are.
</P>
<P>
IDC predicts PC makers will eventually get into the low-cost
Internet device market, or risk missing a passing wave.
</P>
<P>
Indeed, a new wave of technologies and designs has resulted in
more and more smart handheld devices. Apart from letting users
cruise the Internet, they can keep phone number lists and
calendars and send and receivers e-mail. Most handheld devices
weigh less than a pound and fit into a jacket pocket. But the
keyboards on most units are too small to comfortably write much
more than a short message. In addition, improvements are also
called to make the screens brighter.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980618.0062 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-17 19:49 </DATE_TIME>
