<HEADLINE> Thirty Percent Canadian Households Communicate By Computer </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, June 17 (Xinhua) -- Nearly three out of 10 Canadians
households had at least one member who used a computer every month
to communicate, Statistics Canada said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
According to the statistics agency's survey done last October,
35 percent of households in Alberta had at least one member who
had used some form of computer communication each month, the
largest proportion of any Canadian provinces.
</P>
<P>
Communicating by computer, whether it was for e-mail,
electronic banking or surfing the Internet, was more common in
households with young people.
</P>
<P>
At least one person used a computer regularly to communicate in
38 percent of households in which there was someone under the age
of 18, compared with only 25 percent of households in which there
was no one under 18.
</P>
<P>
Canadians were most likely to use a computer to communicate at
their workplace, which was followed by the home, schools and
public libraries.
</P>
<P>
Of those households that typically used computer communications
every month, 84 percent reported using this modern tool to search
for information on the Internet, the agency said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, some 83 percent said they used them for e-mail.
About one third had someone using computers to communicate from
home for employer-related business.
</P>
<P>
The survey also indicates that 15 percent of households used
the Internet from home in a typical month of communicating,
compared with 14 percent in May, 1997.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
