<DOCNO> XIE19980618.0065 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Offers Support to Japanese Yen </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 17 (Xinhua) -- President Bill Clinton said
Wednesday that he would offer support to the Japanese yen after
Japanese Prime Minister Ryutaro Hashimoto had pledged "aggressive"
financial system reform and other economic steps.
</P>
<P>
"I was very encouraged by the prime minister's statement that
he intends to pursue aggressive reform of their banking
institutions and intends to do the things that were necessary to
get their economy going again," Clinton said in response to a
reporter's question during a White House Rose Garden appearance.
</P>
<P>
Clinton spoke to Hashimoto by telephone Tuesday night after
being briefed by top administration economic and national security
officials.
</P>
<P>
"Japan is very important to the world, especially to the United
States, and to the efforts we're making to support an economic
recovery in Asia, which is very important to keeping our own
economic progress going," Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
"We've got a chance to turn that situation in Asia around
before it gets any worse," he added.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, the Treasury Department instructed the New York
Federal Reserve to spend an estimated 2 billion dollars to bolster
the sagging yen, selling dollars for the Japanese currency.
</P>
<P>
Treasury Secretary Rober Rubin said the intervention took place
"in the context of Japan's plans to strengthen its economy" and
said the United States was ready to continue the action if needed.
</P>
<P>
It was the first time U.S. authorities intervened on behalf of
the yen since February 1992 and economists said it indicated how
concerned Washington has become about the slumping Japanese
economy.
</P>
<P>
Clinton said he wanted to "send a clear signal to the markets
that the Untied States supports Japanese reform, and believes the
Japanese people can pull out of this economic slump and restore
growth and opportunity."
</P>
<P>
Clinton also dispatched Deputy Treasury Secretary Lawrence
Summers to head a high-level U.S. delegation to Japan to discuss
the country's economy and financial crisis in Asia.
</P>
<P>
White House spokesman Mike McCurry said the decision was made
after Clinton was briefed by Treasury Secretary Rubin, National
Security Adviser Sandy Berger, White House Chief of Staff Erskine
Bowles and others.
</P>
<P>
McCurry said the intervention came at a critical moment for
Japan. "The president and the United States government obviously
believe that this is an important moment for Japan to deal with
the challenges that it faces," he said.
</P>
<P>
"The United States and Japan are prepared to continue to
cooperate in currency markets," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
