<HEADLINE> U.S. Plans to Boost Iraq's Opposition </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 17 (Xinhua) -- The United States plans a new
effort, funded by Congress, to build up a political opposition to
Iraq's President Saddam Hussein, a senior U.S. official said
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
"We will be launching an effort to help them organize and
coordinate their case against Saddam Hussein," Assistant Secretary
of State Martin Indyk told a group of journalists at the State
Department.
</P>
<P>
He said there were 73 opposition groups outside of Iraq and
"now we're going to get behind them and try to help them," he
said. "They represent an alternative vision for Iraq to Saddam
Hussein."
</P>
<P>
"I don't place a high probability on their ability to overthrow
Saddam but it's important they demonstrate there is a different
way of life for the Iraqi people," he said.
</P>
<P>
Congressional Republicans proposed spending 38 million dollars
to help Iraqi opposition movements overthrow Saddam after a crisis
earlier this year over an Iraqi crisis on weapons inspections.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
