<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Vietnam to Cut Import Tariff on 213 Items </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, June 18 (Xinhua) -- The Vietnamese government is to cut
import tariffs on 213 groups of items in a program of tariff
reduction for access to the ASEAN Free Trade Area (AFTA).
</P>
<P>
The figure accounts for 6.6 percent of the number of products
liable for import tax, the Saigon Times newspaper reported
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The tariff-cutting program is part of the effort by the
nine-member ASEAN to facilitate trade and investment
liberalization in the region.
</P>
<P>
Seven members of the bloc -- Brunei, Indonesia, Malaysia, the
Philippines, Singapore, Thailand and Vietnam -- have agreed on an
average cut of 5 percent or less under the AFTA program by the
year 2003 at their summit in Bangkok at the end of 1995.
</P>
<P>
Laos and Myanmar joined the group in 1997.
</P>
<P>
The Ministry of Trade is preparing a program to lift non-tariff
barriers to increase the competitiveness of local products, the
newspaper said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
