<DOCNO> XIE19980618.0072 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Asian Markets Surge After Intervention </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
 (By Xu Haijing)
</P>
<P>
BANGKOK, June 18 (Xinhua) -- Stock and currency markets across
Asia on Thursday responded warmly to the joint efforts made by the
United States and Japan to bolster the plummeting yen.
</P>
<P>
In Bangkok, the Stock Exchange of Thailand (SET) index
rocketed 22.21 points, or eight percent, to close at 295.15, only
one step from regaining the 300 psychological level.
</P>
<P>
Transactions are active as some 559 million shares worth 4.35
billion baht (1.08 billion U.S. dollars) changed hands, about six
times and four times higher than that of the bearish days last
week.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, stock markets in Hong Kong, Seoul, Singapore and
other major cities in Asia all recorded great gains from four to
seven percent.
</P>
<P>
Back in Japan, the center of the recent financial earthquake,
the Nikkei index gained 646.16 points, or 4 percent, closing above
the 15,000 level.
</P>
<P>
In the currency market, the yen quickly climbed from a nearly
eight-year low of 146 yen to the U.S. dollar to above 136 yen to
one dollar, pushing other Asian currencies higher.
</P>
<P>
In Thailand, the Thai baht rose to 41.00/41.50 to the
greenback from 42.95/43.33 one day earlier.
</P>
<P>
on Wednesday, the United States put 2 billion dollars into the
market, selling dollars and buying yen.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, japan's parliament passed a special 4.65 trillion
yen (32.7 billion dollars) supplementary budget which is part of a
record 16.65 trillion yen (396.4 billion dollars) economic
stimulus package announced in April.
</P>
<P>
The moves had immediately been proved effective as the yen
surged, triggering rallies in stock markets across the United
States and Europe on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
However, analysts said the yen's surge reflected a rather
psychological reaction of the market toward the intervention.
</P>
<P>
They said whether the yen can hold on at a favorable level
depends on the effectiveness of the Japanese government's measures
to stimulate the economy.
</P>
<P>
Japan is now in the eighth year of the post-bubble era. The
world's second-largest economy has never really recovered from
that big blow.
</P>
<P>
Instead, the country registered negative growth of its gross
domestic product (GDP) in the recent two consecutive quarters.
</P>
<P>
Demands at home are low, while scandals from financial
companies can be often heard.
</P>
<P>
All these domestic problems in Japan took a toll of economies
in southeast Asian and east Asian countries, since they are
desperately relying on Japan, a so-called "engine" of Asian
development.
</P>
<P>
Japan is the largest investor in the Association of Southeast
Asian Nations (ASEAN) while remaining the biggest debtor.
</P>
<P>
Taking Thailand as an example, about 55 percent of the
country's debts are owed to Japan. Meanwhile, Japan is among the
three biggest export markets of Thai products.
</P>
<P>
The sharp depreciation of the yen will deeply hurt the export
industries of Thailand, other ASEAN countries and south Korea.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the currency fluctuation triggered by the yen
devaluation is very likely to cause the second round of the Asian
crisis to break out.
</P>
<P>
As the markets welcomed the yen surge after the intervention,
Asian leaders preferred to maintain a clear mind as the
fundamental problems have not been solved.
</P>
<P>
Japanese Prime Minister Ryutaro Hashimoto had pledged to make
every efforts to restore the banking system to health, to achieve
domestic demand-led growth, and to open and deregulate the
Japanese markets.
</P>
<P>
Nevertheless, as Thai Prime Minister Chuan Leekpai said
Thursday, Asian countries must keep an eye on the development of
the situation in Japan. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
