<HEADLINE> Chubais: Russia Needs Much Financial Aid </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, June 18 (Xinhua) - Russia needs up to 15 billion
U.S. dollars of financial assistance to stabilize its financial
market, Anatoly Chubais, the newly-appointed president's special
envoy for finance, said on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Chubais, chairman of United Energy Systems of Russia, was
appointed Wednesday President Boris Yeltsin's special envoy for
liaison with international financial agencies in the rank of
deputy prime minister.
</P>
<P>
The Interfax news agency quoted Chubais as saying that the
current economic situation was complicated, and serious
consideration was being given to the idea of attracting additional
financial resources.
</P>
<P>
However, he stressed, Russia would not accept financial aid "on
just any conditions."
</P>
<P>
He noted that although borrowing from the International
Monetary Fund (IMF) was the cheapest, the organization puts very
tough conditions on its credits.
</P>
<P>
Chubais said he recently had talks with Prime Minister Sergei
Kiriyenko and Deputy Prime Minister Boris Nemtsov on possible
additional financial aid from the IMF.
</P>
<P>
Chubais stressed that Russia should determine its position on
the issue of accepting loans. "There are conditions on the
provision of loans which we would not accept from any financial
organizations," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
