<HEADLINE> Pakistan Said Not to Attend ASEAN Forum </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, June 18 (Xinhua) -- Pakistan will not be able to attend
the ASEAN Regional Forum (ARF) to be held in Manila next month
because of the opposition of its arch-rival, India, Philippine
Foreign Affairs Secretary Domingo Siazon said here Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Siazon, who met Indian Minister of State for External Affairs
Vasundhara Raje Wednesday, told reporters that India did not favor
the proposed participation of Pakistan in the upcoming meeting.
</P>
<P>
Siazon said earlier several members of the ASEAN (Association
of Southeast Asian Nations) Regional Forum had proposed that
Pakistan be invited to the ARF meeting which is expected to
include the nuclear non-proliferation issue in its agenda.
</P>
<P>
India is a regular ASEAN dialogue partner in the ARF. Pakistan
has a pending application with the forum but has not been admitted
in yet.
</P>
<P>
"Neither did India agree to have Pakistani representative
invited to the ARF dinner following their meeting on July 27,"
Siazon added.
</P>
<P>
According to Siazon, since the ARF works by consensus, the move
to get Pakistan to the Manila meet is dead.
</P>
<P>
Siazon said India has asserted that their problem with Pakistan
is "an internal affair between them" and is inclined to discourage
outside intervention into it.
</P>
<P>
Indian Ambassador to Manila C.P. Ravindranathan said that
instead of ARF bringing India and Pakistan together, "it would be
better if they should first be given ample time and opportunity to
resolve their bilateral differences."
</P>
<P>
Ravindranathan added that discussing their India-Pakistan
bilateral problems in the forthcoming ARF meeting in Manila may be
premature. 
</P>
</TEXT>
