<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-18 14:44 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Khatami Backs Interior Minister against Impeachment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, June 18 (Xinhua) -- As Iran's factional struggle waged
on, President Mohammad Khatami again came to the defense of his
interior minister Thursday, who faced impeachment by hardline
members of the Majlis (Parliament).
</P>
<P>
The absence of Abdollah Nouri in the cabinet would "entail
massive damage for the government and the country," Khatami said
while speaking to a group of staff members of the Interior
Ministry.
</P>
<P>
It was the strongest-ever response to a call raised by 31
Majlis deputies last week for the sacking of Nouri on charges of
creating tension in the country, making provocative statements and
using inexperienced people at his ministry.
</P>
<P>
The moderate faction believes the impeachment, following the
trial of Tehran mayor who is a close ally of the president, is yet
another move by the conservatives aimed at weakening Khatami's
government.
</P>
<P>
The underdog conservatives who lost the battle to the moderates
in last year's presidential election, insisted that they should
exercise their constitutional rights and prevent the ministers
from "going too far."
</P>
<P>
According to the official news agency IRNA, Khatami
acknowledged that the conservatives have the freedom and right to
do so "as defined in the constitution."
</P>
<P>
"I and my administration are highly serious about this
principle; of course it has costs which must be paid, just like
building a bridge or a factory which entails expenses," he said.
</P>
<P>
Khatami spoke highly of Nouri, saying that appointing him as
interior minister was "because of his bright record before and
after the Islamic Revolution in 1979, and also that "I trust his
piety and the fact that he was trusted by the late leader (Imam
Khomeini)."
</P>
<P>
Nouri once served as Khomeini's representative in the elite
Islamic Revolution's Guards Corps, and as member of the State
Expediency Council and interior minister in the government of
former President Hashemi Rafsanjani.
</P>
<P>
Khatami persuaded the hardliners to "give a vote of confidence"
to Nouri, "in the light of sensitive conditions of the country and
difficult tasks ahead of the government," to allow "the
administration to carry on with its duties and strengthen the
bonds between the Majlis and the government."
</P>
<P>
"Nouri is one of the strongest ministers in the cabinet and his
presence and opinions in all fields are source of blessing for
us," he said.
</P>
<P>
However, Iran's political analysts are pessimistic that Nouri
would be able to survive a vote in the conservative-dominated
Majlis, as he has been singled out as a punching bag.
</P>
<P>
Khatami warned that the conservatives should heed three key
points in the process of impeachment: the constitution, policies
of the system, and the president's program of action approved by
the public in the course of elections and subsequently by the
Majlis.
</P>
<P>
Khatami won the presidency in May last year by a landslide over
his rival, the Majlis speaker Ali Akbar Nateq Nouri. He was
overwhelmingly supported by the young people, women and
intellectuals who were eager for changes in the society.
</P>
<P>
However, it is the supreme leader, Ayatollah Khamenei, who has
the final say in many a critical issue in the country. This time,
it may also up to the reportedly conservative-leaning leader to
finally mediate a solution to the power-wrestling. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
