<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-18 15:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israeli Institute Clarifies Reported Nuclear Test </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, June 18 (Xinhua) -- To reinforce official denial of
reports that Israel conducted a secret nuclear test, the
Seismological Institute (ISI) said Thursday it did not detected
any seismological evidence of such a test.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with Israel Radio, ISI's head Abbi Shapira
categorically rejected the claim that a nuclear device was
detonated in the Gulf of Eilat in southern Israel on May 28.
</P>
<P>
He said the institute's seismographical instruments, which he
described as "very sensitive," did not pick up any signals of such
a test.
</P>
<P>
Israeli officials earlier firmly denied reports that an
earthquake that jolted the area in late May was caused by a secret
nuclear explosion by Israel.
</P>
<P>
The ISI confirmed that there was indeed an earthquake on May
28, but it's epicenter was in the west of Egypt's Mediterranean
port Alexandria and it was a result of natural seismological
activity.
</P>
<P>
Two Israeli opposition lawmakers, Rafi Elul of the Labor Party
and Abdul Wahab Darawshe of the Democratic Arab Party, said in the
Knesset (Parliament) Wednesday that they have received information
from the International Atomic Energy Agency about the nuclear
testing. They demanded Deputy Defense Minister Silvan Shalom
clarify on the matter.
</P>
<P>
Shalom gave no immediate answer to the question. But in a
statement issued later, he dismissed the two lawmakers' charges as
"baseless," noting that Israel abides by the Nuclear Test Ban
Treaty which it has signed.
</P>
<P>
Ephraim Asculai, spokesman for the Israeli Atomic Energy
Commission, also said Israel has never carried out a nuclear
test. He said his commission had detected only natural
seismological activity instead of signs of a nuclear test.
</P>
<P>
Asked about the safety of the nuclear reactor at the Negev
Nuclear Research Center in Dimona in the south, Shalom said
regular examinations showed that it is safe and "there is no
reason to stop its operation."
</P>
<P>
Israel is the only country in the Middle East that has acquired
nuclear capability. Although western intelligence reports claimed
it has about 200 nuclear warheads, Israel has neither confirmed
nor denied that it has any nuclear weapons.
</P>
<P>
The series of nuclear tests conducted in May by India and
Pakistan, the two arch rivals in south Asia, have got on Israeli
nerves. Calling the Pakistani explosions as the first "Islamic
Bomb," Israel is worried that nuclear weapon technology could soon
be transferred to its enemies in the region like Iran. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
