<HEADLINE> Germany Reports New Rail Sabotage </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, June 18 (Xinhua) -- A Hamburg-Berlin high-speed train was
slowed down, but not derailed, Wednesday afternoon after hitting
gravel deliberately placed on the tracks near the northern German
town of Buechen, police said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The Inter-City Express (ICE) passed through the gravel on a
50-meter stretch of track at a speed of about 150 kilometers per
hour.
</P>
<P>
After hearing the noise, the driver slowed the train to 120
kilometers an hour and continued to Berlin where the train was
inspected.
</P>
<P>
According to an Interior Ministry report last week, Germany has
registered 40 attempts to sabotage rail traffic this year so far.
</P>
<P>
The latest incident also came just two weeks after another ICE
train derailed and crashed into a road bridge near the northern
German town of Eschede, killing 100 people and injuring 88.
</P>
<P>
Police, however, have not linked the tragedy to any deliberate
attack. A broken wheel caused by metal fatigue or material defect
is believed to the cause of the derailment. 
</P>
</TEXT>
