<HEADLINE> Philippines Pledges Support in Reviving </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, June 18 (Xinhua) -- Philippine Vice President and
President-Elect Joseph Estrada on Thursday committed the
Philippines' support to all efforts that will be taken by its
neighbors in Asia in reviving the Japanese economy.
</P>
<P>
In a press briefing, Estrada said "we support all measures that
will be taken by Japan and other OECD (Organization of Economic
Cooperation and Development) countries to strengthen the yen,
revive the Japanese economy."
</P>
<P>
Experts said the recovery of the economies of Asia from the
currency turmoil that hit the region last year rests heavily on
the Japanese economy's ability to survive the recession it is
presently facing.
</P>
<P>
Estrada, who will take his oath of office on June 30, said his
government will also support "the Asian economies that have been
adversely affected by the regional financial economic crisis."
</P>
<P>
Estrada made the commitment even as he admitted that the
Philippines will "take longer to achieve economic growth with
equity and prosperity for all."
</P>
<P>
But he stressed that "we are strongly committed to economic
policies and programs that will promote and finance exports,
maintain fiscal discipline and micro-economic stability."
</P>
<P>
He particularly cited the plan by his administration to
counteract the Philippine economy's reaction to the fall of the
Japanese yen.
</P>
<P>
Among these are moves to "strengthen the banking system,
continue expanding the liberalization of foreign trade and the
peso, privatize government corporations and increase global
competitiveness of domestic firms." 
</P>
