<HEADLINE> Head Of China's Supreme Court Says Sino-US Cooperation In Law Studies Important </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 18 (Xinhua) -- The President of China's Supreme
People's Court Xiao Yang told a Sino-U.S. seminar on the future of
legal studies here today that China needs to use the experiences
of the U.S. and other countries.
</P>
<P>
In 1978, China formulated its policy of developing socialist
democracy and improving the socialist legal system, and in 1997,
it developed its basic strategy of rule by law and now has a legal
framework with Chinese characteristics, and this is progress, he
said.
</P>
<P>
The seminar, which opened yesterday, was the first of a series
of exchanges in the legal sector between the two countries since
Chinese president jiang Zemin visited the US last year. It has
provided an opportunity for presidents of more than 30 Chinese and
American university law schools and legal scholars to discuss
education in their field.
</P>
<P>
