<HEADLINE> Anti-Nuclear March held in India </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, June 18 (Xinhua) -- Indian former Prime Minister
Deve Gowda Thursday led an "anti-nuclear march" in the country's
scientific city Bangalore in southern India for banning all
weapons of mass destruction in the world.
</P>
<P>
Hundreds of people including State ministers, intellectuals,
writers, journalists with black badges tied to their left arms
walked in a silent procession from the National College to Mahatma
Gandhi road where they held a rally against nuclear weapons.
</P>
<P>
The marchers held placards with the message "Say no to nuclear
weapons say yes to life" "Say no to war say yes to friendship and
brotherhood," etc.
</P>
<P>
Since the Indian government conducted five successive
underground nuclear tests on May 11 and 13, various political
parties and mass organizations have accused the government of
conducting the nuclear tests.
</P>
<P>
In their resolution adopted at the rally, the marchers appealed
to all nations in the world, including those that are already
nuclear power states, "to come together and work towards banning
further development of nuclear weapons as well as the destruction
of those that already exist in those nations."
</P>
<P>
Similar protest demonstrations were held in New Delhi, capital
of India, as soon as the government conducted nuclear tests last
month. 
</P>
</TEXT>
