<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> "India Today" Reveals Nuclear Test Secrets </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, June 18 (Xinhua) -- A 100-strong core team of
nuclear experts participated in India's recent nuclear tests, said
the latest issue of India Today magazine in a cover story on the
country's five underground nuclear tests on May 11 and 13.
</P>
<P>
The team members donned army uniforms to avoid raising
suspicion among locals over their frequent visits to Pokhran range
and kept the decision to go ahead with the tests top secret, the
magazine said.
</P>
<P>
So detailed was the planning that scientists were even given
army ranks according to their seniority.
</P>
<P>
For example, Atomic Energy Commission Chairman R. Chidambaram
was code-named Major General Natraj whenever he visited Pokhran
during preparations for the blasts.
</P>
<P>
Scientific adviser to the Defense Minister and Defense Research
and Development Organization Chief A. P. J. Abdul Kalam was known
as Major General Prithviraj.
</P>
<P>
Referring to the transport of plutonium fissile material cores,
the magazine said that 10 days before the blasts, an air force
transport An-32 aircraft took off from Mumbai's Santa Cruz airport
at night with the materials.
</P>
<P>
Two hours later, a convoy of trucks lined up to meet the
aircraft and half-a-dozen wooden crates were placed inside one of
them.
</P>
<P>
To make it seem a routine movement, no extra security was
provided as they sped to the range under the cover of darkness.
</P>
<P>
Inside those crates, protected by metal shield, were perfectly
shaped spherical balls of explosive grade plutonium, with each
ball weighing between five and 10 kilograms.
</P>
<P>
Once in Pokhran, the crates were moved into makeshift
laboratories where other packages containing conventional
explosives, detonators and triggers had been flown in and
scientists began constructing the devices, the magazine said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
