<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Trade Deficit Surges to Record High in April </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 18 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. trade deficit shot up
to a record high of 14.5 billion U.S. dollars in April, the
Commerce Department reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The department said that the deficit was 9.5 percent higher
than the March imbalance of 13.2 billion dollars, the previous
record. The growth is largely blamed on the Asian currency
devaluations which help Asian exports, pushing down the U.S. sales
abroad.
</P>
<P>
While imports declined a slight 0.9 percent after hitting an
all-time high the month before, U.S. exports fell even more
sharply, dropping 2.6 percent as the deepening recession in many
Asian markets cut into U.S. sales.
</P>
<P>
For the first four months of this year, the U.S. deficit in
goods and services signalled an annual rate of 149 billion
dollars, on track to set a record, far surpassing last year's
imbalance of 110.2 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
The deficit with Japan edged down 6 percent in April to 5.4
billion dollars but is still running 13.3 percent ahead of the
same period in 1997.
</P>
<P>
For the entire Pacific Rim region, which includes South Korea
and other countries and regions hard hit by the currency crisis,
the U.S. trade deficit in the first four months of this year
totalled 48.7 billion dollars, 38 percent higher than a year ago.
</P>
<P>
In April, the 2.6 percent drop in the exports of goods and
services pushed them down to 77.1 billion dollars. Exports of
goods fell to 55.3 billion dollars, the lowest level since
February 1997. Exports of the U.S. farm products dropped to 3.8
billion dollars, the lowest level since September 1994.
</P>
<P>
Among the export categories declining were sales of commercial
aircraft which fell 926 million dollars to 1.6 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
Imports of goods and services, which hit a record high of 92.4
billion dollars in March, slipped 0.9 percent in April to 91.6
billion dollars, but still the second-highest level in history.
</P>
<P>
The 14.5 billion dollar deficit was the highest since the
government began tracking goods and services on a monthly basis in
1992. For goods alone, the deficit of 21.5 billion dollars was
also the highest in the U.S. history. 
</P>
</TEXT>
