<HEADLINE> Japanese PM Vows to Revive Economy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, June 18 (Xinhua) -- Japanese Prime Minister Ryutaro
Hashimoto on Thursday vowed to step up efforts to resolve the
bad-loan problem of Japanese banks so as to stimulate the domestic
economy and restore market confidence.
</P>
<P>
"To spark a rebound in the stalled economy, I will do my best
to help write off bad loans, achieve growth driven by domestic
demand, open Japanese markets further and promote deregulation,"
Hashimoto said at the end of the regular 158-day Diet (parliament)
session.
</P>
<P>
Hashimoto said he thought the joint Japan-U.S. intervention to
support the yen Wednesday "won high marks from the markets."
</P>
<P>
"To maintain their appreciation, we need to put in our best
effort to wipe out anxieties about the future of the Japanese
economy in a way that can produce visible results," he said.
</P>
<P>
For that purpose, nonperforming loans held by financial
institutions had to be disposed of so that confidence in the
country's financial system would recover, Hashimoto stressed.
</P>
<P>
Hashimoto said his government would take drastic measures to
resolve the bad-loan problem, which has been dragging economic
recovery.
</P>
<P>
Japanese banks' bad loans have amounted to 27 trillion yen
(197.5 billion U.S. dollars), according to a government estimate
unveiled in January.
</P>
<P>
Hashimoto also reiterated his government's intention to lower
income tax rates as a step to spur economic recovery and to reduce
corporate tax rates from 46.5 percent to about 40 percent to match
the rates seen in most major industrialized countries as early as
possible.
</P>
<P>
On the July 12 House of Councillors (upper house) elections,
Hashimoto expressed his resolve to lead his Liberal Democratic
Party (LDP) to victory.
</P>
<P>
Japan's 142nd ordinary Diet session closed early Thursday,
setting the stage for campaigns officially beginning June 25 for
the upper house. 
</P>
</TEXT>
