<HEADLINE> Bulgaria Pleased with Yeltsin-Milosevic Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SOFIA, June 17 (Xinhua) -- Bulgaria on Wednesday welcomed the
pledge by Yugoslavian President Slobodan Milosevic to continue
negotiations with ethnic Albanian leaders from Kosovo, but called
for the promise to be kept.
</P>
<P>
The meeting between Russian President Boris Yeltsin and
Milosevic during his two-day visit to Moscow this week was
encouraging, Bulgarian Foreign Ministry spokesman Radko Vlaikov
said.
</P>
<P>
The next task was to implement the agreement and observe the
requirement to stop the use of force by Belgrade against Kosovo's
ethnic Albanians, the spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
Milosevic has agreed to resolve the Kosovo crisis by political
means and cease repressive action against civilians -- demands
drawn up by the Contact Group on Yugoslavia comprising the United
States, Russia, Britain, Germany, France and Italy.
</P>
<P>
The group has urged the Yugoslavian government to grant
meaningful autonomy to Kosovo and demanded progress in talks with
the ethnic Albanians who make up 90 percent of the province's
population.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman restated Sofia's commitment to carefully
monitoring the Kosovo situation and remaining in contact with its
partners in the Balkan region in a bid to find a lasting solution
to the crisis.
</P>
<P>
The conflict has been escalating since February when Serbian
police clashed with ethnic Albanians seeking independence from
Belgrade and integration into neighboring Albania.
</P>
<P>
Yugoslavia has stripped the autonomy of the ethnic Albanians
since early 1990s and strongly opposed any external intervention
into the crisis.
</P>
<P>
NATO warplanes thundered across the skies just outside
Yugoslavian airspace on Monday in a show of strength intended as a
deterrent to the use of force by the Yugoslavian government.
</P>
</TEXT>
