<HEADLINE> Chinese Scientist Calls for Legislation for Scientific Research </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 18 (Xinhua) -- Zhang Xiangshun, a prominent
Chinese scientist, has called for legislation for basic
scientific research in China.
</P>
<P>
Zhang made the call at the Second Meeting of the Standing
Committee of the Chinese People's Political Consultative
Conference, that opened here today.
</P>
<P>
Zhang, director of the Chinese Academy of Sciences'
applied mathematics research institute, said China needs to give
more support to scientific research in the way developed countries
do and should allocate more funds for the natural science
foundation, national research institutes, and university research
institutes.
</P>
<P>
China now has some 5,000 research institutes with about
700,000 people, who have long been underpaid and gotten by with
scant research funds, he said, so the country needs a law to help
institutes get adequate funding and better pay for researchers.
</P>
<P>
Cheng Jingpei, a member of the Standing Committee of the CPPCC
National Committee and vice president of Nankai University,
shared Zhang's opinion. He said that fund shortages have seriously
hampered basic scientific research at universities.
</P>
<P>
Cheng said that the government needs to put more into basic
research if it wants to keep up with global scientific and
technological development. 
</P>
</TEXT>
