<HEADLINE> Middle East Economic Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, June 18 (Xinhua) -- The following are economic briefs
from Middle East countries.
</P>
<P>
RABAT -- Morocco and Jordan have signed 13 cooperation
agreements, set up a businessman council and opened a sea route
between the ports of Casablanca and Aqaba, the Al Hayat daily
reported on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The agreements signed during a visit of Jordanian Prime
Minister Abdul-Salam Majali to Morocco concern the fields of
trade, investment, rules of goods' origin, tourism, transport,
agriculture, culture, administration, health security and consular
services.
</P>
<P>
Majali told a press conference before wrapping up his visit
Wednesday that the agreements will help form an integral Arab
market.
</P>
<P>
MUSCAT -- Investors of Oman and foreign countries are planning
to set up a factory at an estimated cost of 300 million
U.S. dollars to produce salt, the Al Hayat reported on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The project will be implemented next year in Oman's Sahar
State. A group of Swiss, French and German investors will finance
75 percent of the cost.
</P>
<P>
The factory will produce 2.4 million tonnes of crude salt and
2.1 million tonnes of refined salt every year. It is expected to
start production in April 2000 and will be ready to export salt by
January 2002.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- Egypt and Iraq have signed an agreement on cooperation
in industry, agriculture, health, communications and construction,
the Egyptian Akhbar daily reported on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Egypt has exported 103 million dollars worth of goods to Iraq
from July 1997 to March 1998 under the oil-for-food program
between Iraq and the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
Egypt's export to Iraq is estimated to reach 200 million
dollars this year.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- The Egyptian Ministry of Agriculture has decided to
carry out 15 projects in the field of food industry, the Egyptian
Alam Al Yom daily reported on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The projects include milling plants, producing bread out of
maize and olive oil of high quality, freezing and drying
vegetables and fruits.
</P>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY -- Kuwait's major economic and monetary indicators
took a downturn in the first quarter of this year, according to a
quarterly bulletin available Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The bulletin issued by the central bank said the public
revenues in the quarter stood at 2,729.1 million U.S. dollars,
976.8 million dollars less than in the last quarter of 1997.
</P>
<P>
The expenditures amounted to 3,161.4 million dollars from
January to March 1998, up 194.7 million dollars from the previous
quarter, the bulletin said.
</P>
<P>
The overall net foreign assets of central and domestic banks
remained relatively firm at the level of 6,362.4 million dollars,
3.3 million dollars below that at the end of 1997. 
</P>
</TEXT>
