<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesia to Launch Program to Raise Rice Production </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, June 18 (Xinhua) -- The Indonesian government will
immediately implement an agriculture program in a bid to increase
the country's husked rice production and reduce rice imports, a
minister said here Thursday.
</P>
<P>
"The crash program will cover 500,000 hectares of rice fields,"
Agriculture Minister Soleh Solahuddin told reporters after a
meeting with President B. J. Habibie.
</P>
<P>
The program aims to double or triple the yields of rice fields,
especially those with irrigation systems.
</P>
<P>
The Central Bureau of Statistics has announced that the year's
first harvest season will yield only 48 million tons of husked
rice, 2.5 percent less than the 51 million tons produced in the
same period last year.
</P>
<P>
The second harvest season is expected to yield even less with
43 million tons.
</P>
<P>
"The crash program aims to add at least 2 million tons to this
or match the first harvest season's 48 million tons," he said.
</P>
<P>
A further decline in forecast rice production will oblige the
country to import more rice, he said. It was reported that
Indonesia would import at least 3.1 million tons of rice this
year.
</P>
<P>
On the decline in the country's rice production, Solahuddin
said one of the factors that caused this is that farmers used up
only 28 percent of the seedlings provided by the Agriculture
Ministry.
</P>
<P>
Another factor is the lack of tractors, he said, citing that
there are only 60,000 tractors across the country, which are only
13 percent of the actual demand.
</P>
<P>
He said that of the 60,000 tractors, only about 40 percent are
functioning. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980618.0121 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton's Trip to Further Ties With China: People's Daily </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The establishment of such a partnership requires strategic and
long-term vision when reviewing and handling Sino-U.S. relations.
</P>
<P>
China and the United States are two of the world's most
influential countries. The kind of Sino-U.S. relations to be
brought into the 21st century will not only affect the immediate
interests of the two countries, but also peace and stability
of the whole world, the commentary says.
</P>
<P>
A sound and stable development of Sino-American relations can
be achieved as long as both sides keep the whole world in view and
look into the 21st century.
</P>
<P>
The establishment of such a Sino-American partnership also
requires actively seeking and expanding common ground on the part
of the two sides. China and the United States have different
social systems, but they also share extensive common interests.
</P>
<P>
The world today is not all peace. Armed conflicts erupt one
after another. The nuclear arms race in South Asia is worrisome.
As permanent members of the U.N. Security Council, China and the
United States share the same interests and responsibility in
safeguarding regional and world peace.
</P>
<P>
In such global issues as environmental protection, the war
against drugs, and international terrorism and crime, prospects
for the two countries' cooperation will expand rather than shrink,
the commentary says.
</P>
<P>
With the deepening of the economic globalization, the two
countries' cooperation to stablize Asia's economy, especially
Asia's finance, is expected to increase.
</P>
<P>
Economically speaking, China and the United States are mutually
complementary, with great potentials and bright prospects for
trade and economic cooperation.
</P>
<P>
In short, the two counties' common ground are larger than their
differences. As long as both countries adopt positive attitudes to
expand their common ground and narrow their divergences,
favorable conditions will be created for the development of
bilateral relationship.
</P>
<P>
To establish a relationship of strategic partnership, China and
the United States need to handle their differences properly. When
doing that, the principles of mutual respect and seeking common
ground while reserving differences should be observed.
</P>
<P>
There is no denying that China and the United States still hold
different opinions on such issues as Taiwan and human rights.
</P>
<P>
China has always advocated that dialogue be held in an
appropriate manner on the basis of equal consultation so as to
reduce or even iron out these differences. Those which cannot be
settled right away should be laid aside for the time being, rather
than being allowed to pose obstacles to the overall situation of
the development of China-U.S. relations, the commentary adds.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
