<BODY>
<HEADLINE> South Korea Liquidates Fifty-Five Nonviable Companies </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, June 18 (Xinhua) -- A South Korean government commission
Thursday announced a list of 55 nonviable companies, including 20
belonging to the nation's top five conglomerates, for liquidation
in the first big step toward economic restructuring.
</P>
<P>
The Financial Supervisory Commission (FSC) said that Daewoo
Group had five companies listed for liquidation, followed by
Hyundai, Samsung and LG groups each with four and SK Group with
three.
</P>
<P>
"The selection of 55 ailing companies is just the beginning of
corporate restructuring. We will continue to weed out nonviable
companies, big or small, without mercy," said the commission.
</P>
<P>
The ailing companies will be immediately cut off all fresh
loans and enter into proceedings for liquidation or takeover.
</P>
<P>
The commission said the need to restructure the industries with
overlapping investment was inevitable in order to raise
competitiveness and dispose of bad debts.
</P>
<P>
The commission's move is in line with South Korean President
Kim Dae-jung's demand for the drastic and swift restructuring of
large conglomerates, which are blamed for the ongoing financial
crisis, to be implemented.
</P>
<P>
The conglomerates are reportedly strongly opposed to the
government's attempt to arrange "big deals", which are aimed at
disposing of their unprofitable companies to raise the
competitiveness of their products in the international markets.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the government has decided to advance its bank
extension of 12 trillion won (9.2 billion U.S. dollars) in special
loans to small and medium-sized companies to prevent bankruptcies
in the financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
The commission said it will start the second selection of more
ailing companies for liquidation while speeding up disposal of the
55 firms' assets and liabilities.
</P>
<P>
Last December, South Korea signed an agreement with the
International Monetary Fund for a loan of 57 billion U.S. dollars
tied to strict conditions, including economic restructuring and
mass layoffs. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
