<HEADLINE> Major News Items In U.S. Leading Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 18 (Xinhua) -- The following are the major
news items in leading U.S. newspapers Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The Washington Post:
</P>
<P>
-- Senate Republicans Wednesday killed a national tobacco bill
championed by public health groups and the White House, ending a
grueling four-week debate.
</P>
<P>
-- President Bill Clinton has decided to nominate Bill
Richardson as energy secretary and replace him as ambassador to
the United Nations with Richard C. Holbrooke, chief architect of
the 1995 Bosnian peace agreement and one of the nation's most
aggressive diplomats.
</P>
<P>
The New York Times:
</P>
<P>
-- Faced with growing criticism of its satellite exports to
China, the Clinton Administration is rethinking whether to allow
one of the biggest sales to date, a 650 million U.S. dollar deal
President Clinton quietly approved two years ago.
</P>
<P>
-- The United States took global financial markets by
surprisely Wednesday joining Japan in buying yen to stop the
precipitous fall of the Japanese currency.
</P>
<P>
The Wall Street Journal:
</P>
<P>
-- The U.S. economy continues to grow strongly, aided by high
employment and low inflation, but the South and Southwest haven't
been keeping pace with other regions.
</P>
<P>
-- Fed Chairman Alan Greenspan and Treasury Secretary Robert
Rubin pledged to try to resolve their differences over updating
financial-services regulation to help the Senate to pass
legislation. 
</P>
