<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Housing Reform Embraces Popular Support (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
At present, there are still more than 3 million urban
households in China with a per capita living space of less than 4
square meters. They are as eager as Wang Liang to improve their
dwelling conditions.
</P>
<P>
A survey shows that 45 percent of Beijing families plan to buy
homes in the next five years, and want to get banking support.
</P>
<P>
According to Li Zigang, manager of the credit department of the
Industrial and Commercial Bank of China, the housing reform will
help improve the mortgage business of banks, which will in turn
help turn the home-buying wishes into real purchasing power.
</P>
<P>
He expects a mortgage spree will be in full swing in the fourth
quarter of this year.
</P>
<P>
In Shanghai and Fujian Province, where mortgage loan service is
considered sound, more than 80 percent of the newly built housing
has been sold to individual buyers.
</P>
<P>
Popular support for the housing reform has also been triggered
by people's discontent with the old welfare housing allocation
practice.
</P>
<P>
Under such a practice, the state can hardly recover its
investment in housing from the low rents they receive from tenants
and thus have inadequate money for new construction.
</P>
<P>
Because the supply falls short, housing allocations have to be
based on seniority and rank, thereby producing unfairness.
</P>
<P>
"Now we can buy houses with the money we earn, we feel fairer,"
said Zhang Ping, a young government employee.
</P>
<P>
Market analysts believe the crux of the matter lies in the
affordablity to ordinary home buyers. They called for the
governments at various levels to aim more for the mid- and
low-income families.
</P>
<P>
Actually, the government has already worked out the principle
of letting urban residents buy homes with 20 or 30 percent of
their income in the coming 10 to 20 years.
</P>
<P>
To win wider support, the government has also decided to
continue to provide low-rent housing to low-income families.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
