<DOCNO> XIE19980618.0135 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-18 12:53 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> FM: Turkey to Take Measures Against Any Attack </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, June 18 (Xinhua) -- Turkish Foreign Minister Ismail
Cem said here Thursday that Turkey will take and is taking all
kinds of measures in response to any attack and preparations
directed against the security of Turkey.
</P>
<P>
Cem made the remarks at a press conference concerning the
landing of four Greek F-16 fighters and a C-130 cargo plane at the
Phaphos Military Air Base in Cyprus on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Six Turkish F-16 fighters arrived at the Gecitkale Military
Air Base on the Turkish Cypriot side Thursday in retaliation for
the landing of the Greek planes in Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
"Greece will be directly liable for all the developments which
can be caused by this dangerous escalation of tension, which has
been started by the Greek side on Cyprus," said Cem.
</P>
<P>
He said that Turkey has carefully evaluated the action taken by
Greece and Cyprus, which upsets the strategical balances on Cyprus
and in the Eastern Mediterranean, adding that this kind of action
has prompted Turkey to take necessary measures.
</P>
<P>
The foreign minister stressed that the attack plans of Greece
on the Greek Cypriot side in Cyprus, the military doctrine
implemented jointly by Greece and the Greek Cypriot side and the
(Russian-made) S-300 missiles, which they try to deploy on the
island, show clearly that southern Cyprus will be a springboard in
case of a possible attack against Turkey from southern Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
"In this respect, the S-300 missiles are not an element of
defense, rather an important part of a possible attack and plan
against Turkey," added Cem.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus clinched a deal with Russia in January 1997 to buy S-300
missiles worth 40 million U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has been divided into Greek Cypriot-dominated south and
Turkish Cypriot-controlled north since 1974 when Turkish troops
landed and took over the northern third of the island in the wake
of a pro-Athens coup.
</P>
<P>
About 35,000-50,000 Turkish troops are stationed in the
northern part of the island with the claimed aim of protecting the
security of the Turkish Cypriots, who declared unilaterally in
1983 a "Turkish Republic of Northern Cyprus" there, which is
recognized only by Turkey. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
