<DOCNO> XIE19980618.0136 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Power to Be Self-supplied in S. Mozambique </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MAPUTO, June 18 (Xinhua) -- The Cabora Bassa Power Plant in
Mozambique's northern Tete Province will soon supply electricity
to the southern part of the country, Mozambican Prime Minister
Pascoal Mocumbi has said.
</P>
<P>
Mocumbi said this after he held talks with visiting Portuguese
State Secretary of Treasury and Finance Fernando Teixeira Dos
Santos, exchanging views on issues concerning the power plant,
the Noticias newspaper reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The Mozambican premier said the operation of the Cahora Bassa
electricity generation plant will not affect the domestic
institutions but instead, it will have influence on the budget
and large potential investors.
</P>
<P>
Currently, the capital city of Maputo, Gaza and Inambane
Provinces in southern Mozambique are using electricity supplied
by South Africa. For this, Mozambique has to pay 1.2 million
U.S. Dollars each month to its southern neighbor.
</P>
<P>
Mocumbi noted that after the Cabora Bassa Power Plant begins
supplying electricity to southern Mozambique, his country can
save between 800,000 and 900,000 U.S. Dollars every month.
</P>
<P>
He added that direct negotiations on payment will take place
between the two share-holders of the power plant, as Portugal
holds 82 percent of its shares while the Mozambicans have 18
percent.
</P>
<P>
A successful cooperation between the two sides on this issue
will set a good example for other cooperative projects between
the two countries, Mocumbi pointed out.
</P>
<P>
He said the Privatization of the plant is possible but it
should be carried out in the context of the integration of
southern Africa.
</P>
<P>
The Cahora Bassa Power Plant was set up in the late 1970s with
a capacity of 2.075 million kilowatts. The major buyer then was
South Africa. It was out of service for long because of civil
war.
</P>
<P>
However, the plant and its cables were rehabilitated by the
end of last year. But so far, it does not supply electricity to
South Africa due to disagreement on power prices. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
