<HEADLINE> Four Indonesian Banks Merge </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, June 18 (Xinhua) -- Four more private banks in
Indonesia, Bank Mashill, Bank Jaya, Bank Ciputra and Bank Media
are merging, the official Antara News Agency reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The four banks last Wednesday signed a memorandum of
understanding on their merger, the report quoted a statement of
Bank Mashill as saying.
</P>
<P>
The new bank is to be called Bank Mashill, with assets of more
than 3.6 trillion rupiah (240 million U.S. dollars), an equity of
536 billion rupiah (35.7 million dollars) and 129 branches across
the country.
</P>
<P>
None of the four banks had obtained liquidity support from the
central bank or has been listed under the Indonesian Bank
Restructuring Agency (IBRA), the statement said. The merger aims
to improve the banks' competitiveness by raising their liquidity
and capital to gain more customers, it added.
</P>
<P>
The Indonesian government has called on private banks in the
country to merge in a bid to improve the banking system and the
efficiency of private banks.
</P>
<P>
Indonesia has about 200 private banks and most of them are
facing financial problems. More than 10 private banks have gone
into merger since October last year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
