<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton's Trip to Further Ties With China: People's Daily </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 18 (Xinhua) -- President Bill Clinton's
forthcoming visit to China, the first by a U.S. president in 10
years, will certainly push Sino-U.S. relations forward, says a
commentary in China's leading newspaper the People's Daily on
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The commentary describes Clinton's China tour from June 25 to
July 3 as another major event in Sino-U.S. relationship following
Chinese President Jiang Zemin's successful state visit to the
United States last year.
</P>
<P>
During Jiang's visit last fall, the two leaders reached
consensus on the orientation and framework for the development of
Sino-U.S. ties, deciding to make joint efforts to establish a
constructive strategic partnership oriented toward the 21st
century.
</P>
<P>
The agreement indicated that the relationship between the two
counties has entered into a new stage of development, the
commentary says.
</P>
<P>
Since Jiang's U.S. tour, a fine momentum of development has
appeared in relations between the two countries, with exchange of
visits at high levels increased, consultations becoming more
frequent, and cooperation on bilateral and international issues
obviously enhanced, it notes.
</P>
<P>
In addition, exchange of visits by military leaders and
cooperation and exchanges in the military field have also
increased or expanded.
</P>
<P>
There has also been a steady growth in exchanges in the
economic, trade, scientific, technological, legislative,
educational, cultural and military fields. The bilateral agreement
on the peaceful use of nuclear energy has begun with a smooth
start, and the agreements and contracts on large projects signed
during Jiang's visit are being gradually implemented.
</P>
<P>
On the Taiwan issue, U.S. leaders have reiterated on several
occasions that the United States will stick to the "One-China"
policy and adhere to the principles as contained in the three
Sino-American joint communiques, not supporting the concept of
"Two Chinas" or "One China, One Taiwan," nor Taiwan's independence
or entry into the United Nations or other international
organizations composed of sovereign states, the commentary recalls.
</P>
<P>
What is more, China and the United States have also cooperated
well with one another in such major international issues as
alleviating Asia's financial crisis, the inspection of Iraqi
weapons, and India's and Pakistan's nuclear tests.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
