<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australia's Tourism Hit by Asian Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, June 18 (Xinhua) -- Australia's tourism industry was
hit by another fall in number of visitors from Asia in May, led by
an almost 80 percent plunge from South Korea, official figures
revealed Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Only 3,900 South Koreans and 3,300 Thais came to Australia in
May, down 78.5 percent and 59.3 percent respectively from the
numbers in May 1997, the Australian Bureau of Statistics (ABS)
preliminary figures show.
</P>
<P>
Tourist numbers from Southeast Asia and Northeast Asia plunged
19.6 percent and 11.3 percent respectively last month, compared
with May 1997.
</P>
<P>
Overall tourist arrivals fell by 1.8 percent to 283,900.
</P>
<P>
But there were rises in the arrivals from the United States,
New Zealand and Europe, and there was a 2.2 percent rise from
Japan, Australia's largest tourist source.
</P>
<P>
The increases went a long way towards filling the gap left by
Asia's spiraling economic downturn, the Tourism Task Force (TTF)
said.
</P>
<P>
TTF chief Christopher Brown said there were too many other
problems over which Australia had no control, like the Asian
economy, which added complications caused by independent MP
Pauline Hanson's anti-Asian immigration policies.
</P>
<P>
The Tourism Council Australia said the overall fall showed the
Asian crisis was continuing to affect the industry despite good
growth out of the United States and Europe. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980618.0141 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China to Send 53 Shooters to Barcelona Shooting Worlds </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 18 (Xinhua) -- Fifty-three Chinese shooters will
compete in the world shooting championships to be held in
Barcelona next month, Chinese head coach Zhang Heng said here on
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Olympic champions Wang Yifu, Zhang Shan and Yang Ling are among
the world championships-bound shooters, Zhang said.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese markmen and women will compete in 47 events out of
over 80 at stake in the championships slated for July 17-29.
</P>
<P>
"We aim for at least five gold medals and our main rivals will
be from Russia, Germany and Italy," the Chinese coach said.
</P>
</TEXT>
