<HEADLINE> Asian Bankers Optimistic About Regional Economy  (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 18 (Xinhua) -- Senior bankers from China,
Thailand and several other Asian nations today expressed their
confidence in the regional economy, which has been severely hurt
by a financial crisis since last July.
</P>
<P>
The overall economic foundation of Asia is good and the
financial crisis has not damaged the fundmentals for the region's
economic growth, said Dai Xianglong, governor of the People's Bank
of China, the central bank, at the 4th annual meeting of the
Association of Development and Industrial Banks in Asia (ADIBA).
</P>
<P>
"The Asian development mode still has considerable vigor," Dai
told the meeting, saying that Asia will prosper again after two or
three years.
</P>
<P>
"I believe that Asia will remain one of the economically most
dynamic places in the world in the 21st century," he said.
</P>
<P>
Abdul Aziz Mokhtar, chief executive officer of Bank Bumiputra
(Malaysia) Berhad, said Japan's economic recovery is crucial as it
will be the keystone for the recovery of the whole of the Asian
region.
</P>
<P>
"The outlook on the region may remain bleak for another year,
but as many economists believe the miracle still lies in Asia for
many years to come," he said.
</P>
<P>
The Asian financial crisis, which has snarled a number of
countries and regions including Malaysia, the Philippines,
Indonesia, Singapore, Hong Kong, the Republic of Korea and Japan,
has left a grave impact on the economy of the region, resulting in
massive currency devaluations, mounting unemployment and economic
recession.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980618.0144 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Asian Bankers Optimistic About Regional Economy  (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Some economists have pointed out that the Asian economy has
touched bottom for the first time in 20 years, with per capita
income of several countries having dropped to the level of 10
years ago.
</P>
<P>
However, the financial crisis has been largely brought under
control and the regional economy will soon recover, although
economic growth is widely expected to slow down significantly this
year, economists said.
</P>
<P>
Thailand and the Republic of Korea are now on their way to
stabilizing their currencies while Indonesia has pledged to the
International Monetary Fund to commit to the new economic reforms
signed in early April, and these developments have helped to
restore confidence in the region, they noted.
</P>
<P>
"We believe that signs of turnaround in some of the Asian
financial markets has actually begun as early as the beginning of
this year," Mokhtar said.
</P>
<P>
Also present at today's meeting were bankers from Japan, the
Republic of Korea, Malaysia, Indonesia, the Philippines, Singapore
and India.
</P>
<P>
Founded in 1995, ADIBA is an organization of policy-oriented as
well as industry-oriented financial institutions of Asian
nations. It is designed to bolster economic ties among the major
economies in Asia and thereby contribute to Asia's economic
growth. Currently, it has nine member countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
