<DOCNO> XIE19980618.0145 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Housing Reform Embraces Popular Support (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 18 (Xinhua) -- The Beijing Housing Fund
Management Center has been crowded with local residents these days
seeking consultations and filling out forms.
</P>
<P>
What they can acquire from the center is low-interest mortgage
loans they badly need to buy back from their working unit the
housing they may have lived in for decades because the ongoing
housing reform will put a halt to the 50-year-long welfare housing
allocation practice.
</P>
<P>
In cooperation with the China Construction Bank, the center has
issued more than 2,000 batches of government-subsized housing
loans since October.
</P>
<P>
"Though preconditions for requiring the loan are quite
involved, the demand is strong as well," said Li Chiying, the head
of the center. "We plan to expand the credit scale to 1 billion
yuan (120.48 million U.S. dollars) or more next year, from this
year's 600 million yuan."
</P>
<P>
Under the planned economy, government departments and state
enterprises allocate low-rent housing to their employers. Now the
reformist government wants to sell the houses to the occupants in
a bid to improve people's living standard and invigorate the
housing market. Chinese people are enchanted by the government's
slogan: "Let the people possess their own home."
</P>
<P>
Since 1998, buying a home has been considered one of the
hottest topics for Chinese urbanites, while the media have been
bombarded with housing advertisements.
</P>
<P>
This month, Wang Liang, who had been living with his parents
since marriage, bought a two-room flat in eastern Beijing with
100,000 yuan of personal savings and 200,000 yuan of
mortgage. "Owning a home gives me a real sense of independence,"
said the 30-year-old Wang, who has to pay back the loan within 20
years.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
