<BODY>
<HEADLINE> ADB Sponsors Workshop for Nepali Lawyers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, June 18 (Xinhua) -- A workshop financed by the Asian
Development Bank (ADB) for 25 lawyers from the Nepali Ministry of
Law and Justice will open here Friday, the bank said in a press
release Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The workshop, which focuses on the preparation, negotiation and
implementation of international financial transactions, is a first
step toward long-term support by ADB for institution building in
the Nepali ministry, the bank said.
</P>
<P>
It said the workshop will be led by Gabriel A. Moens, professor
of the Law School of the University of Queensland, and Martin
Klapper, a partner with the law firm of Clarke and Kann in
Brisbane, Australia.
</P>
<P>
At a preparatory meeting on Wednesday, Tirtha Man Sakya,
secretary of the Nepali Ministry of Law and Justice, highlighted
the importance of the workshop for Nepal and the need for lawyers
to receive continuous training to keep abreast of the rapid
international developments affecting Nepal.
</P>
<P>
Madhab P. Ghimire, joint secretary at the Finance Ministry of
Nepal, said this workshop is the first of its kind in Nepal and
should be viewed as a building block which will hopefully result
in tangible benefits for the administration of justice and the
Nepalese people.
</P>
<P>
Marshuk Ali Shah, resident representative of ADB in Nepal, said
that while Nepal has liberalized its trading practices in line
with international developments, the ADB is keen to support
further development of the Nepalese legal framework in which
further liberalization will take place.
</P>
<P>
The workshop is part of a project financed by the ADB which
aims to train lawyers in the Nepali Ministry of Law and Justice in
international financial agreements, international commercial
arbitration and legal data retrieval using the Internet, the bank
said.
</P>
<P>
It added that the first training session on Friday will be
followed by more in September and December. A second group of 25
lawyers will receive intensive training in legal research using
the Internet, including hands-on training using personal computers
purchased under the project, the bank said,
</P>
<P>
The ADB is financing the project under a technical assistance
grant of 150,000 U.S. dollars for capacity building of the Nepali
Ministry of Law and Justice. 
</P>
</TEXT>
