<HEADLINE> HK-Stocks HK Stocks Rebound on Intervention-Propped Yen </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, June 18 (Xinhua) -- Hong Kong stocks further jumped
by 6.39 percent to a sharply higher close Thursday as the Japanese
yen was propped up by a joint U.S. and Japanese intervention.
</P>
<P>
The key Hang Seng Index leapt 511.62 points to close at
8,515.97 after registering an intra-day high of 8,644.14 points.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. Federal Reserve and the Bank of Japan joined hands in
taking action on the battered yen on Wednesday, which was
immediately followed by a surge of the Japanese currency from 142
to 137 against the U.S. dollar.
</P>
<P>
The market's turnover on Thursday amounted to 10.353 billion HK
dollars (1.327 billion U.S. dollars), which was 4.21 billion HK
dollars (539 million U.S. dollars) more than that of Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The Hang Seng Index registered a gain of 481.28 points, or 6.01
percent, to open at 8,485.63 Thursday morning. It rose 623.16
points, or 7.79 percent, to close at 8,627.51 at midday.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong shares rose 477.9 points to close at 8,004.35 points
on Wednesday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
