<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China to Help More Unemployed Women Find Jobs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 18 (Xinhua) -- China will help 1.68 million
unemployed and laid-off women find jobs within three years,
according to an official with the Ministry of Labor and Social
Security.
</P>
<P>
The ministry plans to provide professional training for 800,000
unemployed and laid-off women each year during the 1998-2000
period, and help 70 percent of them find new jobs, said Liu Yazhi,
vice-minister of Labor and Social Security, at a symposium here
today on the follow-up actions to the Fourth World Conference on
Women.
</P>
<P>
"Chinese women are facing great pressure to keep their jobs in
textile and other light industries, which have more women
employees than men," said Liu.
</P>
<P>
The country has had an overall increase in the number of
unemployed and laid-off workers. Statistics show that, by the end
of last year, there had been 5.768 million jobless people who had
registered with their local governments, about 53 percent of whom
were women, while more than half of the 10 million laid-off
workers in China were women.
</P>
<P>
Liu said that more than 20 provinces and municipalities in
China have issued favorable policies for laid-off women to find
jobs, and special centers have been established across the country
to provide professional training and job opportunities for women.
</P>
<P>
The departments of labor and social security have also expanded
their insurance coverage for women on labor leave, with 24.8
million people benefiting from the insurance system in more than
1,200 cities and counties.
</P>
<P>
The All-China Women's Federation has also launched a project to
help the government give professional training to one million
laid-off women and provide jobs to 470,000 women.
</P>
<P>
With women accounting for 46.4 percent of the country's 696
million employed people, China is one of the countries with the
highest employment rate of women in the world. enditem
nnnn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
