<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Microsoft Introduces Theme Song for Software Campaign </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 18 (Xinhua) -- The world's largest software
producer, Microsoft, Wednesday brought out a song together with
Chinese music producers as a means to nurture the public's
awareness of "doing the right thing."
</P>
<P>
The song, titled "Lai," embodies the idea of using genuine
products while cracking down on pirate software, said Elvin Kim,
director of the Microsoft OEM (Original Equipment Manufacturer)
Sales Division. "Lai" has been chosen as the theme song for
Microsoft OEM and its copyright campaign.
</P>
<P>
"Lai" was jointly produced by Microsoft (China) Co., Ltd. and
Go East Entertainment Co., Ltd. of Hong Kong, and performed by Lao
Lang, a folk singer from the mainland, and Antony Huang, a
longtime Hong Kong pop singer.
</P>
<P>
The introduction of the song is evidence that the information
industry of China, in which Microsoft is a significant player,
places importance on utilizing various channels to promote public
awareness of copyright laws, as well as legal leverage to confront
the infringement, said an official with China's State Press and
Publications Administration.
</P>
<P>
Combining efforts from the software and music industries, both
of which are greatly concerned with copyright protection, is
creative and should be appreciated, he said.
</P>
<P>
To help promote the use of authorized software among individual
computer users, Microsoft has signed pre-installation agreements
with major Chinese personal computer manufacturers such as Legend
and Great Wall to ensure customer access to both computer name
brands and authentic Microsoft operating system software.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Microsoft has brought the Chinese market into a
global action. Microsoft OEM System Builder Program, according to
Wu Shihong, general manager of Microsoft (China), and computer
manufacturers of all sizes, hardware sellers and computer
assemblers will benefit from the authentic software promotion
program.
</P>
<P>
Industry analysts say that these moves have been helping
contain unauthorized duplication of software, and strengthening
the position of genuine products by bringing about convenient
technology support and after-sale service to customers.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
