<BODY>
<HEADLINE> World Food Program to Help Anhui's Anti-Poverty Program </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 18 (Xinhua) -- The World Food Program (WFP) of
the United Nations has agreed to provide 3.3 million U.S. dollars
worth of food to help east China's Anhui Province implement its
poverty-eradication program in the coming five years.
</P>
<P>
An agreement to this effect was signed today in Beijing between
the WFP and China's Ministry of Agriculture.
</P>
<P>
Else Larsen, WFP representative to Beijing, said the assistance
will be used in five impoverished counties in Anhui, mainly to
help local women with educational and technical training.
</P>
<P>
Some 120,000 rural households are expected to benefit from the
WFP assistance, she said.
</P>
<P>
After signing the agreement, Vice-Minister of Agriculture Wan
Baorui thanked the WFP for its donations during the last two
decades.
</P>
<P>
"China is carrying out its poverty-elimination programs and
governments of all levels have increased investment in the field
this year," he said.
</P>
<P>
Wan told Larsen that the Chinese government wants the
international organizations to continue their assistance to China.
</P>
<P>
According to official figures, since 1979 WFP has joined 60
food assistance projects in China with a total value of 780
million U.S. dollars. WFP has been the largest donor for China
among all U.N. organizations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980618.0158 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Interview: Leung Devoted to Faithful Implementation of Basic Law </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, June 18 (Xinhua) -- Having sat in the office of the
first Secretary for Justice of the Hong Kong Special
Administrative region (SAR) for nearly one year, Elsie Leung
Oi-sie felt no regret for her devotion to the public service after
giving up her 30-odd-year legal profession.
</P>
<P>
"The year after the handover is a critical period, and somebody
must come forward to do this challenging and significant job,"
said Leung, who, a new face in the secretariat-rank officials, is
the first Chinese and also the first woman to head the legal
department in Hong Kong's history.
</P>
<P>
In an exclusive interview with Xinhua, the Secretary for
Justice said the top priority on her agenda is how to faithfully
implement the Basic Law within the framework of "one country, two
systems".
</P>
<P>
When the Basic Law came into effect on July 1, 1997, Hong Kong
for the first time had a detailed written constitution. At the
same time, almost all the 600 ordinances that were in force before
the handover were adopted as laws of the SAR, except for 24 that
contravened the Basic Law.
</P>
<P>
Leung noted: "We need to go through an initial exploratory
phase for local laws to be aligned with the Basic Law, which
contains fundamental provisions rather than fine details."
</P>
<P>
She and her colleagues have enacted more than 50 pieces of
legislation since the handover, and some of them have given rise
to misconceptions, criticism and even court challenges.
</P>
<P>
"It is a healthy sign of a society established under the rule
of law," she said. "Individuals have the right to challenge laws
and procedures that they consider to be inconsistent with the
Basic Law."
</P>
<P>
"They are able to challenge the power of the government, and it
is up to the court to decide whether the government is right or
wrong," she observed.
</P>
<P>
Leung is confident that with accumulation of precedents and
wider public understanding of the Basic Law, Hong Kong will be
able to develop an authoritative body of jurisprudence.
</P>
<P>
Adoption of law is hard and meticulous work Leung and her
department have undertaken and will continue. Colonial terminology
needs to be removed from Hong Kong laws. For instance, references
to the "Governor" are replaced by references to the "Chief
Executive", and the word "Crown" is replaced by the word "State".
</P>
<P>
Leung explained: "The adoption preserves the substance of the
law and reflects the resumption of sovereignty, and the new status
of the SAR."
</P>
<P>
She continued that the "one country, two systems" concept has
given Hong Kong a high degree of autonomy and a unique status,
particularly in concluding international legal arrangements.
</P>
<P>
So far, the SAR has signed with foreign governments about 50
agreements on air services, investment protection and promotion,
the surrender of fugitive offenders, mutual legal assistance and
the transfer of sentenced persons. Negotiations on these subjects
are still going on with concerned foreign states.
</P>
<P>
The Secretary for Justice said that her duty is, through
enacting laws, to guarantee the social stability, protect the
public interests of the 6.5 million Hong Kong people, and ensure
the smooth operation of the SAR government.
</P>
<P>
She pledged to safeguard the rule of law and an independent
judiciary, the cornerstone of Hong Kong's stability and success.
</P>
<P>
Leading the Department of Justice through the SAR's first year,
Leung said: "I believe that we are moving in the right direction.
We must look forward and stand firm." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
