<DOCNO> XIE19980618.0159 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> African Ministers Discuss Science, Tech for </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, June 18 (Xinhua) -- African Ministers of Science
and Technology and private sector actors started here Thursday a
two-day dialog on importance of science and technology to African
development, particularly in the area of food security.
</P>
<P>
The two-day dialog is organized by the food security and
sustainable development division (FSSDD) of the United Nations
Economic Commission for Africa (ECA), responsible for raising
awareness on the nexus issues -- population, environment and food
security.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show while Africa's population continues to rise,
food per capita is on a steady decline. Moreover, recurrent
drought and degradation of the environment have made it an
imperative for African countries to harness new technologies to
break the vicious circle.
</P>
<P>
In his opening address, K. Y. Amoako, Executive Secretary of
the ECA, expressed the U.N. organization's support for
development of science and technology in African countries.
</P>
<P>
Amoako said ECA recently established a board-based network of
science and technology for African development and called for
active participation and partnership support as well as logical
and material backing from member states.
</P>
<P>
According to him, the ECA has already developed a number of
networks including one by FSSDD and another by the development
information services division.
</P>
<P>
The first one is a network of science and technology databases
for food security and sustainable development while the second is
the African information society initiative (AISI).
</P>
<P>
During the two-day dialog, the participants will understand
more of their perspective on the new thrust of ECA science and
technology program, raise their awareness on how global trends
and national policies affect technology development in the
private sector and exchange ideas between ministers and private
sector participants.
</P>
<P>
They will gain a perspective on the activities that the ECA
needs to undertake to address the concerns of member states, and
gain an insight into the ministers' perception on general science
and technology issues of importance to the continent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
