<HEADLINE> Kuala Lumpur Stocks Close Higher </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, June 18 (Xinhua) -- Share prices on the Kuala
Lumpur Stock Exchange closed broadly higher Thursday as sentiments
were boosted by a stronger Japanese yen against the U.S. dollar
but gains were trimmed by profit taking in the afternoon.
</P>
<P>
An analyst said the stable Japanese yen helped the local
equities market to extend its gains while news that the Malaysian
government will spend an additional 7.031 billion ringgit (about
1.793 billion U.S. dollars) on key infrastructure projects to pull
the economy out of the current economic slowdown was seen as a
positive move.
</P>
<P>
At the close, the 100-quality stock Composite Index ended 20.94
points higher at 471.82, the all-share Emas Index added 3.95
points to reach 120.81, the Industrial Index rose 33.8 points to
920.8 and the Second Board index was up 1.15 points to 104.7.
</P>
<P>
Gainers overwhelmed losers 417 to 160 with 136 counters
unchanged, 207 not traded and 23 others suspended.
</P>
<P>
The day's turnover soared to 210.331 million shares valued at
470.541 million ringgit (about 119.124 million dollars) from
132.368 million shares worth 290.435 million ringgit (about 73.527
million dollars) on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Main board volume jumped to 201.78 million valued at 456.337
million ringgit (about 115.528 million dollars) from Wednesday's
123.709 million shares worth 277.158 million ringgit (about 70.166
million dollars).
</P>
<P>
But on the second board turnover decreased to 8.551 million
shares worth 14.204 million ringgit (about 3.595 million dollars)
from 8.659 million valued at 13.277 million ringgit (about 3.361
million dollars) on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Off-market deals declined to 26.34 million shares valued at
60.859 million ringgit (about 15.407 million dollars) from
Wednesday's 73.693 million shares worth 60.68 million ringgit
(about 15.362 million U.S. dollars). 
</P>
</TEXT>
