<HEADLINE> ILO Urges Members to Abolish Child Labor </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, June 18 (Xinhua) -- The International Labor
Organization (ILO) Thursday called on all its 174 members to
promote and realize the effective abolition of child labor.
</P>
<P>
Delegates from governments, employers' organizations and trade
unions, which attended the ILO's annual conference here from June
2 to 18, discussed ways for the abolition of child labor and
included the call in the Declaration on Fundamental Principles and
Rights at Work.
</P>
<P>
In the declaration, the ILO also asked all its members, even if
they have not ratified the related conventions, to ensure the
elimination of all forms of forced or compulsory labor and the
elimination of discrimination in respect of employment and
occupation.
</P>
<P>
The ILO estimates that 250 million children between the ages of
5 and 14 in the developing countries are forced to do hard work,
of whom 61 percent are in Asia, 32 percent in Africa, and 7
percent in Latin America. 
</P>
</TEXT>
