<HEADLINE> China Welcomes Japanese, U.S. Intervention to Buy Yen </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 18 (Xinhua) -- China's central bank governor Dai
Xianglong said here today that China welcomes the move taken by
the Japanese and U.S. governments to intervene on the currency
markets to buy Japanese yen.
</P>
<P>
"We are glad to see that the exchange rate of the Japanese yen
is picking up," Dai said at the 4th annual meeting of the
Association of Development and Industrial Banks in Asia, which
opened here this morning.
</P>
<P>
The yen was quoted at 135.70-75 to the U.S. dollar in early
trading in Tokyo today after Japan intervened on the currency
markets to buy yen. The U.S. Federal Reserve also bought yen on
behalf of Tokyo, pushing the currency back from its heavy decline
during the last two weeks.
</P>
<P>
Dai reaffirmed that the Chinese yuan will not be devalued.
"It's unnecessary to do that," he said.
</P>
<P>
He said that some countries and regions in Asia are
experiencing a hard time in restructuring, and that the continued
depreciation of the value of Japanese yen would increase financial
instability.
</P>
<P>
"We welcome the move that related countries and regions will
gather in Tokyo to study measures for further stabilizing the yen,
and we hope Japan, the United States and other countries will make
continuous efforts in this respect," Dai said.
</P>
<P>
He said the Chinese government has taken a responsible attitude
toward the Asian currency crisis by maintaining a stable rate for
the Renminbi (RMB) and by giving fund support to the countries and
regions suffering from the crisis.
</P>
<P>
The economic fundamentals of Asian countries and regions remain
solid, he stressed. Within three years the region should be able
to shake off the consequences of the crisis and embark on a new
round of prosperity, he added.
</P>
<P>
Dai assured participants at the meeting that China will remain
open to development and industrial banks in Asia, and Chinese
banks will increase credit to foreign-funded enterprises both in
RMB and in foreign currency. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
