<HEADLINE> Nigeria Urged to Free Moshood Abiola </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, June 18 (Xinhua) -- The United States has Urged the
Nigerian government to immediately release Moshood Abiola,
detained politician and believed winner of the annulled June 12,
1993 presidential election, so that Abiola can contest in fresh
elections under the transition program.
</P>
<P>
Susan Rice, the U.S. Assistant Secretary of State for African
Affairs, was quoted by local media as saying this in a program on
the U.S. Public Broadcasting Corporation Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
"We have long called for his (Abiola) release and we still
think that's fundamental step along with every other prisoner in
opening up a very genuine and credible democratic process. We do
hope that he'll soon be released, and he and everybody who may
wish to compete in the upcoming election would be allowed to do
so," Rice said.
</P>
<P>
She continued: "We see positive early sign in the release of
nine political prisoners, including very prominent political
prisoners and we hope this will be followed by the release of all
political prisoners without conditions and steps must be taken to
make this transition real."
</P>
<P>
Also Wednesday, the European Union (EU) urged the Nigerian
government to take steps to resolve the case of Abiola, in a
statement by the British High Commission in Lagos.
</P>
<P>
Britain, the current president of the EU, said, "The next
important step will be the resolution of the case of Chief
Abiola..."
</P>
<P>
The release of nine political detainees, including former head
of state, General Olusegun Obasanjo, by the Nigerian government
Monday has been widely welcomed both in and outside Nigeria.
</P>
<P>
Alhaji Gidado Idris, the Secretary to the Government of the
Federation (SGF), Wednesday promised that all political prisoners
will be released, but in batches.
</P>
<P>
Moshood Abiola was widely believed to be the winner of the
1993 presidential election held under the transition to civil
rule program of the then military government of General Ibrahim
Babangida, but the election was annulled by Babangida before the
final results were out.
</P>
<P>
The political crisis caused by the annullment led to the
formation of an interim government headed by Chief Earnest
Shonekan. On November 17, 1993, General Sani Abacha took over the
power and began another transition program in October 1995.
</P>
<P>
Moshood Abiola was arrested and put into jail by Abacha on June 23,
1994, when he announced himself the president of Nigeria.
</P>
<P>
After the sudden death of Abacha on June 8, Abiola's
supporters now demand that the new government led by General
Abdulsalam Abubakar abandon the transition program of Abacha and
give the power to Abiola.
</P>
<P>
The new government said it will continue with the transition
program. 
</P>
</TEXT>
