<HEADLINE> Turkish Fighters Arrive in N. Cyprus </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, June 18 (Xinhua) -- Six Turkish F-16 fighters landed on
the Turkish Cypriot side in Cyprus on Thursday in retaliation for
Greece's landing of fighters at a air base in Cyprus, according to
the semi-official Anatolia news agency.
</P>
<P>
The agency said that the F-16 jets belonging to the Turkish Air
Force arrived at the Gecitkale military air base on the Turkish
Cypriot side Thursday morning.
</P>
<P>
Four Greek F-16 fighters and a C-130 transport plane landed on
the air base in the western coastal town of Phaphos in Cyprus on
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Immediately after the landing of the Greek planes, Turkish
Foreign Ministry Tuesday issued a statement to protest against
Greece.
</P>
<P>
The statement said that "the utilization of the air base by
Greek planes is an extremely grave and provocative development,
directed at breaking security and stability on the island in the
region."
</P>
<P>
"As a guarantor state of Cyprus, we condemn the move and
emphasize that we will take all the necessary measures that this
situation may require," the statement added.
</P>
<P>
Turkish media reports said that it is the first time that Greek
planes have landed at the air base since its completion in
January.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has been divided into Greek Cypriot-dominated south and
Turkish Cypriot-controlled north since 1974 when Turkey landed
and took over the northern third of the island in the wake of a
pro-Athens coup.
</P>
<P>
About 35,000-50,000 Turkish troops are stationed in the
northern part of the island with the claimed aim of protecting the
security of the Turkish Cypriots, who declared unilaterally in
1983 a "Turkish Republic of Northern Cyprus" there, recognized
only by Turkey. 
</P>
</TEXT>
