<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australian Oil Industry Profits Fall in 1997 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, June 18 (Xinhua) -- Net profit from Australia's oil
refining and marketing industry dived to just 81 million
Australian dollars (49 million U.S. dollars) in 1997, compared
with 358 million Australian dollars (218 million U.S. dollars) in
the previous year.
</P>
<P>
The prospects for 1998 are no better, a national survey
released in Melbourne Thursday found.
</P>
<P>
Included in the bottom line was a 79-million-U.S.-dollar stock
(working inventory) loss arising from fluctuations in the price of
crude oil over the 12 months, according to the Ernst &AMP; Young
Downstream Oil Industry Financial Survey.
</P>
<P>
The industry's employment declined further last year to 7,814
people, 29 percent lower than the 1993 tally of 10,972 workers.
Indirect employment in retail- and wholesale-related sectors also
suffered.
</P>
<P>
The survey blamed the profit decline on competitive market
conditions domestically and internationally, stock losses from
falling crude oil prices and the impact of new entrants and
imports in the Australian market.
</P>
<P>
Imports, mainly from Singapore and Thailand, were able to take
advantage of an international oversupply of gas, particularly in
the Asian region, the survey found.
</P>
<P>
The survey said the profit fall came despite lower operating
costs and stronger sales in 1997.
</P>
<P>
The survey covered the big four Australian refiner/marketeer
companies of BP, Caltex, Mobil and Shell, which account for
between 90 and 95 percent of all fuel sold in Australia.
</P>
<P>
Executive Director of the Australian Institute of Petroleum Jim
Starkey described the industry's 1997 profit performance as a
disaster, adding that falling profits could eventually force one
of the big four players to exit the Australian arena. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980618.0177 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-18 </DATE_TIME>
