<HEADLINE> German Chancellor Urges Milosevic to Keep Promise </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, June 18 (Xinhua) -- German Chancellor Helmut Kohl
Thursday called on Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic to hold
on to his promises made earlier this week to end the Kosovo crisis.
</P>
<P>
"We will wait to see with great interest and not without
scepticism whether he holds on to his promises. If it just leads
to a delay, that is unacceptable," Kohl said in a government
statement made to parliament on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The chancellor also praised Russian President Boris Yeltsin for
his efforts to seek a peaceful solution to the Kosovo conflict.
</P>
<P>
During the talks between Yeltsin and Milosevic in Moscow on
Tuesday, the Yugoslav leader offered to meet some Western demands,
including resuming political dialogue with Kosovo Albanian leaders.
</P>
<P>
Kohl noted that the European Union summit in Cardiff, Wales,
had again made concrete demands on Belgrade to cease military
action against civilians in Kosovo, to allow international
monitoring, to facilitate the return of refugees and to start a
dialogue with Kosovo Albanian leaders.
</P>
<P>
In the statement, Kohl also warned that Bonn would back a
military action if necessary.
</P>
<P>
"If these demands were not met immediately, we would have a
comprehensive catalogue of counter measures which also include a
military intervention," Kohl said.
</P>
<P>
However, he stressed that Germany supported the British
initiative to seek a preceding approval by the U.N. Security
Council to this effect.
</P>
<P>
The German chancellor also warned of a new immigration wave to
Germany in case of an escalation of the Kosovo conflict and called
on other European nations to share the possible burden. 
</P>
</TEXT>
