<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigerian Parties Suggest Extension of Transition </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, June 18 (Xinhua) -- Nigeria's five political parties
have suggested the extension of the military government's
transition to civil rule program deadline from October 1 to a
date not exceeding June 1999, local media reports said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
This is part of the recommendations the parties made to the
new leader General Abdulsalam Abubakar in their meeting in Abuja
Wednesday, which is the second of its kind since the death of
late leader General Sani Abacha last Monday.
</P>
<P>
According to Alhaji Abdullahi Magaji, the National Chairman of
the National Centre Party of Nigeria (NCPN), who spoke to
reporters after the meeting, the parties suggested that the
time-frame for the conclusion of the transition program should be
between three months to one year.
</P>
<P>
Asked if this means that the parties would not be opposed to
any move that would amount to an extension of the October 1
hand-over date, the chairman said: "The whole thing we are saying
(is that) if they hand over in a situation where you don't have a
stable polity, it is as good as not doing anything because it
will collapse.
</P>
<P>
"What Nigerians want is to ensure that what the military is
handing over is something concrete, something that will stand the
test of time, not something that will collapse after a few
months. That's what we're after.
</P>
<P>
"We are more anxious than anybody to take over from the
military. But we want to take over something that is going to be
viable," he said.
</P>
<P>
According to him, the parties also suggested the cancellation
of the results of the state and national assembly elections held
on December 6, 1997 and April 25 this year, respectively.
</P>
<P>
The two moves were reportedly opposed by the United Nigeria
Congress Party (UNCP), which won both elections by an
overwhelming majority, but the party may have been forced to
compromise.
</P>
<P>
The parties also demanded the government stopping interfering
in political affairs and sacking officials accused of doing so.
</P>
<P>
They also recommended an overhaul of the National Electoral
Committee of Nigeria "in order to remove the bad eggs there to
ensure a free and fair election," Magaji said.
</P>
<P>
The parties, however, refused the suggestions by some sectors
of the society that they should be dissolved.
</P>
<P>
"If you dissolve the parties, it will take you more time...you
will have to dissolve all the structures on the ground... which
will entail a longer period of stay for the military," he said.
</P>
<P>
The Nigerian government has promised to study the parties'
proposals critically before making decisions on the transition
program, reports said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
