<HEADLINE> China Pursues Dialogue on Human Rights Issue </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 18 (Xinhua) -- China believes that divergence on
the human rights issue can be resolved through dialogue instead of
confrontation, said Chinese Foreign Ministry spokesman Zhu Bangzao
here today.
</P>
<P>
He said that new China has placed great importance on human
rights since its founding in 1949, especially in the reform and
opening-up drive launched in the late 1970s.
</P>
<P>
He added that China has made great efforts to improve the human
rights of its people.
</P>
<P>
China also recognizes the universality of human rights, Zhu
said. "However, different countries, with different conditions,
can take their own ways to achieve the same goal of human rights,"
he said.
</P>
<P>
"It is natural that China and the United States, two nations
with different political systems, ideologies and at different
economic development levels, hold different views on this matter,"
he noted.
</P>
<P>
Zhu said that divergence on human rights can be resolved on the
basis of equality, mutual respect and non-interference in each
other's internal affairs.
</P>
<P>
On a recent report delivered by the Amnesty International on
the human rights conditions in China, Zhu said that the view held
by the Amnesty International on China has always been
"biased". "We will never accept any form of interference from
anybody in China's internal affairs," Zhu stated.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
