<HEADLINE> Australian Dollar Continues to Rise </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, June 18 (Xinhua) -- The Australian dollar closed
higher Thursday as the United States came to the rescue of the
laboring Japanese yen.
</P>
<P>
The Australian dollar received a bounce of 2 U.S. cents after
the U.S. Federal Reserve and the Bank of Japan joined hands in
lifting the yen in overnight trade.
</P>
<P>
The currency closed at 61.21 U.S. cents, from 59.24 U.S. cents
in Sydney late Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
However, traders said the yen would quickly deflate again
unless Wednesday night's foreign exchange intervention was
followed by some positive policies by the Japanese government.
</P>
<P>
The market is eagerly awaiting a meeting soon to take place
between U.S. Deputy Treasury Secretary Lawrence Summers, Japanese
finance officials and other deputy finance ministers of the G-7
nations.
</P>
<P>
"People are looking to take profits and if we don't see
anything concrete from Japan we will start to see more selling of
the yen again," a dealer said.
</P>
<P>
That would in turn be expected to flow through to the
Australian dollar and the fall of the local currency to an
all-time low of 57.1 U.S. cents was not out of the question, he
said.
</P>
<P>
The currency earlier this week touched a new 12-year low of 58
U.S. cents but stopped short of testing that level.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile on the cross rates, the Australian dollar was also
buying 83.77 Japanese yen from 84.9 yen at Wednesday's close and
at 1.0936 German marks from 1.0642 marks. 
</P>
