<HEADLINE> Major News Items in Leading French Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, June 18 (Xinhua) -- The following are major news items in
leading French newspapers on Thursday:
</P>
<P>
Liberation:
</P>
<P>
-- The French government examined on Wednesday a draft law which
will constitutionalize a parity system in participation in
government between men and women. The Socialist group at the
National Assembly has also deposed a motion which aims to adopt the
parity system in the next regional elections in 2003.
</P>
<P>
-- U.S. President Bill Clinton and Japanese Prime Minister
Ryutaro Hashimoto announced on Wednesday that they would act in
concert to stop the collapse of the Japanese yen, which was
threatening to trigger a new round of financial crisis in Asia.
</P>
<P>
Le Figaro:
</P>
<P>
-- The U.S. Federal Reserve Board decided on Wednesday to save
the Japanese yen by selling the dollar. This is the first time since
1992 when Washington intervened in the exchange market to support
the Japanese authorities. This decision marked a sudden turn of the
U.S. government, which was warried about the recession in Japan and
its consequences on the already weakened Asian economy.
</P>
<P>
-- A poll conducted in April among 12,000 people of 12 European
Union countries which will join the monetary union showed that
Germans are the most rebellious against the single currency euro,
while the Italians are the most ardent support of it. Women are
more sceptical about the single currency than men, said the poll.
</P>
</TEXT>
