<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Role Constructive in Asian Financial Turmoil, FM Spokesman </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 18 (Xinhua) -- China has played a constructive
role in curbing the financial turmoil sweeping the Asian continent.
</P>
<P>
Zhu Bangzao, spokesman of the Ministry of Foreign Affairs, made
the remark at the regular press conference here today.
</P>
<P>
"China faced risks and paid a price in the crisis," he said,
adding that it has been widely acknowledged that China has
contributed its due efforts to stabilizing the Asian financial
situation. "The Chinese government has committed itself not to
devalue the renminbi yuan and has provided 4 billion U.S. dollars
in assistance to other Asian nations," he added.
</P>
<P>
On the resurge of the Japanese yen on the international
monetary market, Zhu said that the policy adopted by some
countries could be considered as one of the main factors behind
the rebound.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that U.S. President Bill Clinton and Japanese
Prime Minister Ryutaro Hashimoto recently held talks and reached
consensus on curbing the further slide of yen. The yen was quoted
at 135.75 to one U.S. dollar in early trading in Tokyo today.
</P>
<P>
Zhu welcomed the move which he described as "necessary."
</P>
<P>
Zhu said that "the negative impact of devalued yen on the
Chinese economy is obvious for it imposed new pressure over China
and other economies in the Asian continent."
</P>
<P>
"We hope the countries concerned practically fulfill their
obligations and responsibilities and properly handle their
difficulties and problems so as to make their due contributions to
the economic stability and growth in Asia," he stated.  
</P>
</TEXT>
