<DOCNO> XIE19980618.0198 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE>   U.S. Company Begins Human Tests of Cervical Cancer Vaccine </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, June 17 (Xinhua) -- An American company has begun
the first human test of a possible vaccine against cervical
cancer, Merck &AMP; Co.'s chief scientist said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Merck &AMP; Co. has begun phase one testing of the vaccine, made of
"virus-like particles" (VLP), in women following successful
experiments in animals, said Dr. Katherin Jansen, Merck's chief
scientist.
</P>
<P>
The aim of phase one is testing the vaccine's safety in women,
she said, adding that the goal of phase two, scheduled by the end
of the year, is to see if the vaccine can produce immune cells
that kill the virus.
</P>
<P>
Merck's goal is to vaccinate girls around age 10, before they
have sexual contact that puts them at risk of catching human
papilloma virus (HPV), she added.
</P>
<P>
Merck's genetically engineered VLP can induce the immune system
to produce potent antibodies, immune cells that target and kill
the virus, Jansen explained.
</P>
<P>
Up to 40 million Americans are infected with one of 80 strains
of HPV, the nation's most common sexually transmitted virus, and
untold millions people in the world also are infected. Scientists
found that the virus is harmless to the vast majority, but a few
dangerous strains of virus can possibly cause cervical cancer.
</P>
<P>
Every year, half a million women worldwide get cervical
cancer. That includes almost 16,000 Americans, 5,000 of whom have
died, according to statistics released by the American Cancer
Society. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980618.0199 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-18 09:47 </DATE_TIME>
