<HEADLINE> Turkey Can Use Air Base in N. Cyprus: Turkish </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, June 18 (Xinhua) -- Turkey has the right to use the
air base in northern Cyprus if it wants to do so, a senior
official with the Turkish Cypriot authorities has said.
</P>
<P>
Some necessary steps should be taken (by Turkey) as a response
to the latest military movements of the Greek warplanes in the
Greek Cypriots-controlled south, Turkish Daily News quoted Dervis
Eroglu, "prime minister" of the "Turkish Republic of Northern
Cyprus" self-declared in 1983 by Turkish Cypriots, as saying
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Turkish Cypriot authorities "will allow the Turkish Air
Force's use of the Gecitkale Airport as a military base if Turkey
makes such a request," said Eroglu.
</P>
<P>
Four Greek F-16 fighters and two C-130 transport planes landed
at the newly completed air base near the western town of Paphos on
the divided island on Monday and Tuesday, prompting strong
protests from Ankara and Turkish Cypriots.
</P>
<P>
"Reciprocal steps should be taken, and will be taken," Eroglu
said.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that Turkish Cypriots were ready to solve the
differences with Greek Cypriots through negotiations, but at the
same time were determined to face all unexpected changes.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has been divided into Greek Cypriot-dominated south and
Turkish Cypriot-controlled north since 1974 when Turkish troops
landed and took over the northern third of the small island
following a pro-Athens coup.
</P>
<P>
The "Turkish Republic of Northern Cyprus" is recognized only
by Turkey.


18/06/98 9:47 GMT

NNNN
17:53 17:53 g # PAB
</P>
