<HEADLINE> Work Begins on Rebuilding Noted Lamasery in Inner Mongolia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HUHHOT, June 18 (Xinhua) -- China has begun work to rebuild the
Wu Dang Monastery, a Tibetan-style complex in Baotou, Inner
Mongolia Autonomous Region.
</P>
<P>
The monastery, first built in the 17th century, was damaged to
some extent during an earthquake three years ago. Right after the
quake, the Chinese government dispatched specialists for field
investigations, and later worked out a rebuilding project.
</P>
<P>
The rebuilding project is expected to cost 4 million yuan
(482,000 U.S. dollars), and Jiang Huaiying, a noted designer with
the China Relics Research Institute, has been invited to be the
chief designer. Jiang was responsible for renovations to the
Potala Palace in Lhasa, Tibet, and Angkor Wat, Cambodia.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980618.0203 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Terra Cotta Warriors Attract 100 Heads of State (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Former U.S. Secretary of State Henry Kissinger praised the
terra cotta army as the only treasure of its kind in the world,
and former Vice-President Walter Mondale recommended that people
throughout the world visit to see for themselves.
</P>
<P>
Former U.S. presidents Jimmy Carter and Richard Nixon visited
the museum in 1981 and 1985 respectively. Nixon compared the
awesomeness of terra cotta figurines to the Great Wall.
</P>
<P>
Ronald Reagon became the first incumbent U.S. president to
visit the museum in April, 1984. Reagon was accompanied to the
museum by an entourage of over 600 staffers and reporters.
</P>
<P>
He exhibited great curiousity and requested permission to touch
a figurine. Reagon stroked the tail of a nearby horse and suddenly
withdrew to humorously question whether or not the "horse" would
kick.
</P>
<P>
He approached a headless terra cotta warrior and jokingly
suggested his head would look good on the figurine. Reagon
approached closer on to find that the figurine was much taller.
</P>
<P>
Just prior to leaving, Reagon turned to the "warriors" and
barked the command -- "Dismiss!"
</P>
<P>
The "warriors and horses" became the rage of the western world
as a result of Reagon's humorous improvizations, and the number of
tourists visiting the attractions has since grown by 20-30 percent
annually.
</P>
<P>
The museum has also displayed the "warriors and horses" in 20
countries, attracting well over 10 million people. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980618.0204 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Terra Cotta Warriors Attract 100 Heads of State (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XI'AN, June 18 (Xinhua) -- Over 40 million people from both at
home and abroad have viewed the terra cotta warriors and horses,
the "underground army" of China's first emperor, since the
attraction opened to the public in 1979.
</P>
<P>
The visitors have included more than 100 heads of state and
government, according to the figures released by the Museum of
Terra Cotta Warriors and Houses, located 37 kilometers east of
Xi'an. The museum houses over 7,000 life-sized terra cotta
warriors and horses unearthed since 1974, along with tens of
thousands of pieces of weaponry.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that the museum ranks second after Beijing's
Palace Museum, or the Forbidden City, in terms of the number of
visitors.
</P>
<P>
Known as the eighth miracle in the world, the terra cotta
warriors and horses were made over 2,200 years ago during the Qin
Dynasty (221 BC -- 207 BC). The purpose of lifelike "soldiers and
horses", located less than a mile from the emperor's tomb, was to
maintain and protect the living glory for time immemorial.
</P>
<P>
Qin Shihuang was the first man to unite China. He founded
the Qin Dynasty and assumed the name "Shihuang", a Chinese word
meaning first emperor.
</P>
<P>
The "most splendid archeological finding" in this century was,
in fact, accidentally discovered in 1974 by a local farmer while
he was digging a well.
</P>
<P>
The museum housing the terra cotta treasures opened to the
public on October 1, 1979.
</P>
<P>
The world first learned of the terra cotta warriors and horses
from an unprecedented 17-page story carried in the April 1978
issue of National Geographic. During a September visit that
year, Paris Mayor and future French President Jacques Chirac
referred to them as "the eighth miracle in the world" equal
to Egyptian pyramids.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980618.0205 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> First Automobile Works Develops New Natural Gas Engine </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHANGCHUN, June 18 (Xinhua) -- China's First Automobile Works
(FAW) recently introduced a new series of natural gas engine
components for urban shuttle buses and heavy-duty vehicles.
</P>
<P>
The new CA6102N engine components, the first of their kind in
China, will greatly improve power generation systems on refitted
buses, with the motive power index basically reaching levels for
gasoline-fired vehicles.
</P>
<P>
Refitted buses fueled with natural gas, or so-called "Green
vehicles" which have not as yet been refitted with replacement of
engines, operate with 20 percent power reductions when compared to
gasoline-fired vehicles.
</P>
<P>
Retrofitting automobiles with natural gas engine components is
a major part of China's efforts to curb urban pollution. China had
4,600 vehicles equipped for natural gas by the end of 1997.
</P>
<P>
FAW initiated research of the engine components in 1992 and
their introduction is expected to significantly reduce production
costs and emission levels.
</P>
<P>
Company officials noted that the engine components can also be
adapted to LPG and gasoline-fired vehicles. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980618.0206 </DOCNO>
