<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Boosts Flourishing Campus Industries to Support Schools </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 18 (Xinhua) -- The lack of educational funding
has forced China's one million middle and primary schools to
develop campus industries as a self-supply channel.
</P>
<P>
So far, 738,000 school enterprises have been established
nationwide. Their output reached 120 billion yuan (14.5 billion
U.S. dollars) last year, with most of the profits used to make up
insufficient educational funding, the Ministry of Education
revealed today.
</P>
<P>
The investment problem has long been hindering the development
of China's educational sector, according to the ministry. The
central government's educational allocation was 160 billion yuan
(19.3 billion U.S. dollars) in 1996, accounting for less than 3
percent of the gross domestic product.
</P>
<P>
Middle and primary schools, which have 200 million students and
the main part of China's educational system, are faced with
extremely great challenges, according to the ministry.
</P>
<P>
Many schools have to seek various ways to raise funds. In some
middle and primary schools, half of their funding is collected by
running factories and carrying out other social activities.
</P>
<P>
Campus enterprises have been engaged in a wide range of
industries such as computers, machinery, food, drink, clothing and
entertainment, and some of the firms are foreign-invested joint
ventures.
</P>
<P>
Most of the enterprises are small- or medium-sized, but there
have already been 29 big companies able to make profits of more
than 10 million yuan (1.2 million U.S. dollars) each.
</P>
<P>
Ministry officials said that children are not allowed to work
in campus enterprises, and the firms' operations have not
disrupted classroom activities. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980618.0209 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Key to China's Summer Grain Harvests </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XI'AN, June 18 (Xinhua) -- China is looking forward to another
good summer grain harvest, and the plastic sheeting technique has
played a role.
</P>
<P>
Shaanxi, Shandong and Henan provinces, for example, expect to
reap 1.5 billion kilograms of wheat on 330,000 hectares of
farmland, using the technique.
</P>
<P>
By using the new cultivation technique, farmers can reap 1,500
kilograms of wheat per hectare more than otherwise.
</P>
<P>
China imported the method in the 1970s and has expanded its
application to growing vegetables, corn, rice and other crops. In
1994, the country began to use it on wheat fields with good
results.
</P>
<P>
Last year, the Ministry of Agriculture increased efforts to
spread the use of the technique. As a result, the acreage rose
sharply to nearly 600,000 hectares this year involving 14
provinces, autonomous regions and municipalities.
</P>
<P>
The new practice also brings 1,500 yuan more per hectare to
growers, and has proven especially effective in fighting drought
in north China, agronomists said.
</P>
<P>
The farmland that is good for this wheat cultivation method in
north China totals 10 million hectares. And if the technique is
applied on 1.33 million hectares of wheat by the end of the
century, it could add two billion kilograms to the nation's wheat
production, said Shi Zhicheng, deputy president of the Chinese
Association of Agro-Science Societies. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
