<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Shanghai Fixed Asset Investments Fall 10 Percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, June 18 (Xinhua) -- Fixed asset investments for
Shanghai, China's major economic and financial center, fell by
nearly 10 percent for the first five months of this year.
</P>
<P>
Official statistics show the city's fixed asset investments
totaled 39.26 billion yuan for the January-May period, down 9.8
percent on the 1997 period.
</P>
<P>
A further breakdown shows that investments in technical
renovation projects dropped nearly 30 percent to 7.06 billion yuan
during the period, with investments in basic construction falling
4.8 percent to 18.4 billion yuan.
</P>
<P>
Analysts attribute the significant slowdown for investments in
technical renovation to sluggish demand and sales, as well as the
poor performance of state-owned enterprises.
</P>
<P>
Statistics indicate the number of loss-making state-owned
enterprises in Shanghai jumped from 630 to 804 during the
January-April period.
</P>
<P>
However, negative growth trend for investments in urban
infrastructure reversed during the first five months, with the
total volume rising by 3.4 percent to 9.84 billion yuan.
</P>
<P>
industrial investments rose slightly to 13.56 billion
yuan and investments in real estate fell by 6.1 percent to
8.62 billion yuan.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
