<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Japan's Trade Surplus Rises Sharply in May </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, June 18 (Xinhua) -- Japan's merchandise trade surplus in
May surged by 66.6 percent from a year earlier to 1,219.3 billion
yen (about 9.3 billion U.S. dollars), thanks mainly to a sharp
import decline, the Finance Ministry said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Japan's imports in May fell by 16.3 percent from a year before,
the largest since February 1987, when imports posted a 28.3
percent monthly decline, the ministry said.
</P>
<P>
Japan's exports in May edged down by 1.5 percent from the
previous year to 4,041.9 billion yen (about 30.6 billion dollars)
for the second straight month of decline, while imports came to
2,822.6 billion yen (about 21.3 billion dollars), down for the
fifth consecutive month.
</P>
<P>
Japan's surplus with the United States surged by 41.0 percent
from a year earlier to 455.4 billion yen (about 3.4 billion
dollars), up for the 20th consecutive month, the ministry said.
</P>
<P>
Japan's surplus with Asian countries fell by 28.3 percent,
while that with the European Union jumped by 94.2 percent from a
year earlier.
</P>
<P>
The average foreign exchange rate used for the May report was
132.29 yen to the U.S. dollar, compared with 124.09 yen a year
earlier.
</P>
<P>
On the future trend, an economist at a private financial
institution said Japan's trade surplus would continue to grow at
least for one year, as the yen has much depreciated against the
dollar. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
