<DOCNO> XIE19980618.0218 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Xinjiang Attracts Investment to Reclaim Wasteland </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
URUMQI, June 18 (Xinhua) -- Xinjiang Uygur Autonomous Region in
the Northwest, possessing 10 million hectares of arable wasteland
which accounts for one-third of China's total, has become a magnet
for investors in the reclamation of wasteland.
</P>
<P>
An official of the autonomous region said that, in addition to
a large investment by the central government in the past decade,
about 3 billion yuan (361 million US dollars) has been drawn for
reclaiming wasteland in Xinjiang, which resulted in an increase of
600,000 hectares of farmland.
</P>
<P>
A survey by the regional land administration department in
Xinjiang shows that there are 12 investment forms in reclaiming
land. Among them are developing the state-owned cotton base,
comprehensive agriculture, and agriculture cooperation among
interior provinces and regions.
</P>
<P>
Statistics also show that since the contracts on forming cotton
and beet bases were signed in 1988, China has put in 2.47 billion
yuan (297.6 million US dollars) to reclaim 300,000 hectares of
wasteland in Xinjiang.
</P>
<P>
From 1996 on, 18 provinces and cities, as well as Hong Kong,
have signed agreements for 128 projects to reclaim wasteland in
Xinjiang for 1.97 billion yuan (237 US dollars) involving 120,000
hectares of wasteland.
</P>
<P>
Incomplete statistics show that more than 10,000 peasant-farmer
families in the autonomous region each possessed more than 10
hectares of arable land through reclaiming wasteland at a cost of
more than 100 million yuan (12 million US dollars).
</P>
<P>
Through 1997, there had been 105 non-agriculture companies
involved in reclaiming arable wasteland in Xinjiang.
</P>
<P>
A autonomous region official underlined that high return rates
are the main reason for attracting investors. Xinjiang was given a
series of preferential policies by the central government, as well
as being listed as the state's largest cotton production center.
</P>
<P>
In the past decade, 560,000 hectares of wasteland in Xinjiang
has been reclaimed, local officials said. Further efforts will
also be taken for environmental protection during the activities
to reclaim wasteland in Xinjiang. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
