<DOCNO> XIE19980618.0219 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 17 Kenyans Die, 40 Hurt in Road Crash </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, June 18 (Xinhua) -- Seventeen people were killed and
at least 40 others injured when two buses crashed head on in
central-western Kenya, local press reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Among them fifteen died instantly on the scene, including the
two bus drivers, according to the report by the Daily Nation
newspaper.
</P>
<P>
The survivals narrowly escaped death soon afterwards when a
runaway tanker slammed into a breakdown lorry called to the
scene, sending it careering into one of the wrecked buses.
</P>
<P>
It also hit a police Land Rover into which bodies from the
original accident had been loaded for the journey to the
mortuary.
</P>
<P>
The buses collided after one of them swerved into the path of
the other while trying to avoid a lorry which had broken down in
the middle of the road. Police said the driver of the stalled
lorry had disappeared.
</P>
<P>
The force of the collision sent one of the buses flying off
the road and through a muddy ditch before it finally stopped.
</P>
<P>
The accident happened on a hilly section of the Nakuru to
Eldoret highway, 48 kilometers from the Nakuru town, which is
Kenya's fifth biggest city.
</P>
<P>
Although the crash was on Tuesday night, three passengers were
still trapped in the buses the following morning on Wednesday.
And it took the police about 14 hours to remove the bodies.
</P>
<P>
Rift Valley Provincial Traffic Enforcement Officer Duke Okemwa
said it is the worst road accident in the area in recent years.
</P>
</TEXT>
