<HEADLINE> China to Loosen Controls on Infrastructure Financing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 18 (Xinhua) -- A senior banking official said
here today that, with the progress of China's market-oriented
economic reforms, the financing of infrastructure and basic
industries will be increasingly diversified.
</P>
<P>
Yao Zhongmin, vice-governor of the State Development Bank (SDB)
of China, told the 4th annual meeting of the Association of
Development and Industrial Banks in Asia that the Chinese
government will further relax its monopoly and control over
investment in infrastructure and basic industries, which will draw
more social funds into financing activities.
</P>
<P>
Government financial fund investment and policy bank credit
financing will continue to play important roles, Yao said, and the
proportion of project direct financing will be further increased.
</P>
<P>
Yao said that presently the proportion of direct financing in
the entire infrastructure and basic industries is low.
</P>
<P>
"Some production enterprises in infrastructure and basic
industries with high economic returns can raise capital through
joint-stock company restructuring and issuance of shares, or raise
funds through issuing enterprise bonds and conducting project
financing abroad," he said.
</P>
<P>
The upcoming industrial investment fund will become a low-cost
fund-raising tool for China's infrastructure and basic industries,
he said, and foreign capital utilization will be further
reinforced.
</P>
<P>
The SDB is mainly involved in fixed-asset lending activities
and guaranteeing funding for key state construction projects. The
SDB plays an important role in promoting China's infrastructure
and basic industrial development, he said.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that since the SDB was established in 1994 it
has raised 360 billion yuan for 643 key construction projects.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese government has announced its plan of investing 1
trillion U.S. dollars in the coming three years in infrastructure
and basic industries, indicating that the country's infrastructure
and basic industries will have a fairly rapid development period.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
