<HEADLINE> Wall Street Economists: Moderate Growth for U.S. in 1999 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, June 17 (Xinhua) -- Wall Street economists believe
that the U.S. economy will grow at a moderate and smooth pace in
1999, a survey conducted by Bank of America said on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
In the mid-year assessment of the U.S. economy in 1999, the
consensus view of 18 Wall Street economists is that gross domestic
product will down-shift to a modest, sustainable growth rate of
2.5 percent next year from a projected growth rate of 3.4 percent
in 1998, the San Francisco-based bank said.
</P>
<P>
The panel also believes that inflation will pick up somewhat to
a rate of 2.3 percent in 1999 from 1.6 percent this year. The
growth rate of consumer disposable income will fall to 2.8 percent
next year from 3.8 percent in 1998.
</P>
<P>
Individual estimates of real economic growth in the United
States in 1999 vary widely, said the bank, with forecasts ranging
from a low of 1.7 percent to a high of 3.5 percent. Opinions about
the impact of the Asian economic crisis on the U.S. economy and
the likelihood of continued strength in consumer spending in the
country also vary substantially among the economists.
</P>
<P>
In fact, the bank said, there seem to be two camps forming
among the panel. One is a pro-growth group believing that the
economy will pick up considerable speed in the coming months,
which would force the Federal Reserve to move rates upward to
brake the growth and keep inflation in check. The other camp of
economists thinks that the economy still has plenty of resiliency,
but is expected slow in 1999 to a sustainable pace in the 2
percent to 2.5 percent range, with an inflation rate of about 2.5
percent.
</P>
<P>
According to the panel, there is a 33 percent probability that
the U.S. economy will be growing moderately one year from now. The
probability that the economy will be slowing down by next June is
likely at about 32 percent.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the panel believes there is only a 19 percent
probability that the U.S. economy will be booming a year out. The
chances of a stagnating economy accompanied by rising inflation by
next June have been assigned to a 16 percent probability. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
