<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe Has 230,000 Fixed Telephone Lines </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, June 18 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwe's Posts and
Telecommunications Corporation (PTC) has so far provided some
230,000 conventional telephone lines countrywide, Information,
Posts and Telecommunications Minister Chem Chimutengwende has
said.
</P>
<P>
The minister told the Zimbabwe News Agency Wednesday that the
government was working to ensure that it increased telephones to
a stage where services could be supplied on demand.
</P>
<P>
"There is a current PTC program which will ensure another
250,000 lines by the year 2002 but that will still not fully
satisfy projected demand," he said.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that the government was still looking for a
strategic partner for PTC to help in the partial privatisation
process.
</P>
<P>
"People have misunderstood and think we have already found a
partner for PTC. That is not correct," he said. 
</P>
