<HEADLINE> Backgrounder: World's Longest Ancient City Wall </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XI'AN, June 18 (Xinhua) -- The world's longest extant ancient
city wall is located in the northwest China city of Xi'an, which
was the world's largest metropolis some 1,000 years ago.
</P>
<P>
The wall, which stretches 13.7 kilometers, has attracted over
eight million tourists since 1984, with a long list of foreign
dignitaries including the Japanese Emperor. Xi'an, the seat of
Shaanxi Provincial government, is the major economic and cultural
center in northwest China.
</P>
<P>
The city wall, which enclosed the ancient capital city, is now
at the center of the ever-expanding metropolitan area. Tourists
strolling along the massive wall 12 meters high and 14 meters wide,
have an unobstructed view of the so-called "city inside a city,"
as well as many scenic sites found outside.
</P>
<P>
The municipal government has won praise for its extensive
efforts to maintain and protect the ancient wall. The
vice-president of an American Urban Planning Society noted that
the strategic step centers on bringing new life to the ancient
legacy by ensuring its protection and constructive use.
</P>
<P>
The United Nations Educational, Scientific and Cultural
Organization experts designated the wall as a World Cultural
Heritage in 1994. 
</P>
</TEXT>
