<HEADLINE> Iranian Foreign Minister Leaves for Spain </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, June 18 (Xinhua) -- Iranian Foreign Minister Kamal
Kharrazi left here for Spain early Thursday on his first visit to
a member state of the European Union (EU) following the EU's
decision to resume ministerial contacts with Iran.
</P>
<P>
Tehran radio said that Kharrazi would hold talks with his
Spanish counterpart Abel Matutes on bilateral ties and future
dialog between Iran and the EU.
</P>
<P>
The Iran-EU relations soured after a Berlin court ruled in
April 1997 that Iranian leadership was behind a 1992 killing of
the country's rebel Kurdish leaders.
</P>
<P>
The ties between Iran and the 15-member organization were
normalized last November when EU members' ambassadors returned to
Tehran. The EU also decided to resume exchange of ministerial
visits and "critical dialog" with Iran.
</P>
<P>
With the diplomatic warming-up, EU politicians, industrialists
and businessmen are rushing to Iran in recent months to seek ways
of cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Early this month, Vice President of the Spanish Congress of
Deputies Enrique Fernadez Miranda visited Iran and held talk with
Iranian Majlis (Parliament) Speaker Ali Akbar Nateq-Nouri and Vice
President Masoumeh Ebtekar.
</P>
<P>
During his visit, Miranda voiced Spain's readiness to
cooperate with Iran in carrying out research in environmental
protection and ecosystem.
</P>
<P>
The annual trade volume between Iran and Spain stands at
1.6 billion U.S. dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
