<HEADLINE> Tibet Taps Cultural Resources to Promote Tourism </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LHASA, June 18 (Xinhua) -- The Tibet Autonomous Region is
tapping its unique natural and cultural resources to promote the
development of its tourism industry.
</P>
<P>
The region's tourism development plan for the Ninth Five-Year
Plan Period (1996-2000) and the Long-Range Development Objective
call for expanding investment channels for foreign, collective and
individual investors.
</P>
<P>
Tourism services have emerged as one of Tibet's five pillar
industries over the past 18 years.
</P>
<P>
Over 540,000 overseas tourist visiting the region during the
period have provided earnings totalling 1.28 billion yuan and 200
million U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
A Regional tourism Administration official said that Tibet has
tapped both natural and cultural resources to promote the
development of tourism services.
</P>
<P>
Tibet has expanded tourism to 10 cities and counties, 46
mountain peaks, 24 cultural and relic sites and more than 100
sightseeing areas centered on Lhasa, the regional capital, Xigaze
and Shannan Prefecture.
</P>
<P>
The region also offers a series cultural festivals, including
the Xodoin Festival which features feasting on koumiss and
drinking mare's milk with wine, the Yalong Cultural Festival
and Qiangtang Horsemanship Festival.
</P>
<P>
Tibet, a region with abundant unique natural and cultural
resources, also plans to introduce special tourism programs
centered on scientific expeditions in primitive forests, mountain
climbing adventures and Buddhist pilgrimage tours.
</P>
<P>
Tang Zhengqi, director of the Regional Tourism Administration,
said the central and regional government have invested over 200
million yuan in infrastructure construction projects which include
communications and telecommunications facilities, airports and
hotels.
</P>
<P>
The central government and various provincial and municipal
governments have provided massive funding for 62 construction
projects in the region, said Tang, adding that the projects
scheduled for completion in the near future will provide greater
convenience for foreign tourists travelling to Tibet. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
