<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kenyan Central Bank Stops Further Lending to Govt </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, June 18 (Xinhua) -- The Central Bank of Kenya (CBK)
has stopped any further lending to the government which is said
to have reached the maximum borrowing ceiling.
</P>
<P>
"From now on there is no borrowing by the government from the
bank because we have given out the maximum of seven billion
Shillings (about 1.16 billion U.S. Dollars) allowable under the
Banking Act," CBK Chief Banking Manager Reuben Marambii said.
</P>
<P>
Legally, the maximum borrowing from CBK by the Kenyan
government is pegged at five percent of the annual gross revenue
collected, which it has already taken up, Marambii was quoted by
Thursday's East African Standard newspaper as saying.
</P>
<P>
The five percent limitation was revised downward from the
original six percent during the 1998/99 budget by Finance
Minister Simeon Nyachae who introduced far-reaching changes in
the Banking Act.
</P>
<P>
The CBK action means the government will now not have access
to quick cash whenever urgent need arises, according to the
report.
</P>
<P>
The only options available to the government to raise cash is
to increase the sale of Treasury Bills and Bonds, raise tax or
make drastic cuts in expenditure, said the report.
</P>
<P>
However, the Treasury Bills option appears costly, especially
for the short-term maturing ones.
</P>
<P>
Already, as articulated in the 1998/99 budget, the government
intends to phase out the Treasury Bonds having accumulated a
domestic debt of over 150 billion Shillings (about 2.5 billion
U.S. Dollars).
</P>
<P>
The government now is finding this debt difficult to service
as it attracts interest of over 25 percent, the report commented.
</P>
<P>
On the fears that the parliament might at the behest of the
government change the new banking rules to allow it to borrow
more, Marambii said that would be difficult.
</P>
<P>
"It is however, up to members of parliament to genuinely prove
they want to see a recovery in this economy by not engaging in
activities that encourage financial indiscipline," he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
