<HEADLINE> Share Prices Rise Sharply in Tokyo as Yen Recovers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, June 18 (Xinhua) -- Stock prices rose sharply in Tokyo
Thursday with the key Nikkei index posting the second biggest gain
of the year on yen's dramatic recovery in response to joint
intervention by monetary authorities in the currency markets.
</P>
<P>
The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues on the First
Section of the Tokyo Stock Exchange jumped 646.16 points, or 4.39
percent, from Wednesday's close to finish at 15,361.54.
</P>
<P>
The broader-based Tokyo Stock Price Index (TOPIX), covering all
First Section issues, rebounded 42.00 points or 3.63 percent to
1,198.84.
</P>
<P>
Turnover on the major section increased to an estimated 680
million shares from Wednesday's 405 million shares.
</P>
<P>
Long-Term Credit Bank of Japan (LTCB) was the day's most heavily
traded issue.
</P>
<P>
Overnight yen-supportive intervention by the United States and
Japan turned around the recently deadlocked situation in Tokyo
financial markets, traders said.
</P>
<P>
Buying expanded across the board, with bank, real estate and
brokerage issues leading the way, they said.
</P>
<P>
Tokyo market participants now believe another Asian financial
crisis stemming from lower Tokyo stocks and a weak yen can be
avoided, they added.
</P>
<P>
Of the 1,335 issues listed on the First Section, gainers
overwhelmed losers 1,076 to 62, with 35 issues remaining
unchanged. 
</P>
</TEXT>
