<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe's Export Processing Zones Get Good </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, June 18 (Xinhua) -- Companies operating in Zimbabwe's
export processing zones have created more than 6,000 new jobs and
generated over 27 million U.S. Dollars in export earnings since
the concept was introduced 18 months ago.
</P>
<P>
At least 38 companies investing 27 million U.S. Dollars are
fully operational while a further 36 are still to implement their
projects, The Herald daily reported Thursday, adding that all the
approved projects are valued at 270 million U.S. Dollars, but a
more welcoming climate could speed investment significantly.
</P>
<P>
Elias Ngugama, chairman of the export processing zones
authority, told the newspaper Wednesday that his organization had
so far received more than 150 applications and was processing an
average of two projects every two weeks.
</P>
<P>
"We are pleased with the projects' take-off. The program has
made a dramatic contribution to the creation of employment and in
value-adding," he said.
</P>
<P>
The export zone companies produce mainly for export. They are
allowed to sell a maximum of 20 percent of their production to
the domestic market while the balance is targeted for the export
market.
</P>
<P>
The concept was introduced in Zimbabwe 18 months ago to
spear-head the country's export drive and subsequently promote
national economic growth.
</P>
<P>
Ngugama said the current economic problems were stifling
investment into the zones.
</P>
<P>
"The high interest rates are discouraging investment. The
investors prefer the money markets where they get good returns,"
he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
