<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zambia's Mayors Still to be Elected Indirectly </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, June 18 (Xinhua) -- Zambia's mayors will still be
elected indirectly in the forthcoming local government elections
contrary to an announcement made last year, according to Zambia
Daily Mail Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The newspaper published here quoted Election Commission
Chairman Judge Bobby Bwalya as saying here Wednesday that the
Local Government Amendment Act passed through parliament recently
does not provide for the direct election of the mayors by all the
electorate of a city.
</P>
<P>
He said if the practice has to be implemented, the law will
have to be changed before the local government polls take place.
</P>
<P>
Currently the mayor is elected from an electoral college made
up of councillors elected in the local government polls.
</P>
<P>
"The mayor, deputy mayor, chairman or vice chairman of a
council shall be elected annually at the first meeting of
September in that year," the act stipulates.
</P>
<P>
Judge Bwalya said the Electoral Commission has not received
any instruction to prepare for a mayoral poll.
</P>
<P>
Last year President Frederick Chiluba announced that the
government would introduce a system in which mayors would be
directly elected by the people.
</P>
<P>
Chiluba said that the move was aimed at making the local
government system more accountable to the people.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
