<HEADLINE> New Animal Species Discovered in Three Gorges Area </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 18 (Xinhua) -- More than 40 new wild animal
species have been discovered in the Three Gorges Area in recent
years, according to a survey by the State Environmental Protection
Administration (SEPA).
</P>
<P>
The list includes 12 mammal species, 21 bird species, six
species of reptiles and five species of amphibians.
</P>
<P>
The 1997 survey lists more than 360 species of land vertebrates
in the Three Gorges Area, including 81 mammal species, 236 bird
species, 23 reptile species and 27 species of amphibians.
</P>
<P>
Four species in the area are under special state protection --
golden monkeys, the clouded leopards, the spotted leopards
and the golden eagles. Other protected species discovered during
the survey included rhesus monkeys and pangolins.
</P>
<P>
The survey revealed that the golden monkey mainly lives at the
juncture of Badong County in central China's Hubei Province and
the Shennongjia Forest Area. Experts estimate that some 200 golden
monkeys live in the area.
</P>
<P>
SEPA said the animals will be affected somewhat by the new
reservoir on the Yangtze River. but noted that human activities
pose the major threat to wild animal diversity in the Three Gorges
Area.
</P>
<P>
"Human activities such as lumbering and hunting will affect
biodiversity more than the reservoir," according to the
administration.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980618.0249 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Recruits Poverty-Relief Volunteers Among Urban Youth </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 18 (Xinhua) -- China's urban young people were
called on today to give up their comfortable lives and high
incomes to spend some time in poverty-stricken areas to assist
local educational, scientific, cultural and medical development.
</P>
<P>
People's Daily, China's leading newspaper, carried a huge
advertisement Wednesday, recruiting college-educated volunteers
between 18 and 35 in large and medium cities to go to impoverished
areas for one or two years.
</P>
<P>
The ad said young people could benefit a lot from hard work in
the poverty-stricken areas and could learn how to be steadfast in
the future.
</P>
<P>
In the 1960s and '70s, large numbers of Chinese urban youth
were urged to go to the countryside to engage in physical labor
and receive "re-education" from the farmers.
</P>
<P>
However, the young volunteers with new concepts and good
education from large cities today can offer urban culture, new
thoughts and hope for prosperity to the poverty-stricken areas.
</P>
<P>
The Communist Youth League of China, the initiator of the
poverty-relief plan, promised that they would pay the cost of
living for volunteers who have no income and offer health care and
life insurance during their service period.
</P>
<P>
The Youth League, with a membership of nearly 70 million,
started a project in 1993 calling on young volunteers to provide
various services for society. More than 40,000 young people have
participated in the project since then.
</P>
<P>
Different from part-time volunteers, those participating in the
poverty-relief plan will give up their jobs and change their way
of life for one or two years, said an official of the Youth League.
</P>
<P>
He added that the pattern of open recruitment and rotating at
regular intervals is in line with international practice. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
