<DOCNO> XIE19980618.0250 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mozambique Claims to Have Most Stable Currency </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MAPUTO. June 18 (Xinhua) -- Mozambique claims to have the most
stable currency in the last ten years during which the country
has been embarking on a market economy.
</P>
<P>
According to Bank of Mozambique, the central bank, the
country's currency Metical has remained on a 11543 to 11733 to
one U.S. Dollar level from January to the end of May.
</P>
<P>
The currency devalued about 2.2 percent in 1997 from the 5.3
percent level in 1996.
</P>
<P>
The official exchange rate and that on the free market have
been almost the same with a difference of only about 1.7 percent.
</P>
<P>
Mozambique began using its own currency in 1980 after it won
its independence from Portugal.
</P>
<P>
The new currency Metical, though used along with the Portugal
issued Escudo, saw a dramatic devaluation from 450 to one Dollar
in 1988 to 8252 to one Dollar in May 1995.
</P>
<P>
The latest stability of the currency is said to be a result
of the low inflation rate which has been kept at 0.5 percent
from January to May this year.
</P>
<P>
The country's inflation rate was 5.8 percent in 1997 and 16.3
percent in 1996. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
