<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Technological Cooperation Cements Sino-U.S. Ties (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 18 (Xinhua) -- Scientific and technological
cooperation has been acknowledged as one of the three pillars of
Sino-U.S. relations, along with cooperation in the commercial and
economic fields, according to a senior Chinese official.
</P>
<P>
Commenting during a recent exclusive interview with Xinhua, Zhu
Lilan, minister of Science and Technology, said the scientific and
technological cooperation program between China and the United
States has developed into one of the world's leading
intergovernmental programs thanks to "steady, far-reaching and
durable bilateral exchange mechanisms" established over the past
two decades.
</P>
<P>
Ministry statistics reveal that the two nations have dual-track
exchanges and carried out several thousand research
projects involving thousands of scientists since the first
Sino-U.S. Intergovernment Science and Technology Cooperation
Agreement was signed in 1979.
</P>
<P>
The Agreement has since served as the guiding document for
related activities and the new five-year tenure agreement ensures
bilateral cooperation well into the next century.
</P>
<P>
Relevant government departments from the two nations have
signed memoranda of understanding or protocols covering 32
areas, including agriculture, space, scientific information
exchange, environmental protection, seismology and high-energy
physics.
</P>
<P>
Zhu received her ministerial appointment last March during the
First Plenary Session of the the Ninth National People's Congress.
</P>
<P>
She also serves as the co-chairwoman of the Joint Sino-U.S. Science
and Technology Cooperation Committee. "The committee consists of
12 members from each country, including four to five officials at
the vice-ministerial level. We hold alternating biannual meetings
in the capitals of the two countries," said Zhu.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
