<HEADLINE> Science and Technology Cooperation Cement Sino-U.S. Ties (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Zhu described related efforts as "a large-scale program which
has yielded tangible results in wide-ranging fields." She noted
that "projects such as the electron-positron collider and
nationwide digital network for detecting and monitoring
earthquakes rank as world-class achievements".
</P>
<P>
Scientists from the two countries have focused on global issues
in wide-ranging areas such as the environment, energy, the
protection of endangered species and nuclear safety in recent
years.
</P>
<P>
The impetus and incentives provided by government departments,
semiofficial and nongovernmental institutions in the two
countries, including Chinese provinces and U.S. states, have
enabled institutions of higher education, laboratories and most
recently enterprises to engage in "fruitful" cooperation,
according to Zhu.
</P>
<P>
"Enormous potential remains to be tapped by the two sides,"
said Zhu. She expressed the hope that U.S. President Bill
Clinton's upcoming China visit will enable the countries to expand
consultations related to research and applications of space
technology needed for global studies.
</P>
<P>
She also expressed the hope that China and the United States
will implement programs on energy, the environment and the
peaceful use of nuclear energy as outlined in existing agreements,
in addition to enhancing cooperation in the pharmaceutical,
telecommunications and microelectronic sectors, as well as
bilateral nongovernmental exchanges.
</P>
<P>
She said that scientists from the two nations have successfully
cooperated in macro-science projects over the past 20 years and
noted that "cooperation can be expanded to more projects,
including controlled nuclear fusion and mapping human genes."
</P>
<P>
According to Zhu, "United States' Restrictions to technology
transfers have been a major barrier hindering both economic and
scientific and technological cooperation." She pointed out that
ensuring long-term scientific exchanges and engaging in common
efforts to solve problems in wider arenas should be accompanied by
removing barriers at the earliest possible date." 
</P>
</TEXT>
