<HEADLINE> SAARC Trade Negotiations Likely After 10th Summit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, June 18 (Xinhua) -- The final meeting of the third
round of trade talks under the SAARC Preferential Trading
Arrangement (SAPTA) may be held after the 10th summit of the South
Asian Association for Regional Cooperation (SAARC), an SAARC
official said.
</P>
<P>
As the SAARC member countries are concentrating their attention
on the 10th summit scheduled to be held in July in Colombo, Sri
Lanka, the final meeting of the third round of trade negotiations,
which should have ended in January, is likely to take place after
the summit, Director Tahir Iqbal Butt of the Kathmandu-based SAARC
Secretariat said on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The meeting should have been held from June 8 to 10 after
postponed for three times.
</P>
<P>
The second meeting of the SAARC commerce ministers held in late
April in Islamabad, Pakistan, decided that the member countries
would conclude the third round of trade negotiations on a priority
basis before the 10th summit.
</P>
<P>
The previous two rounds of trade negotiations under SAPTA
offered more than 2,000 items of products for tariff cuts ranging
from 10 to 50 percent.
</P>
<P>
At their ninth summit held in May 1997 in Male, the Maldives,
leaders from the seven SAARC member countries -- Bangladesh,
Bhutan, India, the Maldives, Nepal, Pakistan and Sri Lanka --
agreed that the third round should deepen tariff concessions along
with the removal of non-tariff barriers and structural impediments
in order to move speedily toward the goal of a South Asian Free
Trade Area preferably by the year 2001.
</P>
<P>
To this end, the third round has been adopting a combination of
product-by-product, sectoral and across-the-board approaches.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
