<HEADLINE> Yugoslav President Leaves Moscow </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, June 18 (Xinhua) -- Yugoslav President Slobodan
Milosevic, apparently happy with the result of his talks with his
Russian counterpart Boris Yeltsin, left Moscow for home Wednesday
night
</P>
<P>
During the talks with Yeltsin on Tuesday, Milosevic promised to
resume negotiations with leaders of ethnic Albanians in the Kosovo
region, the Itar-Tass news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The two sides also released a joint statement concerning
various issues in Kosovo, including possible forms of autonomy
for the area.
</P>
<P>
"The most important thing now is to persuade -- and this is our
common task -- primarily our Western partners and the leadership
of the Kosovo Albanians to resume talks immediately," said russian
Deputy Foreign Minister Nikolai Afanasyevsky, who is in charge of
liaisons with NATO.
</P>
<P>
He added that both Milosevic and Yeltsin have publicly
undertaken very serious obligations which must be fulfilled.
</P>
<P>
The deputy foreign minister noted that withdrawal of all police
forces now from Kosovo would mean giving the whole Kosovo
district to separatists and extremists.
</P>
<P>
"The Kosovo problem should be solved within Serbia and
Yugoslavia," he stressed. "Otherwise, it would lead directly to
secession and war."
</P>
<P>
Milosevic arrived in Moscow on Tuesday on a two-day visit.
</P>
</TEXT>
