<HEADLINE> Malaysia Announces Supplementary Budget </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, June 18 (Xinhua) -- Malaysia will set aside a
7.031- billion ringgit (about 1.793 billion U.S. dollars)
supplementary budget in an effort to generate a real GDP growth
higher than the negative 1.8 percent recorded during the first
quarter of the year.
</P>
<P>
The proposed measure was approved by the cabinet at its weekly
meeting Wednesday, Deputy Prime Minister Anwar Ibrahim, who is
also finance minister, announced here Thursday when simultaneously
opening the Umno (United Malays National Organization) Youth and
Woman annual assemblies.
</P>
<P>
Anwar, who is also Umno deputy president, said: "We have to
ensure that the government's supplementary spending will fully
bring about positive effects in generating national economic
growth and boosting the people's general well-being."
</P>
<P>
As such, Anwar said, it is imperative that implementation of
projects under the rehabilitative plan would not lead to an
outflow of national reserves or liquidity.
</P>
<P>
He said that toward this end efforts would be concentrated on
projects that could stimulate high demand for
domestically-produced goods and services within a short period of
time.
</P>
<P>
The focus would also be on projects capable of enhancing the
country's efficiency and competitive edge and of substituting
imports and boosting exports, among other things.
</P>
<P>
"The government will see to it that these projects be expedited
in the second half of 1998 and in 1999 to accelerate national
economic recovery," Anwar said.
</P>
<P>
They would include agriculture and low- and medium-cost housing
projects and expansion of skills training and tertiary
institutions.
</P>
<P>
Construction of clinics, bridges and roads especially for the
rural areas, water supply and infrastructure maintenance would
also be considered, he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
