<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Senate Kills Tobacco Bill </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 17 (Xinhua) -- Proposed legislation to curb
teenager smoking and bring nicotine under federal regulation died
in the Republican controlled Senate of the United States Congress
on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The American people "won't like what they see", said President
Bill Clinton.
</P>
<P>
Following a four-week struggle on the Senate floor, supporters
of the bill failed on two successive procedural votes to gain the
60 votes needed to keep the bill alive.
</P>
<P>
"If this bill goes down today, Joe Camel wins and our kids
lose," said Senator Tom Harkin, a Democrat and one of numerous
Democrats who have sought to end Republican blocking action on the
measure.
</P>
<P>
Moments after the final vote, Clinton said in the White House:
"If more members of the Senate would vote like parents rather than
politicians, we could solve this problem and go onto other
business of the country."
</P>
<P>
A number of Democrats vowed to force the issue back onto the
Senate floor before the mid-term elections, and accused
Republicans of merely doing the bidding of Big Tobacco.
</P>
<P>
Majority Leader Trent Lott of Mississippi spoke for Republicans
who argued that the measure had become a big government "tax and
spend" bill. "We've lost sight of the original noble cause of just
dealing with teen-age smoking and drug abuse," he said.
</P>
<P>
Clinton and the public health groups had sought to give the
government the power to regulate nicotine and take other steps to
rein in the tobacco industry.
</P>
<P>
House Speaker Newt Gingrich, a Republican, said he would try to
revive some form of tobacco legislation, but only a bill "that is
narrowly focused on teen smoking."
</P>
<P>
"Our goal is to reduce teen smoking, not increase taxes," said
Gingrich in a statement.
</P>
<P>
The development was regarded as a remarkable triumph for the
tobacco industry which spent tens of millions of dollars on an
advertising campaign to oppose the bill.
</P>
<P>
Shortly before Wednesday's vote, Clinton appealed for action to
"protect the children and not the tobacco lobby".
</P>
<P>
Of the killing of the legislation, he said: "There can be no
possible explanation other than the intense pressure and the
awesome influence fueled by years of huge contributions of Big
Tobacco," he said.
</P>
<P>
Rejection of the bill is likely to set in motion an
unpredictable chain of political and legal events.
</P>
<P>
Democrats are expected to raise the issue this fall against
Republicans, while tobacco companies would be open to a fresh
round of lawsuits. Left unclear would be the fate of the huge
settlement that several states reached with the tobacco industry
last summer to end their lawsuits.
</P>
<P>
That agreement sparked the drive to write legislation in the
Senate, but election-year politics and other forces swiftly
intruded.
</P>
<P>
Tobacco companies walked away from the bill when it was
expanded beyond what they had agreed on with the states.
</P>
<P>
A proposal to grant limited liability protection to the tobacco
companies was stripped from the bill on the Senate floor as
lawmakers sought a way to show voters they were willing to be
tough on an industry that markets its products to teen-agers.
</P>
<P>
Clinton and Democrats, backed by public health groups, sought
to frame the debate as a question of choosing children over
cigarette makers.
</P>
<P>
"Three thousand kids a day will take up smoking," Senator Tom
Harkin, a Democrat, said. "One thousand of them will die
prematurely."
</P>
<P>
Republicans said the truth was different, that they, too, favor
cracking down on teen smoking, but that the bill had gotten out of
hand. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980618.0260 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Italy Calls for "High Profile" International Criminal Court </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, June 17 (Xinhua) -- The U.N. conference underway here to
create an International Criminal Court (ICC) must strive to set up
a "high profile" court, Italian Foreign Minister Lamberto Dini
told the delegates Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that the ICC must be "strong and independent" and
the prosecutor must have "the power to take initiatives" to
achieve a "credible and efficient" court.
</P>
<P>
Noting that Italy has proposed adding state aggression to the
list of crimes the ICC would handle, Dini said the court should
have "the power to intervene first hand" on behalf of "a
sovereignty which is above and beyond national interests."
</P>
<P>
He urged delegates to work for the "immediate signing of a
statute by all nations involved." Membership, he added, should be
as vast as possible because "the universality of a treaty of this
importance is measured by the number of nations adhering to it."
</P>
<P>
Dini said that a Red Cross proposal to give the ICC a police
force "seems like an excellent idea to me because it could bolster
the ICC's actions."
</P>
<P>
Also on Wednesday, U.S. Ambassador to the U.N. Bill Richardson
said the ICC should not become "a human rights ombudsman."
</P>
<P>
"We must not turn an international criminal court, or its
prosecutor, into a human rights ombudsman open to, and responsible
for responding to, any and all complaints from any source," he
said.
</P>
<P>
Richardson also said the proposal to grant ICC prosecutors
investigative autonomy was "unrealistic and unwise" and would, in
fact, weaken rather than reinforce the court.
</P>
<P>
He said the U.N. Security Council should play a key role in the
ICC "including in the process to start legal proceedings." The
U.S. is a permanent member of the Security Council.
</P>
<P>
Richardson noted the U.S. remains "cautiously optimistic" over
the outcome of the five-week U.N. conference which started Monday.
</P>
<P>
The ICC is designed to be an international criminal tribunal
where defendants will be individuals, whereas the existing
International Court of Justice at The Hague settles judicial
controversies between sovereign states.
</P>
<P>
The Dutch government Wednesday officially confirmed that The
Hague had been designated to host the ICC. The Dutch city is also
the seat of the International Court for War Crimes in the
former Yugoslavia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980618.0261 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Argentine President to Visit Britain </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUENOS AIRES, June 17 (Xinhua) -- Argentine President Carlos
Menem will visit Britain on October 27 to November 1. He is the
first Argentine president to visit Britain since 1982 when the two
countries were engaged in a war, the Argentine Foreign Ministry
announced Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
During his visit, Menem will meet with British Queen Elizabeth
II and Prime Minister Tony Blair. He will also attend a meeting of
British entrepreneurs in Birmingham on November 1.
</P>
<P>
Argentine Foreign Minister Guido di Tella said Wednesday that
Menem's visit is to help establish mutual trust between the two
nations, because mutual acceptance between them needs to be
improved.
</P>
<P>
The Argentine president's trip to Britain was initiated by
former British Prime Minister John Major in September 1995 when
the two governments signed an agreement in New York to jointly
explore the oil and gas resources off the Malvinas Islands.
</P>
<P>
Argentina and Britain severed their diplomatic relations in
1982 when they fought a war of sovereignty over the Malvinas
Islands; they resumed diplomatic ties in 1990.
</P>
<P>
In the past years, relations between Argentina and Britain have
improved, but the position of the two countries on the sovereignty
of the islands has not changed. The Argentine government has
reaffirmed sovereignty over the Malvinas Islands several times and
has expressed a willingness to negotiate with the British
government to seek a better resolution.  
</P>
</TEXT>
