<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Spokesman Defends China's Family Planning Policy (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 18 (Xinhua) -- A spokesman for the State Family
Planning Commission has criticized comments that Harry
Wu and others made recently about China's birth control policies
at a U.S. House of Representatives hearing, calling them a
distortion of the facts.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said that Wu and others vilified China in
their attack on its family planning policies with these so-called
facts they got from the city of Jinjiang in Fujian Province.
</P>
<P>
He said that their purpose was to mislead and deceive the
public and undermine the normal development of the relations
between China and the United States.
</P>
<P>
He said that China is a developing country with 1.2 billion
people and has chosen family planning as a means of keeping the
population from growing too fast and that this was the correct
choice.
</P>
<P>
He said that China has a limited amount of arable land,
relatively insufficient natural resources on a per-capita basis,
and uneven social and economic development and that it has added
13 million more people to its population annually in recent years.
</P>
<P>
It has less arable land than the United States, but has a
higher per unit grain yield than the world average. But, per
capita grain consumption in China is less than a fourth that of
the United States because China's population is five times that of
the United States.
</P>
<P>
Analysts estimate that if China had not pursued family planning
and had continued with its birth rate of the early 1970s, it would
have a population of more than 1.5 billion now and the
consequences would be disastrous, the spokesman said, so China had
every reason to practise family planning, an inevitable option
that any responsible government would have done.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980618.0263 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Spokesman Defends China's Family Planning Policy (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
China has a principle of following state guidance and people's
own wishes in family planning and objects to any coercive
measures. It has always emphasized education and the use of
contraception for people of child-bearing ages, he said.
</P>
<P>
It has dealt firmly with any encroachment upon people's
interests, he said, and has protected the legitimate rights and
interests of women of child-bearing age in the Administrative
Procedural Law enacted in 1991, the Compensation Law enacted in
1994, and the Criminal Law, which was amended in 1997.
</P>
<P>
He said that some family planning workers in Fujian Province,
for example, who infringed upon people's legitimate rights and
interests while doing their job in 1996 had been sentenced to more
than two years in jail.
</P>
<P>
Before they fled to the United States, Gao Xiaoduan and his
wife borrowed more than two million yuan from local credit co-ops
and villagers and have not paid the money back, the spokesman
said, calling their attack on China the result of base motives.
</P>
<P>
Gao Xiaoduan said that, with few exceptions, Chinese families
are allowed to have only one child, but, in fact, the spokesman
said, 25.68 percent of Chinese women of child-bearing age have
three or more children, 32.5 percent have two, 36.1 percent have
one child, and 5.68 percent have no child, according to the State
Statistics Bureau's 1995 study.
</P>
<P>
At the end of June, 1997, in Jinjiang city, Gao's hometown, the
ratio of the women of child-bearing age who had two or more
children is higher than the nation's average.
</P>
<P>
Gao claimed that women who were nine months pregnant were
forced to have an abortion and that fetuses were killed by a
lethal injection, but the State Family Planning Commission did an
investigation in Jinjiang and concluded that there were no such
cases at all.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980618.0264 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Spokesman Defends China's Family Planning Policy (3) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The spokesman said that Harry Wu had said that a man named Pan
in the village of Yingdun, Yonghe Town, Jinjiang City, had two
daughters and the local family planning office suspected his wife
of being pregnant with her third child, so they repeatedly took
Pan's father into custody for as long as four months. But, the
investigators found that Pan was Pan Rongsheng, whose wife is Wang
Lixuan. They married in 1990 and have two daughters and a son.
</P>
<P>
Wang said that during her pregnancy no one took any action
against her family, nor did they take her father-in-law into
custody, nor did they disturb her house.
</P>
<P>
Harry Wu also said that a man named Lin in the village of
Maping in Yonghe had a wife who was forced to have an abortion
because they had no birth permit or quota. But the investigators
found that the couple Wu referred to were Lin Jiazhong and Yang
Meigui who got a marriage certificate in December of 1997. But
Yang discovered that she was pregnant before they were married and
thought that it was wrong, so she had an abortion in a hospital of
her own free will.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said that in pursuing the family planning policy,
the Chinese government resolutely opposes any form of coerced
abortion and the adoption of induced abortion as a means of family
planning.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese government emphasizes that abortions are merely a
means of dealing with contraception failures and must be done
under safe and reliable conditions with the consent of the people
concerned.
</P>
<P>
He said that the family planning program offers information,
consultation, and other services to people of childbearing age and
that there are no quotas and that the use of "birth permits" in
family planning in a few places before the 1990s was changed long
ago.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980618.0265 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Spokesman Defends China's Family Planning Policy (4) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The family planning policy accords with the fundamental
interests of the Chinese nation, and internationally-recognized
principles on population growth, the spokesman stressed and
population growth still strains economic development, resources
utilization, and environmental protection in China, so China will
continue this policy.
</P>
<P>
It has also been written into the Constitution of the People's
Republic of China.
</P>
<P>
He said that carrying out the policy is difficult and
complicated because of regional and urban and rural differences,
but that governments at different levels will make every effort to
solve existing problems and shortcomings, and that, in fact, China
welcomes well-intentioned opinion and suggestions from the
international community and is willing to take them earnestly.
</P>
<P>
But, the Chinese government and the Chinese people resolutely
oppose vicious slander and attacks on the family planning policy
and interference in China's internal affairs.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese people respect the American people's views on
childbirth, he added, but the two countries have completely
different population problems because of different national
conditions, their economic and developmental levels, and historic
and cultural backgrounds, so China's measures on the issue of
population are understandably different from those of the United
States.
</P>
<P>
He said, "we sincerely hope that objective and fair-minded
people will be vigilant against those people who act on the issue
out of ulterior motives."
</P>
<P>
He said that because improved Sino-U.S. relations are in the
interest of Chinese people and American people, and conducive to
world peace and development. Enitem

nnnn
</P>
</TEXT>
