<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thirty Percent of Chinese Live in Cities, Towns </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 18 (Xinhua) -- A report published by the Chinese
Academy of Social Sciences today reveals that 30 percent of
Chinese people now live in cities and towns.
</P>
<P>
The report says that China's urbanization level is quite low --
equal to the world average in the 1950s, 7 percent behind the
average level of developing countries and 45 percent behind
developed countries.
</P>
<P>
The report points out that China is still a big agricultural
country, despite the quickening pace of industrialization in the
past decades.
</P>
<P>
However, the report forecast that in 2000 China's urbanization
level will reach the world's average in the 1970s, the 1990s level
in 2010, and catch up with other countries around 2020.
</P>
<P>
"Considering that China will bridge the 40-year gap in 20
years, the development is quite fast," said Tian Xueyuan, director
of the Population Institute of the academy.
</P>
<P>
China's urban population will increase by 4 percent annually
between 2000 and 2010, Tian said, and by 3 percent between 2010
and 2025.
</P>
<P>
Besides natural growth, migrants from the countryside will be a
major factor in China's urbanization process, he said. Around
2000, there will be 200 million surplus rural laborers in China,
Tian said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
