<HEADLINE> NBA Urged to Toughen Drug Policy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 17 (Xinhua) -- A group of Republican
congressmen urged the NBA league to adopt a zero-taerance drug
policy for its athletes here on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
In a letter to NBA commissioner David Stern, J. Dennis Hastert
wrote: "Specifically, we urge you to adopt a consisent, random
drug testing policy for marijuana and all other illegal drugs for
all players as well as tough penalties for violators."
</P>
<P>
"A drug-free team will be experienced by everyone in your
organization, including your fans," he added.
</P>
<P>
A copy of the letter also was sent to Billy Hunter, executive
director of the players' union.
</P>
<P>
NBA spokesman Chris Brienza siad league officials have received
the letter but declined to comment further.
</P>
<P>
According to current NBA rules, only rookies are subject to
random drug testing three times a year.
</P>
<P>
A player who takes a drug will be suspended with pay for the
first offense. The second time he is suspended without pay, and
the third time he is subject to a lifetime ban. 
</P>
</TEXT>
