<HEADLINE> Joyner-Kersee, Devers Allowed to Compete in USA Meet </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 17 (Xinhua) -- American superstars Jackie
Joyner-Kersee, Gail Devers and Mary Slaney were given green light
Wednesday to compete in the USA Track and Field Championships
despite without qualifying marks.
</P>
<P>
Joyner-Kersee, 36, who said this would be her final year of
career, was allowed to compete in the heptathlon in which she
holds the U.S. and world record of 7,291 points. She won the event
in the 1988 and 1992 Olympics and is the five-time national
champion.
</P>
<P>
The multi-talented athlete also will compete in the long jump
in the three-day championships beginning Friday in New Orleans.
She won the event gold medal in 1988 Olympics and owns the U.S.
national record.
</P>
<P>
Devers, 31, who has been plagued by injuries and illness, will
compete in the 100-meter hurdles in which she owns the U.S. record
of 12.46 seconds. She won the 1993 world gold medal but never got
an Olympic laural in that event. The two times Olympic gold
medalist for the 100 meters dare not to run face-to-face against
new American star Marione Jones, the fastest woman in the world
this year.
</P>
<P>
The 39-year-old Slaney, the U.S. record holder for four
distance events, will double in the championships, competing in
the 1,500 and 5,000 meters.
</P>
<P>
Apart from the big three stars, the women's competition will
feature 12 U.S. record holders in 20 events.
</P>
<P>
In the men's events, Michael Johnson won't run the 200 meters,
and Dan O'Brien declared to skip the decathlon. Shot putter Randy
Barnes and triple jumper Kenny Harrison also have decided to pull
out the competition. The men will have only nine national record
holders in 20 events. 
</P>
</TEXT>
