<HEADLINE> Xinhua World Economic News Summary at 0500 GMT, June 18 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA -- Bangladesh will receive 70 million U.S. dollars from
Japan as grant for its debt relief under an agreement, press
reports said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Japan would provide Bangladesh with a grant assistance of the
said amount with the intention of producing the same effect as
canceling an international debt, said the exchange of notes signed
 between the two sides in Dhaka Wednesday. (Bangladesh-Japan-Grant)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
QUITO -- The prices of Ecuadoran crude dropped from 11 to 7.1
dollars per barrel this month, the lowest level in recent years,
the state-owned company Petroecuador said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The company said the worldwide oversupply of oil continued and
Monday's petroleum prices were down to their lowest rate in the
past 12 years. (Ecuador-Oil Price)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
NEW YORK -- Crude futures posted their largest gain in months
Wednesday in New York after industry data showed a big decline in
U.S. inventories.
</P>
<P>
Crude saw heavy buying after the American Petroleum Institute's
reported late Tuesday that inventories unexpectedly fell by a big
margin. (New York-Crude Futures-Jump)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
LOS ANGELES -- Sales of personal computers through PC stores in
Asia increased dramatically in the first quarter of 1998,
according to the U.S. market research firm Dataquest Inc. based in
California.
</P>
<P>
Despite the significant slowdown in PC shipment growth in the
Asia-pacific region, first quarter 1998 PC shipments through the
region's PC stores increased by 53 percent over the same period
last year. (Asia-PC Sales)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
NEW YORK -- Stocks on Wall Street surged Wednesday on efforts
of the U.S. and Japanese governments to prop up the Japanese yen.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that the United States began to sell dollars to
support the slumping Japanese yen for the first time since
February 1992. Japan, meantime, pledged to accelerate efforts to
revive its economy. (New York-Stocks Higher)
</P>
