<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Yeltsin-Milosevic Agreement May Ease Kosovo Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, June 17 (Xinhua) -- Italian Prime Minister Romano Prodi
said Wednesday that some signs of improvement have appeared in the
Kosovo crisis but seeking a final solution still remained a
delicate business.
</P>
<P>
Prodi made the remark one day after a talk in Moscow between
Russian President Boris Yeltsin and Yugoslav President Slobodan
Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
In a joint statement issued Tuesday with Yeltsin, Milosevic
promised to resume dialogue with ethnic Albanians in Kosovo and to
end repressive action against civilians there.
</P>
<P>
But he refused to withdraw Yugoslav troops immediately from the
troubled province -- the key demand of the six-nation Contact
Group for ex-Yugoslavia, which groups Britain, France, Germany,
Italy, Russia and the United States.
</P>
<P>
Also on Wednesday, Italian Foreign Minister Lamberto Dini said
he believed the Yeltsin-Milosevic statement was an "important step
forward" towards re-opening dialogue between Belgrade and the
ethnic Albanian majority in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
"It must be steady and not sporadic," Dini said.
</P>
<P>
More than 300 people have been killed since tensions escalated
in Kosovo in early March. About 65,000 of the 1.8 million
population have fled their homes in Kosovo, where ethnic Albanians
account for 90 percent of the population. Separatist-minded
ethnic Albanians have been seeking independence from Yugoslavia
since 1981. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
