<HEADLINE> OSCE Chairman Voices Concern Over Kosovo Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
VIENNA, June 17 (Xinhua) -- The current chairman of the
Organization for Security and Cooperation in Europe, Poland's
Foreign Minister Bronislaw Geremek, said here Wednesday that
Yugoslavia's territorial integrity brooks no infringement.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a press conference, Geremek said that the conflict
in the troubled Kosovo province of Yugoslavia is a "test for
Europe."
</P>
<P>
He warned those "tension-makers" among ethnic Albanians that
Yugoslav territorial integrity brooks no infringement.
</P>
<P>
Geremek also said Belgrade should make it clear that it would
respect all criteria of democracy and human rights set by the OSCE
if it wants to be re-admitted to the organization.
</P>
<P>
Yugoslavia's OSCE membership was suspended in 1992 for its role
in the Bosnian war.
</P>
<P>
Geremek also stressed that the OSCE, the European Union and the
six-member Contact Group for ex-Yugoslavia should carry out better
coordination and speak in one and the same voice on the Kosovo
issue.
</P>
<P>
He said he placed great hopes on the planned mission by former
Spanish prime minister Felipe Gonzalez as the international
mediator in the Kosovo crisis.
</P>
<P>
Tension in Kosovo escalated in early March this year when four
policemen and 16 Albanians were killed in an armed conflict.
</P>
<P>
Separatist-minded ethnic Albanians have been seeking
independence from Yugoslavia since 1981. 
</P>
</TEXT>
