<HEADLINE> New Zealand Prime Minister Meets Tung Chee Hwa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, June 18 (Xinhua) -- New Zealand Prime Minister
Jenny Shipley met with visiting Chief Executive of China's Hong
Kong Special Administrative Region (SAR) Tung Chee Hwa in her
office here Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Shipley and Tung exchanged views on a wide range of matters,
including cooperation between New Zealand and Hong Kong within
the APEC, the Asian financial turmoil and bilateral trade issues.
</P>
<P>
Later, the chief executive also called on New Zealand Minister
of Foreign Affairs and Trade Don MaKinnon and Finance Minister
Bill Birch.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to the press after the meetings, Tung described the
discussions with the New Zealand leaders as "extremely useful".
</P>
<P>
He said Hong Kong and New Zealand have a very important
bilateral relationship. At present, 3,000 New Zealanders live in
Hong Kong, while tens of thousands of people from Hong Kong have
settled down in New Zealand in addition to thousands of Hong Kong
students studying in New Zealand.
</P>
<P>
The bilateral relationship, he pointed out, does not cover
only the areas of trade and investment. It also finds itself in
people to people relations.
</P>
<P>
He felt pleased with announcement by Shipley of visa waiver
arrangement for people from Hong Kong to visit New Zealand. He
believed this will be a great help for Hong Kong, coming
particularly soon after the return of Hong Kong to China.
</P>
<P>
Tung said in the talks with the New Zealand leaders, he also
had the opportunity to explain how well the Hong Kong people are
doing there to successfully implement the principle of "one
country, two systems".
</P>
<P>
Asked to comment on the rebound of the Japanese yen, he said
he is pleased with the rebound and hopes it will sustain.
</P>
<P>
Obviously, he noted, the stability of the yen will be
important for Hong Kong and every country around the world as
Japan is the second largest economy of the world.
</P>
<P>
On the impact of the Asian financial crisis, Tung said the
impact is serious and Asia cannot underestimate the difficulties
it caused. But the strength of Asia cannot be underestimated
either, as it has a flexible and hard-working labor force, the
willingness to accept new ideas, a very high savings rate and an
indomitable spirit to succeed, he added.
</P>
<P>
Tung Chee Hwa will fly back to Hong Kong from Auckland Friday
after attending a reception hosted by Chinese Ambassador to New
Zealand Chen Wenzhao here Thursday night. 
</P>
</TEXT>
