<HEADLINE> U.S. to Bridge Gap with Iran: Albright </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, June 17 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine
Albright said Wednesday that it is time to test the possibilities
for bridging the gap between the U.S. and Iran despite the fact
that the gap "remains wide."
</P>
<P>
"We are ready to explore further ways to build mutual
confidence and avoid misunderstanding," Albright said at an Asia
Society function in New York. She urged Iran to "consider
parallel steps."
</P>
<P>
Praising Iran for its efforts in bringing peace in Afghanistan,
its achievements in anti-drug combat and and its aid to Iraqi and
Afghan refugees, Albright said Iran would be welcome to make a
"constructive contribution" to world affairs.
</P>
<P>
Albright's remarks came amid the U.S. administration's latest
move to improve bilateral relationships, which include encouraging
cultural and academic exchanges.
</P>
<P>
"Obviously, two decades of mistrust cannot be erased
overnight," Albright noted, while accusing Iran of continuing its
"support for terrorism" and making efforts "to develop long-range
missiles and to acquire nuclear weapons."
</P>
<P>
The U.S. has adopted a policy of isolating Iran since the 1979
Iranian Revolution. 
</P>
