<HEADLINE> Thailand Eases Conditions for Foreign Shareholding </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, June 18 (Xinhua) -- The Thai government has approved a
plan to ease the conditions for foreign shareholding in
joint-ventures in Thailand, according to a government press
release received Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The cabinet has acknowledged the report submitted by the Board
of Investment (BOI) on easing the conditions, the release said.
</P>
<P>
The decision allows foreigners to enjoy a greater ratio of
shareholding in joint-ventures, especially in projects in the
investment promotion zones.
</P>
<P>
The move is expected to help boost liquidity and enable
investors to find more financial sources.
</P>
<P>
There were 48 requests for changing ratio of foreign
shareholding in the first quarter of 1998 and 21 requests in April
and May.
</P>
<P>
Given the growing demand, a total of 77 Thai corporations will
become alien companies with the majority of foreign shareholders.
</P>
<P>
The change of shareholding ratio was mostly found in such
sectors as automobiles, chemical products, paper and plastic,
electronics and electrical appliances, textiles, accessories and
toys, power plants, basic metal industry and agriculture.
</P>
<P>
Japan, Taiwan and the United States have the highest increase
in shareholding in joint-ventures in Thailand. 
</P>
</TEXT>
