<HEADLINE> Ukraine, Guinea Agree to Expand Bauxite Trade </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KIEV, June 17 (Xinhua) -- Ukraine and Guinea reached an
agreement here Wednesday to increase exports of bauxite to Ukraine.
</P>
<P>
The news was announced by Ukrainian President Leonid Kuchma
following his meeting with the visiting Guinean President Lansana
Conte, who arrived Tuesday on a three-day visit.
</P>
<P>
Kuchma said he also talked with his Guinean counterpart on
Ukrainian investment in Guinea's bauxite mining business which
would help accelerate the restructuring endeavor.
</P>
<P>
In 1997, the two countries signed a ten-year agreement on
Ukraine's annual purchase of two million tons of bauxite from
Guinea.
</P>
<P>
During their recent talks, both sides indicated their
willingness to expand the bauxite trade with a target of 40
million U.S. dollars compared to the current 28 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
The Ukrainian president also expressed an interest in joining
the effort to build a 600-700 kilometer railway in Guinea for the
transportation of minerals.
</P>
<P>
The Guinean president voiced his willingness to also cooperate
with Ukraine on building ships.
</P>
<P>
Last year, the two trade partners had a trade volume of 52
million dollars. 99.8 percent of Ukraine's imports were bauxite
and alumina from Guinea. Metallurgical products formed half of the
country's exports. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
