<BODY>
<HEADLINE> FTAA Trade Talks begin </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUENOS AIRES, June 17 (Xinhua) -- The first meeting of the
trade negotiation committee for the creation of the Free Trade
Area for the Americas (FTAA) began here on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Opening the meeting, Argentine Foreign Minister Guido di Tella
stated that trade is very important for the world and that the
countries of the continents should strengthen trade cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Delegates from 34 nations in the continent met to set the
agendas for nine working groups.
</P>
<P>
During the two-day meeting, the nine groups will discuss
competition policies, allowances, market access, investment,
services, government procurement, agriculture, dispute settlement,
intellectual property rights, subsidies, anti-dumping and
countervailing duties.
</P>
<P>
The meeting is presided over by the Canadian vice-minister of
international trade, Kathryn McCallion.
</P>
<P>
The date for the trade negotiations committee of the FTAA was
established at the trade ministers meeting held in San Jose, Costa
Rica in March and approved a month later at the summit of the
Americas in Santiago, Chile.
</P>
<P>
The negotiations aim to trigger the FTAA operations for the
year 2005, as proposed by the United Sates at the first summit of
the Americas which took place in Miami in September, 1994. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980618.0290 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> India to Explore Possibility of Dhaka Indo-Pak Summit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, June 18 (Xinhua) -- Indian Foreign Secretary K.
Raghunath is expected to visit Dhaka on June 29 to explore
Bangladesh's offer of hosting an Indo-Pak bilateral summit, The
Statesman said here Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Bangladesh Prime Minister Sheikh Hasina during her one-day
visit to India on June 16 had offered to facilitate the dialogue
process by hosting a summit between prime ministers of India and
Pakistan. While India has not yet accepted the offer of a venue
for the bilateral summit, the Indian government has expressed its
willingness to consider the possibility if the logistics of the
proposed summit work out to its satisfaction, the paper said.
</P>
<P>
At the moment, both India and Pakistan have got themselves into
a bind over the conflicting offers of dates and venue. India's
offer of talks in New Delhi on June 22 was met with a
counter-offer from Pakistan suggesting talks in Islamabad on June
20. Now, neither country is in a position to backtrack without
loss of face. In this context, a summit in Dhaka provides a
neutral alternative.
</P>
<P>
India's openness to the offer also stems from the fact that
facilitation by Bangladesh would be far more acceptable than
intervention by any Western power which would be perceived as a
coercive measure. While Sheikh Hasina's offer stems from her
regional ambitions, Bangladesh poses no threat to India's
self-esteem. The earlier trilateral summit of prime ministers of
Bangladesh, India and Pakistan in Dhaka in January this year has
also provided a precedent, enabling India to consider the
proposal, the paper further said.
</P>
<P>
Raghunath's visit on June 29 will follow Sheikh Hasina's
one-day visit to Pakistan on June 24. Pakistan has already
indicated its positive response to the proposal for a summit
between Pakistan and India in Dhaka, but a clearer picture of the
modalities is expected to emerge after Hasina's discussions with
Pakistan Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif, the paper added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
