<DOCNO> XIE19980618.0294 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> NATO Chief Urges Milosevic to Fulfill Promise for Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MADRID, June 17 (Xinhua) -- North Atlantic Treaty Organization
(NATO) Secretary General Javier Solana Wednesday urged Yugoslav
President Slobodan Milosevic to fulfill his pledge for talks with
ethnic Albanians in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
Solana warned that there would "really be big problems" if he
failed to do so.
</P>
<P>
In a telephone interview with Spain's Onda Cero Radio, Solana
said Milosevic made progress in agreeing to negotiate with
Kosovo's Albanians for a political solution to their autonomy
demand after he met Russian President Boris Yeltsin on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Solana pointed out, however, that Milosevic's promise "could be
an operation just meant to gain time" in order to avoid military
interference by western countries.
</P>
<P>
On Monday, more than 80 aircraft from 13 NATO members conducted
an exercise in the Balkans to put pressure on Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
The NATO chief said Milosevic had agreed to mediation of Kosovo
by former Spanish prime minister Felipe Gonzalez Marquez, as
proposed by the Organization for Security and Cooperation of
Europe.
</P>
<P>
Noting that Spain was with the European Union, NATO and the
United Nations on the Kosovo issue, he urged the international
community to prevent another Bosnia war in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
More than 300 people have been killed and about 6,500 made
homeless in Kosovo since early this year when separatist-minded
ethnic Albanians launched a violent independence movement. Ethnic
Albanians make up 90 percent of Kosovo's population. 
</P>
</TEXT>
