<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Shougang Moves Mill for Capital's Environment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 18 (Xinhua) -- The Shougang Corp plans to limit
output, sharply cut back on pollution emissions and move one of
its steel mills out of downtown Beijing, according to today's
China Daily.
</P>
<P>
One of the largest steel manufacturers in China, the 80-year-old
Shougang Corp, also known as Capital Iron and Steel Corp, has
decided to cap its steel output at eight million tons per year,
spokesman Huang An of the Beijing-based corporation said yesterday.
</P>
<P>
By doing so, the corporation will have to readjust its
development strategy from expanding its production capacity to
developing new products and improving quality to boost efficiency
while also boosting investment in new technologies.
</P>
<P>
The move is expected to improve the capital's
environment. Steel-making is considered a major pollutant.
</P>
<P>
In the meantime, the corporation has drafted a plan to invest a
total of 3.9 billion yuan (US$469.8 million) in environmental
protection projects during the Ninth Five-Year Plan period
(1996-2000).
</P>
<P>
Part of the money will be used to build a waste-water treatment
plant capable of processing 55 million tons of waste water
annually.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, a large-type production line for steel
residue processing will be built in the near future.
</P>
<P>
The largest among all the new initiatives is to remove its
special steel mill out of downtown Beijing and upgrade the
resettled mill. The special steel mill is a major pollutant, he
said.
</P>
<P>
The corporation expects to cut down its industrial dust
emission by 20 to 30 percent, and bring all its industrial
waste-gas and waste-water emission into compliance with State
standards by the year 2000. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
