<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thai Productivity, Competitiveness Low: Survey </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, June 18 (Xinhua) -- The average productivity of Thai
industrial and service sectors has been at an alarmingly low
level, the Bangkok Post Thursday quoted a study as saying.
</P>
<P>
Low productivity affected the competitiveness of Thai
industries and services in the world market, the study conducted
by Siam Productivity Co. (SPC), said.
</P>
<P>
The results of the study are based on field survey and
samplings of over 1,000 companies from a broad range of business
activities.
</P>
<P>
The rapid growth of the Thai economy over the past three
decades had affected local competitiveness, since local
entrepreneurs can always sell their goods whether they are good or
not, the study said.
</P>
<P>
"They (local entrepreneurs) are not interested in improving
production capacity and that has continued to depress their
competitiveness," Paritud Bhandubanyong, SPC executive director,
said.
</P>
<P>
SPC is an affiliate of American-based Productivity Inc., the
worldwide industrial consultant company.
</P>
<P>
Judging by five key indices, SPC found Thai industrial and
service sectors lack efficiency and their productivity are
dramatically low.
</P>
<P>
The five indices are: overall equipment efficiency index
measuring the readiness and efficiency of a company to meet the
requirements of customers: value-added time ratio index, measuring
the level of customer satisfaction: inventory cost index: defect
index, measuring the amount of waste on the production line: and
preparing index, measuring the warming up time before production.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980618.0305 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Experts Suggest Rebuilding of Yuanmingyuan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 18 (Xinhua) -- More than 100 Chinese experts on
cultural relics and historians suggested that the world-famous
imperial garden -- Yuanmingyuan (Garden of 10,000 Gardens) --
should be rebuilt.
</P>
<P>
The remarks came at a forum on Yuanmingyuan held here
yesterday.
</P>
<P>
Yuanmingyuan, built over a 150-year period from 1709-1859,
covers 330 hectares. It was burned and destroyed in October of
1860 by British and French forces and looted and burned again in
1900 when the Allied Eight Power Force came to Beijing.
</P>
<P>
According to the suggestions at the forum, the ruins of part of
the garden's buildings would be protected as they are to remind
people of the brutal acts of the invaders.
</P>
<P>
Other suggestions included rebuilding some of the garden's
buildings to reflect Chinese classical garden building arts,
establishing a Yuanmingyuan museum, making a study of
Yuanmingyuan, and establishing an academy to study Yuanmingyuan
and conduct cultural exchanges with foreign countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980618.0306 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Myanmar's Manufacturing Sector Grows 5.3 Percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, June 18 (Xinhua) -- Myanmar's processing and
manufacturing sector achieved a 5.3 percent growth in output value
in 1997-98 fiscal year ending March over the previous year,
according to the latest official statistics.
</P>
<P>
The growth of the sector was attributed to the extensive
participation of domestic and foreign private enterprises and
promotion of production of value-added goods, said a report on the
country's financial, economic and social conditions issued by the
Ministry of National Planning and Economic Development.
</P>
<P>
Of the main industrial goods, the production of rice mills in
the fiscal year reached 9.37 million tons; edible oil, 252,650
tons; sugar, 80,530 tons; cement, 530,000 tons; fertilizer,
250,000 tons; petrol oil, 469 million liters; and diesel oil,
907.8 million liters.
</P>
<P>
Measures were also taken for the development which included
liberalization of state-owned industrial enterprises in terms of
administration and finance, encouragement of setting up private
enterprises, extension of loans to them and establishment of
industrial zones with local and foreign private entrepreneurs.
</P>
<P>
The report said that 17 industrial zones have already been set
up and production of agricultural implement and other industrial
goods are underway.
</P>
<P>
According to the statistics, foreign investment in the
manufacturing sector had amounted to 1.43 billion U.S. dollars in
113 projects by March, the end of the 1997-98 fiscal year, rising
to the second position after oil and gas from the sixth in 1996
out of the total foreign investment of 7 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
The manufacturing sector has a total of 53,338 enterprises in
1997-98, of which 51,101 are private-run, 1,600 state-owned and
637 cooperative-operated, it stated.
</P>
<P>
The manufacturing sector also stood as the second largest
contributor to Myanmar's gross domestic product (GDP) after
agriculture, sharing 9.2 percent of the GDP in 1997-98 which grew
4.6 percent.
</P>
<P>
The export value of the processing and manufacturing sector was
173.6 million dollars in the previous fiscal year 1996-97, it
added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
