<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Workers Spend Less Time on Work, Household Chores </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 18 (Xinhua) -- A recent national survey shows
that the expanded use of household electrical appliances and
reform of the labor system have enabled Chinese workers to spend
less time on work and household chores.
</P>
<P>
The State Statistics Bureau survey shows that urban workers
worked an average five hours and 37 minutes daily during 1997,
compared to seven hours and 19 minutes in 1990. The reduction was
mainly due to the advent of the five-day work week.
</P>
<P>
The survey also showed that female workers spent three hours on
household chores each day in 1997, down from four hours and 23
minutes in 1990. Male workers, on the other hand, dedicated two
hours and 10 minutes to family duties, compared with an hour and
43 minutes in 1990. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980618.0310 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-18 </DATE_TIME>
