<HEADLINE> China Welcomes Japanese, U.S. Intervention in Yen </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 18 (Xinhua) -- China's central bank governor Dai
Xianglong expressed here this morning that China welcomes the move
taken by the Japanese and U.S. governments to intervene on the
currency markets to buy Japanese yen.
</P>
<P>
"We are glad to see that the exchange rate of the Japanese yen
is picking up," Dai said at the 4th Annual Meetings of the
Association of Development and Industrial Banks in Asia, which
started here this morning.
</P>
<P>
The yen was quoted at 135.70-75 to the U.S. dollar in early
trading in Tokyo today after Japan intervened on the currency
markets to buy yen. The US Federal Reserve also bought yen on
behalf of Tokyo, pushing the currency back from its heavy falls
in the past two weeks.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Dai reaffirmed that the Chinese yuan will not be
devalued. "It's unnecessary to do that," he said. 
</P>
