<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 0100GMT, June 18 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN -- Germany's rail authorities said Wednesday that a broken
wheel has been established as the clear cause for the country's
worst post-war train derailment which occurred earlier this month.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters in Bonn Wednesday, officials of the
German Railway company said preliminary investigations showed that
a broken metal wheel tire on the first carriage of the ICE train
had been the triggering cause for the whole derailment.
</P>
<P>
The faulty tire, probably the result of an internal fracture
caused by metal fatigue or material defect, broke about six
kilometers before the crash site and wedged in the undercarriage
of the car.
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- Stability in Asia, crime and drug smuggling,
nonproliferation and cooperation on environment and economy will
be high on the agenda of President Bill Clinton's trip to China,
said senior U.S. officials Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
At a White House background briefing just one week before the
visit, Presidential National Security Advisor Sandy Berger,
Treasury Secretary Robert Rubin and the president's special
assistant on economic policy, Gene Sperling, outlined a broad
agenda for the visit.
</P>
<P>
Clinton will start his trip next Thursday and his first stop
will be Xi'an, and then Beijing, Shanghai, Guilin and Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
Top on the agenda during the summit in Beijing between Clinton
and Chinese President Jiang Zemin will be the stability in Asia.
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- Lebanese Prime Minister Rafiq al-Hariri said
Wednesday that peace talks between Israel on the one side and
Lebanon and Syria on the other are expected to resume within
several weeks.
</P>
<P>
"I cannot give you details but I can say that I am confident
that something will happen in the next few weeks on the
Lebanese-Syrian track," the prime minister told a news conference.
</P>
<P>
Hariri declined to elaborate on what he expected but he linked
it to his prediction that agreement with Israel was possible in
three months, if Israel resumes negotiations where they left off.
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- The United States plans a new effort, funded by
Congress, to build up a political opposition to Iraq's President
Saddam Hussein, a senior U.S. official said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
"We will be launching an effort to help them organize and
coordinate their case against Saddam Hussein," Assistant Secretary
of State Martin Indyk told a group of journalists at the State
Department.
</P>
<P>
He said there were 73 opposition groups outside of Iraq and
"now we're going to get behind them and try to help them," he
said. "They represent an alternative vision for Iraq to Saddam
Hussein."
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- President Bill Clinton said Wednesday that he
would offer support to the Japanese yen after Japanese Prime
Minister Ryutaro Hashimoto had pledged "aggressive" financial
system reform and other economic steps.
</P>
<P>
"I was very encouraged by the prime minister's statement that
he intends to pursue aggressive reform of their banking
institutions and intends to do the things that were necessary to
get their economy going again," Clinton said in response to a
reporter's question during a White House Rose Garden appearance.
</P>
<P>
Clinton spoke to Hashimoto by telephone Tuesday night after
being briefed by top administration economic and national security
officials.
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
TEHRAN -- Iran's conservative Majlis Speaker Nateq Nouri was
urged on Wednesday to use his influence on the right
(conservative) faction to prevent political tensions "through
controlling its radical elements."
</P>
<P>
Making the call, Majid Ansari, chairman of the left-wing
Hezbollah Assembly at the Majlis, said that people such as Nouri
should move to prevent tensions between the left and right
factions.
</P>
<P>
The Iranian official news agency IRNA quoted Ansari as
criticizing the right faction for demanding the impeachment of the
moderate Interior Minister Abdollah Nouri, saying the motion was
not helpful to unity. 
</P>
