<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Old Passenger Lands Small Plane Following Pilot's Death </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 17 (Xinhua) -- An old passenger with no flying
experience landed a small airplane in Indiana on Wednesday with
the help of voices on the radio after the pilot died at the
controls, the Associated Press said.
</P>
<P>
Robert Kupferschmid, 81, and friend Wesley Sickle, 52, were
flying from Indianapolis to Muncie to have lunch when Sickle
suddenly slumped in his seat.
</P>
<P>
Kupferschmid grabbed the flight stick of the two-seat Cessna
and got on the radio, asking for help.
</P>
<P>
A nearby pilot, Mike Bowen, who was flying about 30 kilometers
away for a survey of gas lines, heard Kupferschmid's plea for help
and instructed the old man to fly and make an emergency landing at
Mount Comfort, the nearest airport.
</P>
<P>
Also with the help from another nearby pilot, Eddie Merchant,
Kupferschmid successfully landed with little damage to the plane
and no injury of himself. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
