<DOCNO> XIE19980618.0316 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Panamanian FM Rules Out Extending U.S. Military Presence </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PANAMA CITY, June 17 (Xinhua) -- Panamanian Foreign Minister
Ricardo Alberto Arias emphasized Wednesday that there will be no
United States military presence remaining in Panama after 2000.
</P>
<P>
Arias' clarification answered remarks by U.S. Senator Jesse
Helms that the United States should try to continue its military
presence in Panama, though Washington agreed in 1977 to withdraw
all military forces from Panama by December 31, 1999.
</P>
<P>
"This only reflects the personal opinion of Senator Helms and
not the position of the United States government," Arias said.
</P>
<P>
"Obviously, the position of Senator Helms is a very relevant
and important point of view in the United States, but it does not
reflect the majority of the North-American society," Arias said in
a press release.
</P>
<P>
On bilateral relations between the two countries, Arias
said: "We have a great deal in common, and we hope that our links
continue to be excellent after year 2000." 
</P>
</TEXT>
