achievements of Chinese lawyers, in Beijing's Museum of the
Chinese History, which is sponsored by the Ministry of Justice.
</P>
<P>
"Xinhua Daily Telegraph"
</P>
<P>
-- The Chinese government yesterday announced an ambitious
market-oriented housing reform plan aimed at providing better
dwellings for its urban residents.
</P>
<P>
The plan, declared at a national housing reform conference
which closed in Beijing yesterday, will end the long-practiced
welfare housing distribution system for government officials and
employees of state enterprises.
</P>
<P>
-- Vice-premier Li Lanqing told the 16th meeting of the State
Council's Academic Degree Committee yesterday that graduate
studies play an indispensable role in revitalizing the nation
through science and education.
</P>
<P>
Li, who is the Committee's chairman, said that China's economic
structure and its growth pattern mean that society relies more on
people with higher academic degrees, especially in technology.
</P>
<P>
"China Daily"
</P>
<P>
-- China is well-prepared to bail out most of its loss-ridden
State-owned enterprises before the end of this century.
</P>
<P>
While continuing to seek breakthroughs in the textile industry,
the government will support other struggling sectors such as the
coal and defence industries, said a circular issued by the State
Economic and Trade Commission.
</P>
<P>
-- Although the slump in the value of the yen is putting
unprecedented pressure on exports, China will stick firmly to its
promise not to devaluate the renminbi, a senior trade official
said yesterday.  
</P>
