<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Broken Wheel Set as Cause for German Train Derailment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, June 17 (Xinhua) -- Germany's rail authorities said
Wednesday that a broken wheel has been established as the clear
cause for the country's worst post-war train derailment which
occurred earlier this month.
</P>
<P>
The Inter-City Express (ICE), Germany's fastest train with a
top speed of 280 kilometers an hour, jumped the tracks near the
northern German town of Eschede on June 3 and crashed into a
nearby road bridge, killing 100 people and injuring another 88
passengers.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters in Bonn Wednesday, officials of the
German Railway company said preliminary investigations showed that
a broken metal wheel tire on the first carriage of the ICE train
had been the triggering cause for the whole derailment.
</P>
<P>
The faulty tire, probably the result of an internal fracture
caused by metal fatigue or material defect, broke about six
kilometers before the crash site and wedged in the undercarriage
of the car.
</P>
<P>
The train then traveled on about 5.5 kilometers on the tracks
before the broken tire hit a switch mechanism on the rail lines,
jerking the wheel off the track and derailing the carriage along
with all the following ones.
</P>
<P>
German Transport Minister Matthias Wissmann said that it would
still take several months before the explanation could be formally
confirmed.
</P>
<P>
As a precaution, the German rail authorities had already
withdrawn all 59 ICE trains of the same generation of the
ill-fated train and equipped them with new wheels.
</P>
<P>
The accident, however, has considerably undermined the public
trust in the high-speed trains which had had a perfect safety
record since entering into service in 1991. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980618.0336 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> IFC Launches Estonian Kroon Global Medium-Term </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 17 (Xinhua) -- The International Finance
Corporation (IFC) Wednesday announced its debut into the Estonian
market with the launch of an Estonian kroon 100 million Eurobond
issue, which is equivalent to 6.9 million U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
The three-year notes carry an annual coupon of 10.00 percent,
and were issued at a price of 101.35 percent of the par. The
proceeds of the issue were swapped into U.S. dollar floating rate
funds.
</P>
<P>
This issue is part of the IFC's goal of contributing to the
development of new capital markets. The IFC is a member of the
World Bank Group, and also the largest multilateral source for
financing private sector projects in developing countries.
</P>
<P>
This transaction under the IFC's Global Medium Term Note
Program brings the IFC's market borrowing to some 3,973 million
dollars for the fiscal year 1998, which began on July 1, 1997.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
