<BODY>
<HEADLINE> IDB Assists Project to Improve Housing Conditions </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 17 (Xinhua) -- The Inter-American Development
Bank (IDB) Wednesday announced the approval of a 60 million U.S.
dollar soft loan to Bolivia to improve housing conditions,
particularly for low-income groups.
</P>
<P>
The financing will enable the government to carry out a housing
policy aimed at making the real estate and housing finance markets
more efficient, enabling more funds to be channeled into the
sector and reducing the cost of housing.
</P>
<P>
Most of the resources for the program will consist of grants to
municipalities for upgrading low-income neighborhoods in cities
throughout the country, primarily through investments in basic
services.
</P>
<P>
Municipalities will compete for the grants by offering more
counterpart funding for the projects. The municipalities will also
take steps to modernize their land registers and property tax
systems, revise urban legislation to make it more effective, take
steps to legalize land tenure in informal settlements and provide
city sanitation services and road and draining maintenance in
beneficiary areas.
</P>
<P>
The total cost of the program is some 71 million dollars. Apart
from the IDB loan, local counterpart funds some 11 million
dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
