<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Outlines Agenda for Clinton's China Trip </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 17 (Xinhua) -- Stability in Asia, crime and
drug smuggling, nonproliferation and cooperation on environment
and economy will be high on the agenda of President Bill Clinton's
trip to China, said senior U.S. officials Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
At a White House background briefing just one week before the
visit, Presidential National Security Advisor Sandy Berger,
Treasury Secretary Robert Rubin and the president's special
assistant on economic policy, Gene Sperling, outlined a broad
agenda for the visit.
</P>
<P>
Clinton will start his trip next Thursday and his first stop
will be Xi'an, and then Beijing, Shanghai, Guilin and Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
Top on the agenda during the summit in Beijing between Clinton
and Chinese President Jiang Zemin will be the stability in Asia.
</P>
<P>
Berger noted that China has played a "constructive role" in
forging a consensus among the five permanent members of the U.N.
Security Council on the nuclear tests by India and Pakistan on the
steps that they must take to move towards a situation of less
tension.
</P>
<P>
"We will be working with the Chinese to try to encourage both
the Pakistanis and the Indians to take those steps," he added.
</P>
<P>
On nonproliferation of weapons, Berger said "there's been quite
remarkable progress" in this area in the past five years. He hoped
that more progress is to be made.
</P>
<P>
On economy, Rubin said, "The United States has an enormous
stake in the economic well-being of China."
</P>
<P>
His remarks were echoed by Sperling. "We feel it is strongly in
our national interest to bring China into the global trading
system," he said.
</P>
<P>
The American and Chinese officials will continue the
discussions that they have had about the state-owned enterprises,
the reform of that system, the issues around the financial sector
and the challenges in the banking sector, said Rubin.
</P>
<P>
Both Berger and Rubin praised China for its "absolutely
critical role" in maintaining the currency rate in helping
stabilize the financial market in Asia.
</P>
<P>
However, Clinton "will press during the meeting for China to
open its markets for goods, service and agriculture as it engages
in the sweeping economic reforms," said Sperling.
</P>
<P>
On crime and drug trafficking, Berger said that "it has been an
area of growing cooperation" between China and the United States.
</P>
<P>
Berger reiterated that the United States has a fundamental
interest in engagement with China.
</P>
<P>
One of the administration's fundamental strategic objectives is
to "build a strong bridge to Asia" and "in particular, to put the
U.S.-China relationship on a more solid footing," he said.
</P>
<P>
"The reason for that is because the direction China takes over
the next 10 or 20 years will fundamentally and profoundly affect
our interests, our children's future, stability in Asia, peace in
the world," Berger told reporters.
</P>
<P>
"Engagement is a vehicle, is a means to both expand the areas
of our cooperation and to deal with the Chinese directly, face to
face, about areas of difference," he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980618.0339 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Study: Toys on Greek Market Contain Toxic Substances </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, June 17 (Xinhua) -- Children's toys on the Greek market
contained high levels of toxic substances which could cause
serious damage to children's livers and kidneys, according to a
study carried out by the Greek branch of the environmental
protection organization Greenpeace.
</P>
<P>
The Greenpeace selected random samples of toys made from soft
PVC and sent them for analysis to an independent laboratory in
Germany. The results showed that the toys contained levels of
toxic phthalic compounds ranging from 20 to 50 percent.
</P>
<P>
In Athens, the Greenpeace members Wednesday demonstrated
outside the Greek Health Ministry to demand the withdrawal of the
toys from the markets. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
