<DOCNO> XIE19980618.0340 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Crude Futures Up, Sharp Decline in Crude Stocks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, June 17 (Xinhua) -- Crude futures posted their
largest gain in months Wednesday in New York after industry data
showed a big decline in U.S. inventories.
</P>
<P>
Crude saw heavy buying after the American Petroleum Institute's
reported late Tuesday that inventories unexpectedly fell by a big
margin.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. Energy Department also reported Wednesday a sharp
decline in crude stocks.
</P>
<P>
At the closing of the market, crude for July delivery rose 62
cents to 12.60 U.S. dollars a barrel; July unleaded gasoline rose
0.58 cent to 46.51 cents a gallon; July heating oil rose 0.35 cent
to 37.32 cents a gallon.
</P>
<P>
But analysts still doubted if oil producers who pledged in
March to cut a total 1.72 million barrels a day from the market
actually met that target.
</P>
<P>
And there is concern that Iraq will soon be able to freely
export oil without having to get the permission of the United
Nations.
</P>
<P>
Futures prices also advanced after the U.S. government stepped
in to support the Japanese yen by selling U.S. dollars.
</P>
</TEXT>
