<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Asia-Pacific PC Sales Shift to Stores: Dataquest </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, June 17 (Xinhua) -- Sales of personal computers
through PC stores in Asia increased dramatically in the first
quarter of 1998, according to the U.S. market research firm
Dataquest Inc. based in California.
</P>
<P>
Despite the significant slowdown in PC shipment growth in the
Asia-pacific region, first quarter 1998 PC shipments through the
region's PC stores increased by 53 percent over the same period
last year.
</P>
<P>
PC shipments through PC stores were just below 496,000 units
for the first three months of 1998.
</P>
<P>
One of the market pressures resulting from the regional
economic crisis is the overall demand shift to a higher proportion
of lower-end systems. The home and small business sectors have
registered slightly higher demand growth than other end-user
segments.
</P>
<P>
Dataquest said that China is the leading contributor to the
growth in PC retail shipments in the region, with an 88 percent
increase in home market PC volume over the first quarter of 1997.
China accounted for 28 percent of the first quarter 1998 PC volume
through PC stores in Asia-Pacific.
</P>
<P>
The strong growth in regional demand for PCs from PC store
retailers is a direct reflection of the degree of home and small
office consumption in the markets like China, Dataquest said.
</P>
<P>
In another report, Dataquest said that the fast-growing Chinese
video compact disc (VCD) player production market is projected to
reach 14.5 million units in 1998, sustaining a 26 percent growth.
</P>
<P>
China's VCD-player demand will surge 17.4 percent on an annual
basis to reach 13.5 million units in 1998 and another 5.1 percent
in 1999 to 14.2 million units. The growth trend will decline in
2000 when digital video/versatile disc (DVD) players are projected
to dominate, according to Dataquest. 
</P>
</TEXT>
