<HEADLINE> Lebanese Leader Expects Resumption of Talks With Israel </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 17 (Xinhua) -- Lebanese Prime Minister Rafiq
al-Hariri said Wednesday that peace talks between Israel on the
one side and Lebanon and Syria on the other are expected to resume
within several weeks.
</P>
<P>
"I cannot give you details but I can say that I am confident
that something will happen in the next few weeks on the
Lebanese-Syrian track," the prime minister told a news conference.
</P>
<P>
"Maybe we'll see the Americans moving towards something on the
Lebanese-Syrian track. Let's wait and see because there are steps
based on many things that may happen before," he added.
</P>
<P>
Hariri declined to elaborate on what he expected but he linked
it to his prediction that agreement with Israel was possible in
three months, if Israel resumes negotiations where they left off.
</P>
<P>
He made the prediction Tuesday after his meeting with President
Bill Clinton and Secretary of State Madeleine Albright in
Washington. Israel responded Wednesday by insisting that
negotiations should be "unconditional" -- a word Hariri
interpreted as meaning Israel wants to start the talks from
scratch.
</P>
<P>
"As for the Syrians and the Lebanese, we are ready to fulfill
an agreement in three months' time if Israel continues the
negotiations. Everyone was interested in what we said yesterday. I
believe that something might move very quickly," Hariri said.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister repeated Labanon's dismissal of Israel's
offer to withdraw from south Lebanon if the Lebanese government
gives it some security guarantees.
</P>
<P>
Lebanon says the U.N. Security Council has already demanded an
unconditional Israeli withdrawal and that Israel is in no position
to set conditions.
</P>
<P>
"Either Israel withdraws from our territory unconditionally,
or, if Israel wants to have a different relationship that the one
we have now, it has to continue the peace process and we are ready
for that also," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
